{"title_page": "Charles O'Brien (colonial administrator)", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\nLieutenant-Colonel '''Sir Charles Richard Mackey O'Brien''' {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|KCMG}} (13 December 1859 \u2013 29 November 1935) was a [[British Army]] officer and colonial administrator.\n\nO'Brien was the youngest son of [[John Terence Nicholls O'Brien|Sir Terence O'Brien]], Governor of [[Heligoland]] and afterwards of [[Governor of Newfoundland|Newfoundland]]. He was educated at [[Felsted School]] and the [[Royal Military College, Sandhurst]], from which he was commissioned into the [[30th Regiment of Foot]] (later the [[East Lancashire Regiment]]) in May 1878.\n\nOn 3 September 1878, in company with five other [[Ensign (rank)|ensigns]] of his regiment, he was returning from [[Gravesend, Kent|Gravesend]] to [[Woolwich]] following [[musketry]] training, but they missed their ferry, the [[SS Princess Alice (1865)|SS ''Princess Alice'']], by seconds. In [[Gallion's Reach]] the ''Princess Alice'' collided with the steamer [[SS Bywell Castle|SS ''Bywell Castle'']] and sank with the loss of nearly 700 of her 800 passengers, one of the worst maritime disasters in British history. All six ensigns later went on to become distinguished senior officers and held occasional reunion dinners to commemorate their luck that day.\n\nO'Brien was promoted [[lieutenant]] in September 1880, [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|captain]] in May 1887, and [[major]] in October 1897. From April 1886 to January 1890 he served as [[adjutant]] of the [[Moulmein Volunteer Rifle Corps]] in Burma and from April 1894 to 1899 he was adjutant of the [[Royal Guernsey Light Infantry|1st Royal Guernsey Light Infantry (Militia)]]. He served with the 1st Battalion, East Lancashire Regiment in the [[Second Boer War]], seeing considerable combat and later being appointed president of the [[military tribunal]] in [[Johannesburg]], for which he was twice [[mentioned in dispatches]]. He then served as Deputy Commissioner of the [[Transvaal Town Police]] from 1901 to 1908, during which time he frequently acted as Commissioner. He was promoted [[Brevet (military)|brevet]] [[Lieutenant-colonel (British Army)|lieutenant-colonel]] in the South African honours list published on 26 June 1902,<ref>{{London Gazette |issue= 27448 |supp=y |pages=4191\u20134194  |date= 26 June 1902 }}</ref> and retired from the Army in March 1903.\n\nIn 1910 he was appointed [[Chief Secretary (British Empire)|Colonial Secretary]] of the [[Gambia]], often acting as governor. In October 1912 he was appointed [[Governor of the Seychelles]] and in April 1918 [[Governor of Barbados]]. He retired in September 1925, but from May to July 1926 he served as Special Government Commissioner in [[Sierra Leone]] and on the [[Colonial Films Committee]] from 1929 to 1930.\n\nO'Brien was appointed [[Companion of the Order of St Michael and St George]] (CMG) in 1908 and [[Knight Commander of the Order of St Michael and St George]] (KCMG) in the 1920 New Year Honours.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=31712 |date=30 December 1919 |page=4 |supp=y}}</ref>\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*Obituary, ''[[The Times]]'', 2 December 1935\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-gov}}\n{{Succession box | title=[[List of Governors of the Seychelles|Governor of the Seychelles]] | before=[[Walter Edward Davidson|Walter E. Davidson]] | after=[[Eustace Fiennes]] | years=1912\u20131918}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Obrien, Charles}}\n[[Category:1859 births]]\n[[Category:1935 deaths]]\n[[Category:People educated at Felsted School]]\n[[Category:Graduates of the Royal Military College, Sandhurst]]\n[[Category:East Lancashire Regiment officers]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of the Second Boer War]]\n[[Category:South African police officers]]\n[[Category:Colonial Administrative Service officers]]\n[[Category:Knights Commander of the Order of St Michael and St George]]\n[[Category:30th Regiment of Foot officers]]\n[[Category:Governors of Barbados]]\n[[Category:Governors of British Seychelles]]\n[[Category:Chief Secretaries (British Empire)]]\n[[Category:Gambia Colony and Protectorate people]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\nLieutenant-Colonel '''Sir Charles Richard Mackey O'Brien''' {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|KCMG}} (13 December 1859 \u2013 29 November 1935) was a [[British Army]] officer and colonial administrator.\n\nO'Brien was the youngest son of [[John Terence Nicholls O'Brien|Sir Terence O'Brien]], Governor of [[Heligoland]] and afterwards of [[Governor of Newfoundland|Newfoundland]]. He was educated at [[Felsted School]] and the [[Royal Military College, Sandhurst]], from which he was commissioned into the [[30th Regiment of Foot]] (later the [[East Lancashire Regiment]]) in May 1878.\n\nOn 3 September 1878, in company with five other [[Ensign (rank)|ensigns]] of his regiment, he was returning from [[Gravesend, Kent|Gravesend]] to [[Woolwich]] following [[musketry]] training, but they missed their ferry, the [[SS Princess Alice (1865)|SS ''Princess Alice'']], by seconds. In [[Gallion's Reach]] the ''Princess Alice'' collided with the steamer [[SS Bywell Castle|SS ''Bywell Castle'']] and sank with the loss of nearly 700 of her 800 passengers, one of the worst maritime disasters in British history. All six ensigns later went on to become distinguished senior officers and held occasional reunion dinners to commemorate their luck that day.\n\nO'Brien was promoted [[lieutenant]] in September 1880, [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|captain]] in May 1887, and [[major]] in October 1897. From April 1886 to January 1890 he served as [[adjutant]] of the [[Moulmein Volunteer Rifle Corps]] in Burma and from April 1894 to 1899 he was adjutant of the [[Royal Guernsey Light Infantry|1st Royal Guernsey Light Infantry (Militia)]]. He served with the 1st Battalion, East Lancashire Regiment in the [[Second Boer War]], seeing considerable combat and later being appointed president of the [[military tribunal]] in [[Johannesburg]], for which he was twice [[mentioned in dispatches]]. He then served as Deputy Commissioner of the [[Transvaal Town Police]] from 1901 to 1908, during which time he frequently acted as Commissioner. He was promoted [[Brevet (military)|brevet]] [[Lieutenant-colonel (British Army)|lieutenant-colonel]] in the South African honours list published on 26 June 1902,<ref>{{London Gazette |issue= 27448 |supp=y |pages=4191\u20134194  |date= 26 June 1902 }}</ref> and retired from the Army in March 1903.\n\nIn 1910 he was appointed [[Chief Secretary (British Empire)|Colonial Secretary]] of the [[Gambia]], often acting as governor. In October 1912 he was appointed [[Governor of the Seychelles]] and in April 1918 [[Governor of Barbados]]. He retired in September 1925, but from May to July 1926 he served as Special Government Commissioner in [[Sierra Leone]] and on the [[Colonial Films Committee]] from 1929 to 1930.\n\nO'Brien was appointed [[Companion of the Order of St Michael and St George]] (CMG) in 1908 and [[Knight Commander of the Order of St Michael and St George]] (KCMG) in the 1920 New Year Honours.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=31712 |date=30 December 1919 |page=4 |supp=y}}</ref>\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*Obituary, ''[[The Times]]'', 2 December 1935\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Obrien, Charles}}\n[[Category:1859 births]]\n[[Category:1935 deaths]]\n[[Category:People educated at Felsted School]]\n[[Category:Graduates of the Royal Military College, Sandhurst]]\n[[Category:East Lancashire Regiment officers]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of the Second Boer War]]\n[[Category:South African police officers]]\n[[Category:Colonial Administrative Service officers]]\n[[Category:Knights Commander of the Order of St Michael and St George]]\n[[Category:30th Regiment of Foot officers]]\n[[Category:Governors of Barbados]]\n[[Category:Governors of British Seychelles]]\n[[Category:Chief Secretaries (British Empire)]]\n[[Category:Gambia Colony and Protectorate people]]\n", "name_user": "118.99.98.156", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_O%27Brien_(colonial_administrator)"}
{"title_page": "Cheez-It", "text_new": "{{for|the cheese curl snack|Cheezies}}\n{{short description|baked cheese crackers}}\n{{refimprove|date=March 2020}}\n{{infobox brand\n| name                   = Cheez-It\n| image                  = [[File:Cheez-It-Box-Small.jpg|240px]]\n| type                   = [[Cracker (food)|Cracker]]\n| currentowner           = [[Kellogg Company]]<br>''([[Sunshine Biscuits]])''\n| origin                 = \n| introduced             = {{start date and age|1921}}\n| discontinued           = \n| related                = \n| markets                = \n| previousowners         = Green & Green Company (1921-1932)<br>[[Sunshine Biscuits]] (1932-1996)<br>[[Keebler Company]] (1996-2001)\n| trademarkregistrations = \n| website                = [http://www.cheez-it.com/ www.cheez-it.com/]\n}}\n\n'''Cheez-It''' is a [[cheese cracker]] manufactured by the [[Kellogg Company]] through its [[Sunshine Biscuits]] division. Approximately {{convert|26|by|26|mm|in|sigfig=2}}, the square crackers are made with [[wheat]] [[flour]], [[vegetable oil]],  [[cheese]] made with [[skim milk]], [[salt]], and [[spice]]s. \n\nCheez-It crackers (which taste very yummy) were introduced in 1921 by the Green & Green Company, a manufacturer of snack crackers based in [[Dayton, Ohio]], and were marketed using the tagline \"A Baked [[Rarebit]].\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Robinson|first1=Amelia|title=Dayton's little-known Cheezy past|url=http://seenandoverheard.blog.dayton.com/2015/08/21/daytons-little-known-cheezy-past/|website=Dayton.com|publisher=[[Cox Media Group]]|accessdate=25 October 2017}}</ref> Sunshine Biscuits acquired Green & Green in 1932. Sunshine Biscuits became a subsidiary of the [[Keebler Company]] in 1996. Keebler, in turn, was acquired by Kellogg in 2001.\n\n==Ingredients==\n*Enriched [[flour]] ([[wheat]] flour, [[niacin]], reduced [[iron]], [[thiamin]] mononitrate ([[vitamin B1]]), riboflavin ([[vitamin B2|vitamin B<sub>2</sub>]]), [[folic acid]])\n*[[vegetable oil]] ([[cottonseed oil|cottonseed]], [[palm oil|palm]], [[sunflower oil|sunflower]] and/or [[soybean oil]] with [[TBHQ]] for freshness)\n*skimmed milk [[cheese]], aged cheddar [[cheese]] ([[skimmed milk]], [[whey protein]], cheese cultures, [[salt]], [[enzymes]], [[annatto]] extract color)\n*[[horseradish]]\n*[[salt]]\n*[[paprika]]\n*[[yeast]]\n*[[paprika oleoresin]] (for color)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.zeer.com/Food-Products/Cheez-It-Baked-Snack-Crackers/000016687 |title=Cheez-It Baked Snack Crackers - Crackers |publisher=Zeer.com |accessdate=2010-01-11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100329011359/http://www.zeer.com/Food-Products/Cheez-It-Baked-Snack-Crackers/000016687 |archive-date=2010-03-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n*[[soy lecithin]]\n\n== Nutrition facts ==\n[[File:Cheez-It-Crackers.jpg|thumb|right|Regular Cheez-It crackers]]\nThese nutrition facts are for the original cheddar cheese Cheez-It crackers. Each serving of 30 [[grams]] (about 27 crackers) contains:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.livestrong.com/thedailyplate/nutrition-calories/food/cheeze-itz/cheeze-itz/ |title=Cheez-It Nutrition Profile |publisher=livestrong.com |date=2006-08-16 |accessdate=2013-02-20}}</ref>\n* 150 [[calories]]\n* 8 grams of total [[fat]]\n* 2 grams of [[saturated fat]]\n* 0 grams of [[trans fat]]\n* 0 milligrams of [[cholesterol]]\n* 230 milligrams of [[sodium]]\n* 17 grams of total [[carbohydrates]]\n* Less than 1 gram (but listed as 3% DV) of total [[dietary fiber]]\n* 3 grams of [[protein]]\n* 0 grams of [[sugar]]\n* 1 gram of  [[dietary fiber]]\n\n== Flavors and types ==\n\nThere are a variety of Cheez-It products, including:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cheezit.com/en_US/products.html |title=Cheez-It Baked Snack Crackers |publisher=Cheez-it.com |date= |accessdate=2016-09-18}}</ref>\n<div style=\"{{column-count|3}};\">\n* Atomic Cheddar\n* [[Buffalo Wing|Buffalo Wing]]\n* Cheddar Cheese Grooves\n* [[Swiss cheese (North America)|Swiss Cheese]] Grooves\n* [[Cheddar Jack]]\n* Cheez-It Big (a larger cracker more suitable for garnishing or dipping)\n* Cheese Pizza\n* [[Chipotle]] Cheddar\n* Duoz (two flavors in one box)\n* Duoz Sharp Cheddar & Parmesan\n* Duoz Bacon & Cheddar\n* Duoz [[Jalape\u00f1o]] & Cheddar Jack\n* Extra Toasty\n* Gripz \"mighty tiny\"\n* Hot & Spicy (made without [[Tabasco sauce|Tabasco]])\n* Italian Four Cheese\n* [[Mozzarella]]\n* [[Pepper Jack]]\n* Provolone (With Real Hickory Smoke Flavor Added)\n* Queso Fundido\n* Reduced Fat\n* Reduced Fat White Cheddar\n* Scrabble Junior\n* Sharp White Cheddar Grooves\n* Snack Mix\n* Snack Mix Double Cheese\n* Snack Mix Sweet & Salty\n* Snap'd\n* [[White cheddar|White Cheddar]]\n* Snap'd Cheddar Sour Cream\n* Whole Grain\n* Zesty Cheddar Ranch Grooves\n* Zingz Chipotle Cheddar\n* Zingz Queso Fundido\n</div>\n===Discontinued===\n<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/cheezit/status/1119692122448379904?lang=en |title=CHEEZ-IT Twitter |publisher=twitter.com |date= |accessdate=2019-10-27}}</ref>\n* Hot & Spicy (made with Tabasco)\n* Hot and Spicy Grooves\n* [[Parmesan]] & [[Garlic]]\n* Asiago\n* Chili Cheese\n* [[Colby-Jack|Colby]]\n* [[Romano cheese|Romano]]\n* Twists Buffalo Bleu\n* Smoked Cheddar\n* Duoz Smoked Cheddar and Monterey Jack\n* Duoz Zesty Queso and Cheddar Blanco\n* Nacho\n* Cheesy Sour Cream & Onion\n* Baby Swiss\n*Snack Mix Sriracha\n*Barbecue & Cheddar Snack Mix\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.cheezit.com/ Official Cheez-It website]\n\n{{Kellogg's}}\n\n[[Category:Products introduced in 1921]]\n[[Category:Brand name crackers]]\n[[Category:Kellogg's brands]]\n[[Category:Cheese]]\n[[Category:History of Dayton, Ohio]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the cheese curl snack|Cheezies}}\n{{short description|baked cheese crackers}}\n{{refimprove|date=March 2020}}\n{{infobox brand\n| name                   = Cheez-It\n| image                  = [[File:Cheez-It-Box-Small.jpg|240px]]\n| type                   = [[Cracker (food)|Cr