{"title_page": "Juwan Howard", "text_new": "{{short description|American basketball coach and former player}}\n{{featured article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name = Juwan Howard\n| image = Juwan Howard Michigan (cropped).jpg\n| width =\n| caption = Howard as head coach of [[Michigan Wolverines men's basketball|Michigan]] in 2020\n| position = Head coach \n| league = [[Big Ten Conference]]\n| team = Michigan Wolverines \n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 9\n| weight_lb = 240\n| nationality = American\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1973|2|7}}\n| birth_place = [[Chicago, Illinois]]\n| high_school = [[Chicago Vocational High School|Chicago Vocational]]<br>(Chicago, Illinois)\n| college = [[Michigan Wolverines men's basketball|Michigan]] (1991\u20131994)\n| draft_year = 1994\n| draft_round = 1\n| draft_pick = 5\n| draft_team = [[Washington Bullets]]\n| career_start = 1994\n| career_end = 2013\n| career_position = [[Power forward (basketball)|Power forward]] / [[Center (basketball)|Center]]\n| career_number   = 5, 7, 55, 6\n| coach_start = 2013\n| years1 = {{nbay|1994|start}}\u2013{{nbay|2000|end}}\n| team1 = [[Washington Wizards|Washington Bullets / Wizards]]\n| years2 = {{nbay|2000|end}}\u2013{{nbay|2001|end}}\n| team2 = [[Dallas Mavericks]]\n| years3 = {{nbay|2001|end}}\u2013{{nbay|2002|end}}\n| team3 = [[Denver Nuggets]]\n| years4 = {{nbay|2003|full=y}}\n| team4 = [[Orlando Magic]]\n| years5 = {{nbay|2004|start}}\u2013{{nbay|2006|end}}\n| team5 = [[Houston Rockets]]\n| years6={{nbay|2007|full=y}}\n| team6 = Dallas Mavericks\n| years7 = {{nbay|2008|start}}\n| team7 = Denver Nuggets\n| years8 = {{nbay|2008|full=y}}\n| team8 = [[Charlotte Bobcats]]\n| years9 = {{nbay|2009|full=y}}\n| team9 = [[Portland Trail Blazers]]\n| years10 = {{nbay|2010|start}}\u2013{{nbay|2012|end}}\n| team10 = [[Miami Heat]]\n| cyears1 = {{nbay|2013|start}}\u2013{{nbay|2018|end}}\n| cteam1 = Miami Heat (assistant)\n| cyears2 = 2019\u2013present\n| cteam2 = [[Michigan Wolverines men's basketball|Michigan]]\n| highlights =\n* 2\u00d7 [[NBA champion]] ([[2012 NBA Finals|2012]], [[2013 NBA Finals|2013]])\n* [[NBA All-Star]] ({{nasg|1996}})\n* [[All-NBA Third Team]] ({{nbay|1995|end}})\n* [[NBA All-Rookie Second Team]] ({{nbay|1994|end}})\n* Second-team [[NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|All-American]] \u2013 [[National Association of Basketball Coaches|NABC]] ([[1994 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|1994]])\n* Third-team All-American \u2013 [[Associated Press|AP]] (1994)\n* First-team [[Parade All-America Boys Basketball Team|''Parade'' All-American]] (1991)\n\n| stat1label = [[Point (basketball)|Points]]\n| stat1value = 16,159 (13.4 ppg)\n| stat2label = [[Rebound (basketball)|Rebounds]]\n| stat2value = 7,428 (6.1 rpg)\n| stat3label = [[Assist (basketball)|Assists]]\n| stat3value = 2,663 (2.2 apg)\n| bbr = howarju01\n}}\n'''Juwan Antonio Howard''' (born February 7, 1973) is an American college [[basketball]] coach and former professional player who is the head coach of the [[Michigan Wolverines men's basketball|Michigan Wolverines men's basketball team]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.freep.com/story/sports/college/university-michigan/wolverines/2019/05/22/juwan-howard-michigan-basketball-coach/3769448002/|title=Michigan basketball to hire Juwan Howard as new head coach|author1=Nick Baumgardner|author2=David Jesse|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=May 22, 2019|accessdate=May 22, 2019}}</ref> He was an assistant coach for the [[Miami Heat]] of the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA) from 2013 to 2019. Howard played in the [[NBA]] from 1994 until 2013. \n\nA one-time [[NBA All-Star Game|All-Star]] and one-time [[All-NBA]] [[Power forward (basketball)|power forward]], he began his NBA career as the fifth overall pick in the [[1994 NBA draft]], selected by the [[Washington Bullets]]. Before he was drafted, he starred as an [[All-American]] on the [[Michigan Wolverines men's basketball|Michigan Wolverines men's basketball team]]. At Michigan he was part of the [[Fab Five (University of Michigan)|Fab Five]] recruiting class of 1991 that reached the finals of the [[NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Championship]] in [[1992 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|1992]] and [[1993 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|1993]]. Howard won his first NBA championship with Miami in the [[2012 NBA Finals]] and his second NBA championship in the [[2013 NBA Finals]].\n\nHoward was an All-American [[center (basketball)|center]] and an [[honors student]] at [[Chicago Vocational Career Academy]]. Michigan was able to sign him early over numerous competing offers and then convince others in his recruiting class to join him. The Fab Five, which included [[Chris Webber]], [[Jalen Rose]], [[Jimmy King]] and [[Ray Jackson (basketball)|Ray Jackson]], served as regular [[starting lineup|starters]] during their freshman and sophomore years for the [[1991\u201392 Michigan Wolverines men's basketball team|1991\u201392]] and [[1992\u201393 Michigan Wolverines men's basketball team|1992\u201393 Wolverines]]. Howard was the last member of the Fab Five to remain active as a professional basketball player. Although many of the Wolverines' accomplishments from 1992 to 1998 were forfeited due to the [[University of Michigan basketball scandal]], which involved booster payments to players to [[Money laundering|launder money]] from illegal gambling, Howard's [[1994 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|1993\u201394 All-American]] season continues to be recognized.\n\nHoward played six-and-a-half seasons (1994\u20132001) for the Bullets franchise (renamed the Wizards in 1997), three full seasons (2004\u201307) for the [[Houston Rockets]], two plus seasons for the Heat and shorter stints for several other teams. During his rookie year with the Bullets, he became the first player to [[#Graduation|graduate on time]] with his class after leaving college early to play in the NBA. After one season as an [[NBA All-Rookie Team|All-Rookie]] player and a second as an All-Star and an All-NBA performer, he became the first NBA player to sign a $100&nbsp;million contract. While he continued to be a productive starter, he was never again selected to play in an All-Star Game. Towards the end of his contract, he was traded at the NBA trade deadline twice to make [[salary cap]] room. He was most recently a regular starter during the [[2005\u201306 NBA season]]. In 2010, he signed with the Heat and entered his 17th NBA season, during which he reached the playoffs for the sixth time and made his first career [[2011 NBA Finals|NBA Finals]] appearance. He remained with the Heat the following season and won his first NBA championship during the 2012 NBA Finals. He returned to the Heat for part of the following season, and won a second championship. Howard has developed a reputation as a humanitarian for his civic commitment.\n\n==Early life==\nHoward's grandmother, Jannie Mae Howard, was the daughter of [[sharecropper]]s from [[Belzoni, Mississippi]]. She had four daughters by her 19th birthday, including Howard's mother Helena. Helena was an employee at a Chicago restaurant when she became pregnant with Juwan. Howard's father, Leroy Watson, had just returned from the Army to a phone company job in Chicago. The two married quickly once they realized Helena was pregnant. For Howard's first week of life, his high school junior mother kept him in a drawer at Jannie Mae's house.<ref name=Albom4>{{harvnb|Albom|1993|page=4}}</ref> Helena, who was 17 years old, did not want to be restricted or burdened raising her child, so Jannie Mae adopted him.<ref name=Hehg/> His biological father, Leroy Watson Jr., wanted to name him Leroy Watson, III, but his grandmother rejected the suggestion, insisting on Juwan Antonio Howard.<ref name=GmiH>{{cite news|title=Grandma's memory inspires Howard |date=April 5, 1992|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|page=5, sports section|author=Mariotti, Jay}}</ref>  Although his mother visited on occasion as he was growing up, his grandmother raised him,<ref name=Albom4/> along with two cousins.<ref name=CU/> Howard has no siblings and is not close to his biological parents;<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/11/22/sports/sports-of-the-times-the-bullets-may-now-be-loaded.html|title=Sports of The Times; The Bullets May Now Be Loaded|accessdate=May 21, 2010|date=November 22, 1994|author=Berkow, Ira|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> his grandmother was the primary influence in his life.<ref name=Albom4/> He moved with her to several low-income [[South Side, Chicago|Chicago South Side]] projects; she kept him out of trouble and away from gangs as he was growing up.<ref name=Albom4/> One of their residences was a three-bedroom apartment on 69th Street on the South Side of Chicago.<ref name=Hehg>{{cite news|title=Howard's effort honors grandma|date=April 7, 1992|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Milbert, Neil |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1992-04-07/sports/9202010228_1_juwan-howard-michigan-early-period|accessdate=September 6, 2010}}</ref> As he blossomed under his grandmother's influence and discipline, he became her \"pride and joy\".<ref name=Hehg/>\n\n==High school==\n\nHoward went to [[Chicago Vocational Career Academy]], where he went on to play three seasons of varsity basketball.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1995-01-01/sports/1995001153_1_juwan-howard-bullets-atlanta-hawks|title=Bullets' Howard practices positive thinking|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=January 1, 1995|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|author=Bembry, Jerry}}</ref> Vocational had an unheated gym and no [[locker room]]s, which required that the team dress for games in a history classroom.<ref name=CU/> Nonetheless, Howard went on to be named a 1991 All-American basketball player by ''[[Parade (magazine)|Parade]]'' magazine and won [[McDonald's All-American Game|McDonald's All American]] honors. He was also chosen for the [[National Honor Society]] and served as Vocational's [[homecoming]] king.<ref name=Hehg/><ref name=GmiH/><ref name=TasiM/><ref name=KHoPA/> During recruiting visits by college coaches such as [[Illinois Fighting Illini men's basketball|Illinois]]' [[Lou Henson]], [[DePaul Blue Demons men's basketball|DePaul]]'s [[Joey Meyer (basketball)|Joey Meyer]] and [[Michigan Wolverines men's basketball|Michigan]]'s [[Steve Fisher]], Jannie Mae Howard did most of the questioning.<ref name=GmiH/>\n\n===Sophomore year===\nAt the start of his sophomore year in 1988, Howard was 15 years old and already expected to be a coveted [[blue chip (sports)|blue chip]] recruit in 1991.<ref>{{cite news|title=Top players get chance in Shootout|date=December 3, 1988|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Bell, Taylor|page=108, sports section}}</ref>  He was regarded as one of the best sophomore basketball players in the [[Chicago metropolitan area]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Holiday cheer from tournaments \u2013 Simeon, King best as most others fail |date=January 2, 1989|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Bell, Taylor|page=12, sports section}}</ref> He scored 26 points in a [[Chicago Public High School League]] quarterfinal loss against a [[Deon Thomas]]-led [[Simeon Career Academy]] team. Vocational ended the year with a 23&ndash;7 record.<ref>{{cite news|title=Brandon free throws lift King|date=March 8, 1989|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|page=119|author=Potash, Mark}}</ref> Howard was a second-team selection and the only sophomore named to the league coaches' 20-man 1988\u201389 All-Public League team.<ref>{{cite news|title=All-Public League |date=February 24, 1989|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|page=88, sports section}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Brandon top vote getter \u2013 Thomas next |date=February 24, 1989|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Bell, Taylor|page=88, sports section}}</ref>\n\nThe summer after his sophomore year, the {{convert|6|ft|8|in|m|2|adj=on}} center attended the [[ABCD Camp|Nike Academic Betterment and Career Development (ABCD) camp]], which was held annually in [[Princeton, New Jersey]], during the late 1980s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2007/highschool/01/25/sonny.vaccaro/|title=End of an era: Vaccaro closes ABCD camp as he eyes hoops academy|accessdate=September 2, 2010|date=January 26, 2007|work=[[Sports Illustrated]]|author=Armstrong, Kevin}}</ref> There he was matched against the {{convert|7|ft|4|in|m|2|adj=on}} [[Shawn Bradley]]. At this camp, even though the much-taller Bradley [[block (basketball)|blocked]] his shots several times, Howard established himself as one of the best junior-year [[Basketball terms#B|big men]] in the country.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1989-07-13/sports/8902170182_1_henson-won-t-illinois-jamie-brandon|title=- The ultimate redshirt: One of the most unusual stories&nbsp;... |date=July 13, 1989|accessdate=October 6, 2010|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|last=Temkin|first=Barry}}</ref>  He was involved in controversy for receiving a second pair of [[Sneaker (footwear)|sneakers]] at the camp because he was suspected of stealing them.<ref name=CHfc/>  Howard denied theft, but he was sent home on the last day of the six-day camp.<ref name=CHfc/>\n\nHoward also participated in the Bill Cronauer camp in [[Rensselaer, Indiana]], which more than 100 college coaches attended. According to the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'',  he was ranked as one of the top 10&nbsp;[[underclassmen]] in the country during the camp.<ref name=CHfc>{{cite news|title=CVS' Howard fights charge \u2013 Basketball star fears college coaches, recruiters may back off |date=July 23, 1989|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Bell, Taylor|page=22, sports section|quote=Howard, a 6\u20138 1/2 junior who is rated among the top 10 underclass prospects in the nation&nbsp;...'I was issued a pair of shoes at the beginning of camp. But they tore. I was issued another pair. Then a counselor gave me another pair. I thought it was a joke. But somebody saw me walk out with a shoebox and thought I had stolen some shoes.'}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Top stars are waiting|date=July 22, 1989|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Bell, Taylor|page=105, sports section|quote=...&nbsp;Top 20 all-star game at the B/C camp in Rensselaer, Ind&nbsp;... Juwan Howard, Vocational's 6\u20138 1/2 junior, showed he is a rising star, establishing himself among the top 10 underclassmen in the nation. In the all-star game, he had 18 points and 12 rebounds.}}</ref> Howard attended other camps that summer; his goal was to overcome Thomas, who was the reigning ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' basketball player of the year,<ref name=CTHRD/> as the best big man in the state.<ref name=CHfc/>  By the time he ended his college career in 1994, Howard was drafted a full round ahead of Thomas.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/draft/NBA_1994.html|title=1994 NBA Draft|accessdate=August 8, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref>\n\n===Junior year===\nAs Howard entered his junior year, some sources listed him as the best junior basketball player in Illinois,<ref name=Lpbid>{{cite news|title=Last playoff bids in doubt|date=October 28, 1989|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Bell, Taylor|page=101, sports section|quote=It's too early to make a formal commitment but Vocational's 6\u20139 Juwan Howard, rated the best junior basketball prospect in the state, is expected to commit to Illinois. Why? Because Illini freshman Deon Thomas is Howard 's idol. They played against each other in high school. Howard still is considering DePaul, however. }}</ref> while others ranked [[Tom Kleinschmidt]] ahead of him.<ref>{{cite news|title=S-T tourney looking a year ahead|date=August 4, 1989|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Bell, Taylor|page=77, sports section}}</ref> Taylor Bell of the ''Chicago Sun-Times'' noted that Howard was leaning toward playing either for DePaul or for Illinois. Howard was interested in Illinois because Thomas, whom Howard admired, had become a member of the [[1989\u201390 Illinois Fighting Illini men's basketball team|1989\u201390 Fighting Illini team]].<ref name=Lpbid/>  By the end of his junior year, league coaches named him to the first-team All-Chicago Public School League.<ref>{{cite news|title=All-Public League Selections|date=February 23, 1990|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|page=77, sports section}}</ref>  He was selected to the ''Chicago Sun-Times'' All-Area team as well as the Class-AA All-State team and established himself as the top Chicago-area junior ahead of Kleinschmidt.<ref>{{cite news|title=All-Chicago Area Profiles|date=March 2, 1990|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|page=74, sports section}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Class-AA All-State Profiles|date=March 16, 1990|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|page=83, sports section}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Chicago Area's Top 25 Juniors|date=March 19, 1990|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|page=107, sports section}}</ref>  Howard had a sub-par performance against [[King College Prep High School|King High School]] in the Chicago Public School League semifinals,<ref name=SHcho/>  but the ''Chicago Tribune'' named him to its All-State second team.<ref name=CHcMAS/> Vocational finished the year 24&ndash;7.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1990-03-13/sports/9001210781_1_jamie-brandon-brandon-wasn-t-public-league|title=Brandon, King Streak Past Cvs|accessdate=March 4, 2013|date=March 13, 1990|author=Sullivan, Paul|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]}}</ref>\n\nHoward was also an honors student.<ref name=SHcho/> After his junior year, he was one of 10 Illinois players invited back to the Nike All-American Camp at Princeton. Others invited included Kleinschmidt, [[Donnie Boyce]], [[William Gates (basketball)|William Gates]], [[Billy Taylor (basketball)|Billy Taylor]], [[Rashard Griffith]] and [[Howard Nathan]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Penguins hire Johnson, Bowman|date=June 13, 1990|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|page=119, sports section}}</ref>  Although Howard was considered one of the top prospects in the city of Chicago at that time, the player perceived as the best Chicago-area prospect was [[Glenn Robinson]] of [[Gary, Indiana]].<ref name=\"Wherethe1990\">{{cite news|title=Where the camps will be in action during July|date=July 1, 1990|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|page=25, sports section}}</ref> By this time, Howard had eliminated DePaul from consideration since Deryl Cunningham, another Chicago-area all-star who might have otherwise convinced Howard to stay in Chicago, had transferred to [[Kansas State Wildcats men's basketball|Kansas State]]. He was considering Michigan, [[Michigan State Spartans men's basketball|Michigan State]], [[Kentucky Wildcats men's basketball|Kentucky]], [[Arizona Wildcats men's basketball|Arizona]], [[Dayton Flyers men's basketball|Dayton]], [[Marquette Golden Eagles men's basketball|Marquette]] and Illinois.<ref name=\"Wherethe1990\"/>  Howard was evaluated as the best senior basketball player at the camp; the group of players in attendance included [[Chris Webber]], [[Cherokee Parks]], Robinson and [[Alan Henderson]].<ref name=SHcho/><ref>{{cite news|title=High School Report|date=July 13, 1990|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|page=84, sports section}}</ref>\n\nAfter being named [[Most Valuable Player]] (MVP) at the prestigious Boston Shootout and acknowledged as the leading participant at the Nike camp, Howard was mentioned as the best prospect in the country. By this time, he had dropped Michigan State and Illinois from his list of possible college destinations and had begun considering [[UNLV Runnin' Rebels basketball|UNLV]] as well.<ref name=SHcho>{{cite news|title=Sought-after Howard considers his options |date=July 15, 1990|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Travis, Clyde|page=20, sports section}}</ref> Following his time at the Nike camp, his household was besieged by recruiters. Howard issued the following statement: \"Contact my coach. I do not want my grandmother and aunt upset about calls at all times of the day and night. I'm not the only person who lives in this house. I think my wishes should be respected. If not, when it comes time to make my decision, I'll take those things into account.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=CVS' Howard upset by pushy recruiting|date=July 18, 1990|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Travis, Clyde|page=111, sports section}}</ref>  Although Howard was the best performer at the camp, talent scout Bob Gibbons felt Webber and Robinson were equally talented prospects.<ref>{{cite news|title=3 top Class of '91 as best in nation \u2013 CVS' Howard vying for No. 1 rating |date=August 5, 1990|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Bell, Taylor|page=22, sports section|quote=Gibbons, based in Lenoir, N.C., flew from Charlotte, N.C., to Philadelphia to Washington to Louisville, Ky., to Long Beach, California, to Houston to Chicago to Memphis, Tenn., to Las Vegas, Nev., to Lubbock, Texas, to Dallas to Memphis to Charlotte and determined there are three major candidates going into the 1990\u201391 season. And each of them is a 6\u20139 center-forward}}</ref>  Despite Howard's most recently listed college preferences and the fact that the team was under investigation for recruiting violations, Illinois continued pursuing Howard as its number one recruit.<ref>{{cite news|title=Morris Shootout draws Henson's full attention|date=July 23, 1990|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Potash, Mark|page=111, sports section}}</ref>  By the end of July 1990, Howard was projected to sign with Michigan.<ref>{{cite news|title=High School Report|date=July 27, 1990|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Potash, Mark|page=84, sports section}}</ref>\n\n===Senior year===\nDuring Michigan's in-home visit, Howard's grandmother treated Michigan [[head coach]] Fisher, his assistants [[Mike Boyd (basketball)|Mike Boyd]] and Brian Dutcher, Vocational coach Cook, Vocational assistant coach Donnie Kirskey, Lois Howard (Howard's aunt) and Howard to a [[soul food]] dinner.<ref>{{harvnb|Albom|1993|page=2}}</ref> Dutcher had the responsibility to contact Howard several times a week.<ref name=Albom3>{{harvnb|Albom|1993|page=3}}</ref> Howard grew close to assistant coach Kirskey, often staying at his house and using his car once he got a [[driver's license]].<ref name=Albom5>{{harvnb|Albom|1993|page=5}}</ref> During the summer 1990 30-day visitation period, Dutcher watched Howard practice 28 consecutive days.<ref name=Albom3/> Dutcher developed an understanding of the dynamics of Howard's relationship with his grandmother. While other coaches, such as [[Lute Olsen]], almost ignored her during the recruiting, Dutcher understood that she was the key influence on his life,<ref name=Albom4/> and understood that Kirskey also had sway with Howard. He encouraged Fisher to hire Kirskey for a summer basketball camp that, which became the young athlete's introduction to [[Ann Arbor, Michigan]].<ref name=Albom5/>\n\nHoward was the president of Vocational's Senior Boys' Council.<ref>{{harvnb|Albom|1993|page=1}}</ref> In the final days before his senior season decision regarding his [[college basketball]] team, Howard wavered between [[Arizona State Sun Devils men's basketball|Arizona State]] and Michigan. He also made an official visit to Dayton.<ref name=CHcMAS>{{cite news|title=CVS' Howard considers Michigan, Arizona State|date=October 31, 1990|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Temkin, Barry, Paul Sullivan and Linda Young|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1990-10-31/sports/9004020315_1_illinois-state-arizona-state-illini|accessdate=September 6, 2010}}</ref>  Despite the ongoing recruiting scandal, he made an unofficial visit to Illinois, which had recruited four of the five previous Chicago Public School League Illinois Players of the Year.<ref>{{cite news|title=Publics await word on Illini|date=October 29, 1990|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Bell, Taylor|page=102, sports section}}</ref> At the time of his decision, Howard was considered one of the top five seniors in the country, but unlike many top basketball recruits, he decided not to hold a press conference to announce his choice.<ref>{{cite news|title=CVS star on verge of choice|date=November 1, 1990|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Temkin, Barry|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1990-11-01/sports/9004020352_1_press-conference-cvs-chicago-vocational|accessdate=September 6, 2010}}</ref>  Although the official signing period was set for November 14\u201321, 1990, he selected Michigan on November 2.<ref>{{cite news|title=Michigan gets CVS' Howard|date=November 2, 1990|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author1=Temkin, Barry  |author2=Steve Nidetz|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1990-11-02/sports/9004030441_1_girls-basketball-state-high-school-basketball-boys-action|accessdate=September 6, 2010}}</ref> Howard's grandmother died of a heart attack a few hours after he announced that he would attend Michigan,<ref name=Hehg/> and he moved in with his high school coach, Richard Cook.<ref name=GmiH/>\n\nHoward averaged 26.9 points, 8.4 [[Rebound (basketball)|rebounds]] and 3.4 [[assist (basketball)|assists]] during his senior season,<ref name=Hehg/> and finished in the top 10&nbsp;percent of his academic class.<ref>{{cite news|title=Class of 1991 The dedication|date=June 16, 1991|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1991-06-16/sports/9102230619_1_state-finals-illinois-state-individual-titles|accessdate=September 6, 2010}}</ref> He took Vocational to the Public League semifinals where they lost to [[George Westinghouse College Prep|Westinghouse College Prep]], finishing with a 25&ndash;5 record, despite his 25 points and 12 rebounds.<ref>{{cite news|title=W-house maneuvers past CVS|date=March 10, 1991|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|page=32|author=Potash, Mark}}</ref> He befriended [[Jimmy King]] when they visited Michigan on the same weekend; according to the ''Chicago Tribune'' Fisher Howard influenced King's decision to also enroll there.<ref name=Hehg/><ref>{{cite news|title=CVS' Howard already pays Michigan dividend|date=November 11, 1990|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author1=Temkin, Barry  |author2=George Knue|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1990-11-11/sports/9004050175_1_juwan-howard-wolverine-prospects|accessdate=September 6, 2010|quote=Thursday, 6-foot-4-inch guard Jimmy King of Plano, Texas, announced he would sign a letter-of-intent with Michigan during the Nov. 14\u201321 early-signing period. King is regarded as one of the top 20 prospects in the nation. A major reason he chose Michigan is the 6\u20139 Howard, who had orally committed to the school a week earlier.}}</ref> According to Clyde Travis of the ''Chicago Sun-Times'', Howard's verbal commitment made up for Fisher's failure to recruit [[Eric Montross]] the prior year,<ref>{{cite news|title=Howard to Michigan |date=November 2, 1990|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Travis, Clyde|page=101, sports section|quote=Fisher was desperate to land a player of Howard 's caliber after losing Eric Montross to North Carolina last year and apparently losing 6\u20139 Chris Webber of Birmingham, Mich., the nation's No. 2 prospect this year, to Michigan State. }}</ref> even though Montross' father and grandfather had played for Michigan.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dislike Michigan? Count the ways|date=April 5, 1993|work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |author=Lincicome, Bernie |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1993-04-05/sports/9304050210_1_chris-webber-jalen-rose-juwan-howard |accessdate=September 6, 2010}}</ref>  With [[Jalen Rose]], Webber, Howard and King&nbsp;\u2013 along with [[Ray Jackson (basketball)|Ray Jackson]], a less-heralded prospect&nbsp;\u2013 the Michigan recruiting class was considered to be the best in the nation.<ref>{{cite news|title=Michigan adds to riches Wolverines assemble top freshman class|date=April 14, 1991|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Armour, Terry|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1991-04-14/sports/9102030423_1_michigan-signing-wolverines|accessdate=September 6, 2010}}</ref>  Some regarded the class as among the greatest recruiting classes of all time.<ref>{{cite news|title=Michigan gets top guns 'Great recruiter' Fisher lures 4 of top 10|date=April 28, 1991|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Armour, Terry|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1991-04-28/sports/9102070824_1_top-point-guards-recruiting-eric-pauley|accessdate=September 6, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Michigan's recruiting class hailed as best|date=March 28, 1991|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Bell, Taylor|page=94, sports section}}</ref>\n\nAs a senior, Howard edged Griffith and [[Kiwane Garris]] for the most votes to the ''Sun-Times''' annual All-Chicago Public School League boys' basketball team.<ref>{{cite news|title=Howard tops All-Public team |date=February 22, 1991|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Bell, Taylor|page=71, sports section}}</ref>  He was also selected to the All-Area team and was a repeat Class-AA All-State selection.<ref>{{cite news|title=All-Chicago Area Boys' Basketball Profiles|date=March 1, 1991|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|page=88, sports section}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Boys' Class AA All-State Profiles|date=March 15, 1991|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|page=87, sports section}}</ref>  Howard, Kleinschmidt and Robinson were all selected to the 10-member first team of ''Parade'' magazine's 40-member high school All-America boys' basketball team.<ref name=KHoPA>{{cite news|title=Kleinschmidt, Howard on Parade All-America|date=March 3, 1991|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Bell, Taylor|page=28, sports section}}</ref>  They were also chosen to play in the McDonald's All-America game.<ref name=TasiM>{{cite news|title=Two area stars in McDonald's|date=March 19, 1991|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Bell, Taylor|page=79, sports section}}</ref>  West MVP Webber posted 28 points and 12 rebounds in the game; with Howard adding 16 points, the West won 108\u2013106.<ref>{{cite news|title=Webber, Howard help West capture McDonald's game|date=April 7, 1991|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|page=30, sports section}}</ref>  Howard also earned the Gatorade Circle of Champions' Illinois Player of the Year Award.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mashburn, Cheaney Top AP All-America|date=March 16, 1993|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|page=75, sports section}}</ref>  Howard's [[ACT test]] score was high enough to make him eligible under [[Proposition 48 (NCAA)|Proposition 48]] academic requirements to play as a freshman.<ref>{{cite news|title=Michigan's Howard eligible|date=April 30, 1991|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|page=81, sports section}}</ref> Only eight of the top 25 Chicago Public School League players achieved a qualifying score on the test.<ref>{{cite news|title=ACT proves disaster for most top recruits \u2013 Results this season seen as the worst since '84 |date=May 10, 1991|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Bell, Taylor|page=81, sports section}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\n\n===Freshman year===\n[[File:Fab Five original crop.jpg|thumb|left|300px|[[Michigan Wolverines men's basketball|Michigan]]'s [[Fab Five (University of Michigan)|Fab Five]] (left to right) [[Jimmy King]], [[Jalen Rose]], [[Chris Webber]], [[Ray Jackson (basketball)|Ray Jackson]] and Howard|alt=five Black males in gold athletic uniforms in the foreground on the sidelines of an athletic court while a few opposing athletes in green wait in the middle of the court.]]\nHoward matriculated to the University of Michigan and joined his fellow freshmen for the [[1991\u201392 Michigan Wolverines men's basketball team|1991\u201392 Michigan Wolverines]] in forming a group that became known as the [[Fab Five (University of Michigan)|Fab Five]]. He also joined future NBA personalities [[Eric Riley]] and [[Rob Pelinka]].<ref>{{cite news|title='Fab' also applies to this role player|date=April 2, 1993|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Temkin, Barry|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1993-04-02/sports/9304020386_1_lake-forest-michigan-fab|accessdate=September 6, 2010}}</ref> As Michigan celebrated [[Midnight Madness (basketball)|Midnight Madness]] on October 15, 1991, there was already talk that at least four of the five freshmen would be starting before the season ended.<ref>{{cite news|title=Chicago players court fame|author=Bell, Taylor|date=October 15, 1991|page=70, sport section|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]}}</ref> (The five eventually started in a combined 304 of a possible 350 man-games among them during their first two seasons.)<ref name=\"MB07-8p13-21\"/> Early in his freshman season, Howard started in some games and came off the bench in others for the highly rated Wolverines.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1992-01-18/sports/9201050918_1_illini-program-lou-henson-juwan-howard|title=Illini face Michigan-and the one who got away|date=January 18, 1992|accessdate=October 6, 2010|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Sullivan, Paul}}</ref> Over time, he won a starting role from Riley.<ref name=HDICT/> In Michigan's first matchup against Illinois, Howard scored 13&nbsp;points and denied Thomas the ball consistently enough to hold him to 8&nbsp;shots. His biggest contribution in the game was getting his hand on a loose ball to force a [[jump ball]] with 16&nbsp;seconds left and Michigan leading by only three points.<ref>{{cite news|title=Michigan holds off Illinois|date=January 19, 1992|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Sullivan, Paul|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1992-01-19/sports/9201060339_1_illini-michigan-coach-steve-fisher-lou-henson|accessdate=September 6, 2010}}</ref>  In the [[Elite Eight]] round of the [[1992 NCAA Men's Division&nbsp;I Basketball Tournament]], Michigan faced a [[Jim Jackson (basketball)|Jimmy Jackson]]-led [[1991\u201392 Ohio State Buckeyes men's basketball team|Ohio State Buckeyes]] team that had beaten them twice during the regular season by double-digit margins.<ref>{{cite news|title=Michigan's 'Fab Five' vow to have their say|author=Boers, Terry|date=March 29, 1992|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|page=8, sports section}}</ref>  Michigan won the rematch, during which the Fab Five scored all but two of the Wolverines' points.<ref>{{cite news|title=Who'll reign \u2013 and who'll wane?|author=Hanley, Brian|date=March 30, 1992|page=90, sports section|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]}}</ref>\n\nThe victory gave the 24\u20138 Wolverines a berth in the [[final four|Final Four]], where they found themselves matched against a 29\u20134 [[Bob Huggins]]-coached [[1991\u201392 Cincinnati Bearcats men's basketball team|Cincinnati Bearcats]] team that averaged 83.6&nbsp;[[point (basketball)|points]] per game and had lost to only three teams, two of which had beaten Michigan.<ref>{{cite news|title=Fisher out of Michigan spotlight|date=April 4, 1992|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Milbert, Neil |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1992-04-04/sports/9201310208_1_athletic-director-bo-schembechler-bill-frieder-steve-fisher|accessdate=September 6, 2010}}</ref>  [[Nick Van Exel]] led Cincinnati in postseason scoring.<ref name=CMcd>{{cite news|title=Cincy-Michigan choice debatable|author=Hanley, Brian|date=April 3, 1992|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|page=93, sports section}}</ref>  Howard, King and Riley shaved their heads for the game.<ref>{{cite news|title='Guilt' keeps Raveling at Southern Cal|date=April 3, 1992|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Myslenski, Skip |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1992-04-03/sports/9201310056_1_legendary-high-school-coach-jalen-rose-factor|accessdate=September 6, 2010}}</ref>  Michigan won and earned a rematch with a [[1991\u201392 Duke Blue Devils men's basketball team|Duke Blue Devils team]] that had beaten them by three points in overtime in December.<ref name=Hehg/><ref>{{cite news|title=Too young to get this far&nbsp;... Not!|date=April 5, 1992|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Lincicome, Bernie |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1992-04-05/sports/9201310662_1_college-basketball-blank-slate-duke|accessdate=September 6, 2010}}</ref>  In the initial contest, Howard had scored only four points.<ref name=Hehg/> Entering the final game, he was averaging 11.2&nbsp;points and 6.3&nbsp;rebounds for the season.<ref name=Hehg/>  The day before the game, Howard had stomach cramps and fever and received fluids to combat dehydration. As a result, he was exempted from mandatory media meetings.<ref name=LHwba>{{cite news|title=Little Hurley wins big award|date=April 7, 1992|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author1=Boers, Terry  |author2=Brian Hanley|page=85, sports section}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Duke fears sprain might sideline Davis|date=April 6, 1992|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author1=Boers, Terry  |author2=Brian Hanley|page=90, sports section}}</ref>  Howard was part of a rotation with Webber and Riley that guarded the National Player of the Year, [[Christian Laettner]].<ref name=Hehg/>  During Laettner's first six possessions against Howard, Laettner dribbled the basketball off his foot, missed a shot, threw a pass that resulted in a [[turnover (basketball)|turnover]], [[traveling (basketball)|traveled]], threw the ball away and hit the backboard with a shot.<ref name=Hehg/>  Duke scored in its final 12&nbsp;possessions of the championship game, going on a 23\u20136 run to win by a final margin of 71\u201351.<ref>{{cite news|title=Michigan kids crushed, but Howard sees title in '93.|date=April 7, 1992|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Milbert, Neil |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1992-04-07/sports/9202010255_1_eastern-michigan-laettner-college-basketball|accessdate=September 6, 2010}}</ref> Despite his condition, Howard contributed 9&nbsp;points in 29&nbsp;minutes.<ref name=LHwba/> Howard earned a reputation for his quick feet, ability to grasp fundamentals, and excellent moves in the [[low post]], but also for his 1-to-2 assist-to-turnover ratio and a high number of [[foul (basketball)|fouls]].<ref name=Hehg/>\n\n===Sophomore year===\nAs his sophomore year began, media reports alleged that three Wolverines basketball players were paid $300 each to participate in a charity basketball tournament in mid-1992, during the off-season. The reports further alleged that some others, including Howard, appeared at several summer basketball camps together, which was a possible violation of NCAA rules.<ref>{{cite news|title=3 Ineligible at Michigan \u2013 Basketball Players Received Money in Charity Tourney |date=September 17, 1992|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Rosewater, Amy|page=92, sports section}}</ref>  At the beginning of his [[1992\u201393 Michigan Wolverines men's basketball team|1992\u201393 sophomore season]], Michigan returned its top nine scorers and began the season ranked number one in the country by the [[Associated Press]].<ref>{{cite news|title=U-M At Top Of The Polls|date=November 17, 1992|work=[[Detroit Free Press]]|author=Stoda, Greg}}</ref>  Michigan lost its second game of the season in a rematch with [[1992\u201393 Duke Blue Devils men's basketball team|Duke]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Top Tow Take a Tumble \u2013 Duke, Kansas knock Off Michigan (1), Indiana (2) |date=December 6, 1992|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Adande, J. A.|page=1, sports section}}</ref> Howard was described as the steadiest player on the team that season by coach Fisher.<ref>{{cite news|title=Fisher praises Howard's play|date=January 12, 1993|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author1=Milbert, Neil  |author2=Andrew Bagnato|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1993-01-12/sports/9303161374_1_michigan-indiana-lehigh|accessdate=September 6, 2010}}</ref> During the season, Howard purchased a million-dollar disability insurance policy approved by the NCAA under the Exceptional Student Athlete Disability Insurance Program available to student-athletes who are projected to be chosen high in the NBA, [[National Football League]] (NFL), and [[Major League Baseball]] drafts.<ref>{{cite news|title=Michigan Super Sophs Are Worth Millions|date=December 18, 1992|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|page=97, sports section}}</ref>\n\nIn the semifinals of the [[1993 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament]] against [[1992\u201393 Kentucky Wildcats men's basketball team|Kentucky]], Howard contributed on offense and held [[Jamal Mashburn]] in check defensively; Mashburn did not make a field goal in the last 12:36 of regulation.<ref name=OAFFPTNF>{{cite news|title=Once Again, Fab Five Prove They're No Fad|date=April 4, 1993|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Mariotti, Jay|page=2, sports section|quote=...&nbsp;Juwan Howard, the steady, bullish center from Chicago who did such a terrific defensive job on Jamal Mashburn&nbsp;...}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Mich. Again \u2013 N.C., Too \u2013 Wolverines Fabulous In Overtime|date=April 4, 1993|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Adande, J. A.|page=1, sports section|quote=Mashburn scored 26 points, but had only nine after halftime and went the last 12:36 of regulation without a field goal.}}</ref> Sportswriter [[Jay Mariotti]] wrote that Howard had done \"a terrific defensive job\" in guarding Mashburn.<ref name=OAFFPTNF/> The 31\u20134 Wolverines were matched up against the 33\u20134 [[1992\u201393 North Carolina Tar Heels men's basketball team|North Carolina Tar Heels]] in the championship game; both Fisher and North Carolina head coach [[Dean Smith]] were seeking their second national title.<ref>{{cite news|title=Season's end is Finally near Michigan, N. Carolina vie for title|date=April 5, 1993|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Myslenski, Skip |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1993-04-05/sports/9304050272_1_lighter-touch-michigan-dean-smith|accessdate=September 6, 2010}}</ref>  During the championship game Howard picked up his second [[Personal foul (basketball)|personal foul]] with 9&nbsp;minutes 42&nbsp;seconds remaining in the first half and was soon substituted out as the entire team dealt with an accumulation of fouls.<ref>{{cite news|title=Closely called game creates foul mood Carolina wins battle of free throws|date=April 6, 1993|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Bagnato, Andrew |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1993-04-06/sports/9304060303_1_foul-michigan-bench|accessdate=September 6, 2010|quote=From the beginning, it was clear that the referees were going to call this heavyweight brawl closely. Too closely, Michigan might have thought. By halftime, Wolverines Chris Webber, Juwan Howard and Jimmy King each had two fouls, and Ray Jackson had three&nbsp;... The game shifted when Howard and Webber drew their second fouls in a 64-second span midway through the first half. Howard's second came with 9 minutes 42 seconds until the break; Webber's with 8:38 left. After Webber's foul, Fisher replaced Howard with 7-footer Eric Riley. But Fisher couldn't afford to have both big men on the bench, so Webber had to begin playing cautiously.}}</ref><ref name=Mcft/>  The game would be remembered for a late [[technical foul]] against Webber for attempting to call a [[Time-out (sport)|time out]] when the Wolverines had none left; this led to a Tar Heels victory.<ref name=Mcft>{{cite news|title=Michigan calls fatal timeout|date=April 6, 1993|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Myslenski, Skip|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1993-04-06/sports/9304060237_1_tourney-foul-shooting|accessdate=September 6, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Webber deserves a break&nbsp;... and Carolina more credit|date=April 7, 1993|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Myslenski, Skip|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1993-04-07/sports/9304070138_1_chris-webber-calling-defenders|accessdate=September 6, 2010}}</ref>  Over the course of the season, Howard averaged 14.6&nbsp;points and 7.4&nbsp;rebounds.<ref>{{cite news|title=College Basketball '93\u2013'94 \u2013 Big Ten Conference|date=November 25, 1993|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|page=133, sports section}}</ref> After the season, Webber and Howard were invited to try out for the United States national basketball team that would compete at the [[1993 Summer Universiade|1993 World University Games]] and [[FIBA Under-21 World Championship|Under-22 World Championships]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Top collegians invited to international tryout|date=April 22, 1993|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Myslenski, Skip|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1993-04-22/sports/9304220154_1_invited-shawn-respert-collegians|accessdate=September 6, 2010}}</ref> Howard did not make the team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usabasketball.com/mens/worlduniversity/mwug_1993.html|title=Seventeenth World University Games \u2013 1993|accessdate=May 22, 2012|publisher=[[USA Basketball]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120523072126/http://www.usabasketball.com/mens/worlduniversity/mwug_1993.html|archivedate=May 23, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Junior year===\nWith Webber's departure for the NBA after his sophomore season, the [[1993\u201394 Michigan Wolverines men's basketball team|1993\u201394 Wolverines team]] entered the season ranked fifth in the nation as it opened the season against number&nbsp;13 {{cbb link|1993|sex=men|team=Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets|school=Georgia Institute of Technology|title=Georgia Tech}}.<ref>{{cite news|title=With No One To Lean On This Season, Michigan's Rose Grows Up|date=November 26, 1993|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Myslenski, Skip|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1993-11-26/sports/9311260286_1_warriors-webber-chris-webber-michigan|accessdate=September 6, 2010}}</ref> Since his grandmother had been born on December 25, Howard got a tattoo reading \"Jannie Mae\" over his heart during Christmas break.<ref name=CU>{{cite web|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1007777/1/index.htm|title=Cleaning Up: Juwan Howard, a do-everything forward the Bullets resignedly drafted, is wiping out his NBA opponents|accessdate=March 5, 2013|date=February 26, 1996|work=[[Sports Illustrated]]|author=Howard, Johnette}}</ref> During the season, Howard contracted the [[chicken pox]] in January.<ref>{{cite news|title=Game of the Day For Spotty Play \u2013 Michigan's Howard Chills Listless Illini |date=January 24, 1994|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Adande, J. A.|page=100, sports section}}</ref>  Michigan had a 21\u20136 (13\u20134 [[Big Ten Conference|Big Ten]]) record and tied with the [[1993\u201394 Purdue Boilermakers men's basketball team|Purdue Boilermakers]] for the conference lead with one game remaining.<ref>{{cite news|title=Michigan Ties For Big 10 Lead|date=March 10, 1994|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|id={{ProQuest|283770889}}}}</ref>  Michigan then lost (for the third time in its last four games) to a struggling {{cbb link|1993|sex=men|team=Northwestern Wildcats|school=Northwestern University|title=Northwestern Wildcats}} team,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/03/13/sports/college-basketball-hard-day-for-high-mighty-arkansas-company-take-falls.html|title=College Basketball; Hard Day for the High and Mighty: Arkansas and Company Take Falls|accessdate=May 19, 2010|date=March 13, 1994|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> and finished second in the Big Ten.<ref name=USRWPMTFHIMR>{{cite news|title=Underdogs Still Running With Pack Maryland, Tulsa Face Heavyweights In Midwest Regional|date=March 25, 1994|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Deardorff, Julie|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1994-03-25/sports/9403250177_1_michigan-upstart-maryland-regional-semifinal|accessdate=September 6, 2010}}</ref> After the season, Howard was selected as a first team All-Big-Ten member along with his teammate Rose, Purdue's Robinson, Michigan State's [[Shawn Respert]], and Indiana's [[Damon Bailey]].<ref>{{cite news|title=All-Big Ten|date=March 15, 1994|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|page=87, sports section}}</ref> In the opening round of the [[1994 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament]], Howard helped Michigan to a 78\u201374 overtime victory over {{cbb link|1993|sex=men|team=Pepperdine Waves|school=Pepperdine University|title=Pepperdine}} by scoring 28&nbsp;points and adding 9&nbsp;rebounds before fouling out.<ref>{{cite news|title=Michigan Needs OT To Escape Pepperdine|date=March 18, 1994|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Myslenski, Skip|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1994-03-18/sports/9403180073_1_damin-lopez-pepperdine-juwan-howard|accessdate=September 6, 2010}}</ref> In the second round, Howard posted 34&nbsp;points and 18&nbsp;rebounds to lead the team to an 84\u201379 victory over {{cbb link|1993|sex=men|team=Texas Longhorns|school=University of Texas|title=Texas}}.<ref name=HKMAH3P1RRT>{{cite news|title=Howard Keeps Michigan Alive His 34 Points, 18 Rebounds Repel Texas|date=March 20, 1994|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Myslenski, Skip|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1994-03-20/sports/9403200331_1_michigan-texas-juwan-howard|accessdate=September 6, 2010}}</ref>  Michigan faced a [[Joe Smith (basketball)|Joe Smith]]-led {{cbb link|1993|sex=men|team=Maryland Terrapins|school=University of Maryland|title=Maryland}} in the Sweet Sixteen round.<ref name=USRWPMTFHIMR/> Howard scored 24&nbsp;points and had 11&nbsp;rebounds before fouling out with 2:49 remaining in the 78\u201371 victory.<ref>{{cite news|title=Big Ten Splits \u2013 Michigan Foils Maryland Bid \u2013 Arkansas Next|date=March 26, 1994|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Gould, Herb|page=104, sports section}}</ref>  Howard earned the regional MVP award with a game-high 30&nbsp;points and 13&nbsp;rebounds in the Elite Eight round, despite collecting two fouls in the first two minutes and losing against the [[1993\u201394 Arkansas Razorbacks men's basketball team|Arkansas Razorbacks]], which had [[United States President]] [[Bill Clinton]] in attendance as a vocal supporter.<ref>{{cite news|title=Michigan Suffers Shortfall Howard Not Enough, So It's Arkansas|date=March 28, 1994|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Deardorff, Julie|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1994-03-28/sports/9403280204_1_arkansas-michigan-corliss-big-nasty-williamson|accessdate=September 6, 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn April 18, Howard announced his intention to enter the [[1994 NBA draft]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1994-04-19/sports/9404190118_1_jannie-mae-howard-webber-and-rose-college-athletics|accessdate=September 6, 2010|title=Howard, The 'Rock' For Michigan, Enters NBA Draft|date=April 19, 1994|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Myslenski, Skip}}</ref>  The following day, Rose announced he would enter the draft as well.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1994-04-20/sports/9404200204_1_ncaa-tourney-dugan-fife-travis-conlan|accessdate=September 6, 2010|title=Michigan's Fav 5 Slips To 2 As Rose Enters NBA Draft|date=April 20, 1994|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Myslenski, Skip}}</ref> Howard was 37 [[credit hour]]s short of University of Michigan degree requirements, but said he intended to keep his promise to his grandmother that he would earn his diploma.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/04/19/sports/sports-people-college-basketball-howard-of-michigan-to-enter-nba-draft.html|title=Sports People: College Basketball; Howard of Michigan To Enter N.B.A. Draft|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=April 19, 1994|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref>\nHoward left Michigan after being named an Associated Press third team [[1994 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|All-American]] during his junior year, and was taken by the [[Washington Bullets]] fifth overall in the 1994 NBA Draft.<ref name=JHBR>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/h/howarju01.html|title=Juwan Howard|accessdate=May 18, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref>  Howard was represented by [[David Falk]].<ref name=HHOARBHAN>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1994-09-28/sports/9409280024_1_bulls-vinson-smith-bears|accessdate=September 6, 2010|title=Howard Hangs Out As Rumors Bounce Him Around NBA|date=September 28, 1994|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Armour, Terry}}</ref>\n\n===Graduation===\nHoward became the first NBA athlete who entered the draft early and graduated with his academic class,<ref name=JHNBABIO>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/playerfile/juwan_howard/bio.html |title=Players: Juwan Howard (Bio) |accessdate=August 20, 2008 |publisher=National Basketball Association |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081013003826/http://www.nba.com/playerfile/juwan_howard/bio.html |archivedate=October 13, 2008 }}</ref> thus fulfilling a promise he had made to his grandmother on the last day he saw her alive.<ref name=FHSCBD/><ref name=TADHKHPTHG/> He told [[Mitch Albom]] that when he made it to the NBA, he realized how much leisure time the multimillionaire players had and decided to do something productive instead of find ways to spend his new riches. \"I knew if I kept pushing it off, I'd never get it done\", he said. He completed his final 32 course hours by taking summer classes in 1994 during the NBA off-season. He took correspondence classes and [[independent study]] courses during the following season, studying on road trips and mailing in his papers from the nearest post office. In the end, he earned a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree in  communications at Michigan. He told Albom that earning his degree made him a better example when speaking about staying in school.<ref name=TADHKHPTHG>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=rOgyAAAAIBAJ&sjid=wgcGAAAAIBAJ&pg=6140,5912218&dq=juwan+howard+graduation&hl=en|title=To A Degree, Howard Keeps His Promise To His Grandmother|author=Albom, Mitch|work=[[The Free Lance-Star]]|accessdate=September 14, 2010|date=April 29, 1995}}</ref>  Although Howard had spent the prior year playing in the NBA, he returned to campus to partake in graduation ceremonies with his classmates.<ref name=FHSCBD>{{cite web|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost/access/19558776.html?dids=19558776:19558776&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Apr+30%2C+1995&author=Rachel+Alexander&pub=The+Washington+Post+%28pre-1997+Fulltext%29&desc=For+Howard%2C+Success+Comes+By+Degree%3B+Bullets+Rookie%27s+Hard+Work+Leads+to+Michigan+Graduation&pqatl=google|title=For Howard, Success Comes By Degree; Bullets Rookie's Hard Work Leads to Michigan Graduation|accessdate=September 14, 2010|date=April 30, 1995|work=[[The Washington Post]]|author=Alexander, Rachel|page=DO1}}</ref>   During the graduation, keynote speaker [[Marian Wright Edelman]] paid special recognition to Howard and Fab Five teammates King and Jackson, who graduated together, and noted that Howard's graduation made him a role model for children.<ref>{{cite news|title='95 Seniors Bid Bittersweet Goodbye To Blue|author=Klein, Stephanie Jo|work=[[Michigan Daily]]|date=May 3, 1995}}</ref>\n\n===Forfeits===\nAlthough the Fab Five's games in the Final Four have since been forfeited,<ref name=\"MB07-8p8\">{{cite book |title=2007\u201308 Men's Basketball Media Guide |publisher=University of Michigan |page=8 |year=2007}}</ref> Howard was not among the players, which included [[Robert Traylor]], Webber, Rose, [[Maurice Taylor]], and [[Louis Bullock]], called before a [[grand jury]] to testify<ref name=\"FUaatiMc\">{{cite news |title=Former U-M assistant testifies in Martin case: Also, prosecutors issue two indictments of Martin's associates  |date=October 19, 2000 |publisher=Michigan Live LLC |work=[[Ann Arbor News]] |author=Larcom,Geoff}}</ref> in the [[University of Michigan basketball scandal]]. He was not implicated in the scandal.<ref>{{cite news |title=Text of the indictment  |date=March 22, 2002 |publisher=Michigan Live LLC |work=[[Ann Arbor News]]}}</ref> Although the NCAA sanctioned Michigan Wolverines men's basketball by forfeiting many of its records and accomplishments from 1992 to 1998, Howard's status as a 1993\u201394 All-American remained intact.<ref name=\"MB07-8p13-21\">{{cite book |title=2007\u201308 Men's Basketball Media Guide |publisher=University of Michigan |pages=13\u201321 |year=2007}}</ref>\n\n==NBA career==\n\n===Washington Bullets/Wizards (1994\u20132001)===\nEntering the {{nbay|1994|app=season}}, the NBA players and owners had not yet agreed on the terms of a new [[collective bargaining agreement]], and Howard was unsigned two weeks before training camp began. He continued to train in Chicago in late September amidst rumors that his draft rights could be traded to another team.<ref name=HHOARBHAN/>  While holding out, he was rumored to be part of a trade package with the [[1994\u201395 Chicago Bulls season|Chicago Bulls]] that included [[Calbert Cheaney]] and a first-round draft choice in exchange for [[Scottie Pippen]].<ref name=EGHORTNS/><ref>{{cite news|title=Pippen Talk Heats Up in Miami Again|date=August 25, 1994|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|page=94, sports section}}</ref> Another rumor had Howard being packaged with [[Rex Chapman]] and [[Don MacLean (basketball)|Don MacLean]] for Pippen.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bullets Pursuing Pippen, But Bulls Aren't Biting|date=July 23, 1994|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Adande, J. A.|page=93, sports section}}</ref>  On November 9, eleventh overall 1994 NBA draft selection [[Carlos Rogers (basketball)|Carlos Rogers]] signed an NBA contract, making Howard the last first-round selection without a contract.<ref>{{cite news|title=9-Year Deal For Warriors' Rogers Howard Is Only First-Round Pick Who Hasn't Signed|date=November 9, 1994|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|id={{ProQuest|283856405}}}}</ref> He missed most of the first month of the season and resided at an [[O'Hare Airport]] hotel while protracted talks continued.<ref name=EGHORTNS>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1995-02-15/sports/9502150107_1_juwan-howard-bulls-general-manager-jerry-bullets-coach-jim-lynam|title=Ex-CVS Great Howard On Rise To NBA Stardom|accessdate=September 6, 2010|date=February 15, 1995|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Smith, Sam}}</ref> Howard's agent [[David Falk]] said that one of the main problems was that the Bullets wanted Howard to sign for a lower average salary than number six selection [[Sharone Wright]].<ref name=CU/> The Bullets stuck to a 10-year, $30&nbsp;million (${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|30|1994|r=1}}}}&nbsp;million in {{Inflation-year|US}} dollars{{inflation-fn|US}}) offer.<ref>{{cite news|title=English Breathes Sigh of Relief|date=October 30, 1994|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Jackson, John|page=21, sports section}}</ref> On November 17,<ref name=WGW>{{cite news|title=Webber Gets Wish \u2013 Sent to Bullets For Gugliotta, 3 No. 1 Picks |date=November 18, 1994|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Heisler, Mark|page=146, sports section}}</ref> Howard signed what was believed to be a 12-year, $37.5&nbsp;million (${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|37.5|1994|r=1}}}}&nbsp;million) contract.<ref name=EGHORTNS/> Howard's contract, which ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' later said was an 11-year $36&nbsp;million (${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|36|1994|r=1}}}}&nbsp;million) deal, had an [[escape clause]].<ref name=CU/> Once he signed, he was reunited with Michigan teammate Webber as a member of the Bullets.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1995-01-03/features/9501030015_1_juwan-howard-skyhook-michigan|accessdate=September 6, 2010|title=Bros In The Pros Ex-College Teammates Take On NBA Together|date=January 3, 1995|author=Hanrahan, Brendan |work=[[Chicago Tribune]]}}</ref>  Webber, who had also sat out training camp and the first eight games of the season,<ref name=WHBB>{{cite news|title=Webber, Howard Bolster Bullets|date=November 20, 1994|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Banks, Lacy J. |page=13, sports section}}</ref> was traded from the {{NBA Year|1994|team=Golden State Warriors|title=Golden State Warriors}} to the Bullets on November 18 for [[Tom Gugliotta]] and three first-round draft choices.<ref name=WGW/>\n\nAfter Webber joined the Bullets, many thought that the two former Fab Five members would bring success to the team, coached by Lynam. The Washington front line was expected to include Webber, Howard, and [[Kevin Duckworth]] and to have [[Gheorghe Mure\u0219an]], a {{convert|7|ft|7|in|cm|adj=on}} [[Romania]]n center, coming off the bench.<ref name=WHBB/>  Chapman, MacLean, Cheaney, [[Mitchell Butler]] and [[Scott Skiles]] were expected to provide solid perimeter play.<ref name=WHBB/> Experts projected the Bullets as contenders for the Eastern Conference title.<ref name=WHBB/> The Howard/Webber Bullets debut against the [[Boston Celtics]] established new Bullets [[Nielsen ratings|television ratings]] records for the [[Home Team Sports]] network.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1994-11-25/sports/1994329009_1_tomorrow-night-juwan-howard-game|title=There's much TV to feast upon|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=November 25, 1994|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|author=Kent, Milton}}</ref> However, the early season trade left the team in a state of confusion due to lack of familiarity, which resulted in communication difficulties on the court.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1994-11-29/sports/1994333156_1_larry-stewart-bullets-juwan-howard|title=Unfamiliarity leaves Bullets lost, for now|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=November 29, 1994|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|author=Tanton, Bill}}</ref> Howard eventually moved into the starting lineup.<ref name=EGHORTNS/> As a power forward, Howard posted impressive numbers after he became a regular starter.<ref name=EGHORTNS/>  Howard participated in the February 11, 1995, [[1995 NBA All-Star Game|NBA All-Star]] weekend events as a member of the [[Rising Stars Challenge|Rookie Challenge]].<ref>{{cite news|title=All-Star Facts|date=February 11, 1995|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|page=94, sports section}}</ref>  He earned second team All-Rookie honors at the end of the season.<ref name=JHBR/> That month, he became the second Bullet (since the award's inception in 1981) and first since [[Jeff Ruland]] in January 1982 to be named NBA Rookie of the Month.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/wizards-insider/wp/2013/01/03/bradley-beal-wins-eastern-conference-rookie-of-the-month/|title=Bradley Beal wins Eastern Conference rookie of the month|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=February 26, 1995|work=[[The Washington Post]]|author=Lee, Michael}}</ref> During the month he averaged 20.1 points, 8 rebounds and 1.2 blocks in 14 games, including his first two 30-point games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1995-03-02/sports/1995061131_1_howard-juwan-grant-hill|title=Howard top player in February|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=March 2, 1995|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|author=Bembry, Jerry}}</ref> The following month Howard suffered an ankle injury, missing a total of 10 games (all of which were Bullets losses).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1995-04-14/sports/1995104072_1_bullets-13th-straight-game-chris-webber|title=Bullets drop 13th straight game|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=April 14, 1995|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|author=Bembry, Jerry}}</ref> Over the course of the season, he averaged 17.0&nbsp;points per game and posted 17&nbsp;[[Double (basketball)#Double-double|double-double]]s in 65&nbsp;games played (52&nbsp;starts).<ref name=JHBR/><ref name=JH95GL>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/h/howarju01/gamelog/1995/|title=Juwan Howard 1994\u201395 Game Log|accessdate=May 20, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref>  He totalled 30&nbsp;points or more on three separate occasions.<ref name=JH95GL/>  The members of the team combined to miss a total of 317&nbsp;games due to injury,<ref name=CBFEOP/> and the team finished the season with a 21\u201361&nbsp;record.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/teams/WSB/1995.html|title=1994\u201395 Washington Bullets Roster and Statistics|accessdate=May 20, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of his rookie season Howard finished his undergraduate degree, and [[#Graduation|graduated from the University of Michigan]], becoming the first NBA player to graduate after leaving college early.\n\nIn the off-season, the {{NBA Year|1995|team=Washington Bullets|title=Bullets}} traded Chapman, MacLean and Duckworth,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/c/chapmre01.html|title=Rex Chapman|accessdate=May 19, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/m/macledo01.html|title=Don MacLean|accessdate=May 19, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/d/duckwke01.html|title=Kevin Duckworth|accessdate=May 19, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref> and drafted [[Rasheed Wallace]] in the [[1995 NBA draft]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/w/wallara01.html|title=Rasheed Wallace|accessdate=May 19, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref> In the preseason, the Bullets played the [[Detroit Pistons]] in an October game at the University of Michigan's [[Crisler Arena]], marking a homecoming for Howard. Webber was sidelined with a shoulder injury and missed the homecoming.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1995-10-26/sports/1995299094_1_juwan-howard-bullets-homecoming|title=At Michigan, Howard savors a fabulous homecoming Bullets forward remains a big man on campus|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=October 26, 1995|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|author=Bembry, Jerry}}</ref> Prior to the [[1995\u201396 NBA season|1995\u201396 season]], the Bullets were expected to be a contender with Webber, Howard, Muresan, [[Mark Price]], and [[Robert Pack (basketball)|Robert Pack]]. However, Webber, Price and Pack missed almost the entire year (65, 75 and 51&nbsp;games respectively) because of injuries.<ref name=CBFEOP>{{cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost/access/22093080.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&date=Apr+21%2C+1996&author=J.A.+Adande&pub=The+Washington+Post+%28pre-1997+Fulltext%29&edition=&startpage=D.01&desc=Caps%2C+Bullets+Feel+Each+Other%27s+Pain%3B+Injuries+Story+of+Their+Seasons|title=Caps, Bullets Feel Each Other's Pain; Injuries Story of Their Seasons|accessdate=May 20, 2010|date=April 21, 1996|work=[[The Washington Post]]|author=Adande, J. A.|page=D01}}</ref>  In February, the [[New York Knicks]] made two trades that put them in position to bid on Howard in the 1996 free agent market.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/02/20/sports/basketball-howard-hopes-knicks-wish.html|title=Basketball;Howard Hopes, Knicks Wish|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=February 20, 1996|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> Since Falk was the agent for both [[Patrick Ewing]] and Howard, sportswriter [[Dave Anderson (sportswriter)|Dave Anderson]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' felt the Knicks would have a good chance at Howard in July when the free agent market began.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/05/23/sports/sports-of-the-times-will-ewing-help-knicks-get-howard.html|title=Sports Of The Times;Will Ewing Help Knicks Get Howard?|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=May 23, 1996|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Anderson, Dave}}</ref>\n\nHoward earned his only career [[NBA All-Star Game]] selection for the February 11, [[1996 NBA All-Star Game|1996 game]].<ref name=JHBR/> A ''Sports Illustrated'' story showed examples of him dominating games at will during that season.<ref name=CU/> Howard also made news that season for his theatrics after being ejected from a February 27 game against the [[Charlotte Hornets]]. He kicked a water cooler across the court and was fined $5,000 for making an obscene gesture.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/02/28/sports/sports-people-pro-basketball-a-costly-gesture-by-bullets-howard.html|title=Sports People: Pro Basketball; A Costly Gesture by Bullets' Howard|accessdate=May 20, 2010|date=February 28, 1996|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref>  He concluded the season by scoring at least 20&nbsp;points in his last 16&nbsp;games.<ref name=JH96GL/>  Howard became just the second player in Washington franchise history, after [[Bernard King]], to post back-to-back 40-point games (against [[1995\u201396 Boston Celtics season|Boston]] on April 17, 1996, with 40, and at [[1995\u201396 Toronto Raptors season|Toronto]] on April 19, 1996, with 42).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/scores96/96108/96108391.htm|title=Celtics vs. Bullets|accessdate=May 20, 2010|date=April 17, 1996|work=[[USA Today]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/scores96/96110/96110397.htm|title=Bullets vs. Raptors|accessdate=May 20, 2010|date=April 19, 1996|work=[[USA Today]]}}</ref>  The 42&nbsp;points proved to be his career high.<ref name=JHNBASTATS>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/playerfile/juwan_howard/career_stats.html|title=Players: Juwan Howard (Career Stats and Totals)|accessdate=May 20, 2010|publisher=National Basketball Association|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100507112502/http://www.nba.com/playerfile/juwan_howard/career_stats.html|archivedate=May 7, 2010}}</ref> His strong finish earned him an NBA Player of the Month award for April.<ref name=JHNBABIO/> In spite of the injuries to key teammates, 1995\u201396 was Howard's best season, statistically. During the season, he finished third in the NBA in minutes played, 6th in points scored and 10th in points per game (22.1).<ref name=JHBR/> He was the Bullets' leading scorer.<ref name=BaHdHwfa>{{cite web|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1996-08-09/sports/1996222088_1_juwan-howard-miami-heat-arbitration|title=Bullets await Howard decision Heat will force arbitration: no date set for hearing|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=August 9, 1996|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|author=Goldstein, Alan}}</ref> Over the course of the season, he accumulated 22&nbsp;double-doubles in 81&nbsp;games, including 6 in his last 8&nbsp;games.<ref name=JH96GL>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/h/howarju01/gamelog/1996/|title=Juwan Howard 1995\u201396 Game Log|accessdate=May 20, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref>  At the end of the season, he was named to the [[All-NBA]] team.<ref name=JHBR/>  In addition to his two 40-point performances, he posted 3 additional 30-point performances and scored at least 20&nbsp;points in 56 of 81&nbsp;games.<ref name=JH96GL/>  Averaging 22.1&nbsp;points, 8.1&nbsp;rebounds and 4.4&nbsp;assists,<ref name=JHNBASTATS/>  he helped the Bullets record 39&nbsp;victories.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/teams/WSB/1996.html|title=1995\u201396 Washington Bullets Roster and Statistics|accessdate=May 20, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref> This was not enough for the Bullets to make the playoffs during their ninth consecutive losing season.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost/access/22093004.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&date=Apr+21%2C+1996&author=Richard+Justice&pub=The+Washington+Post+%28pre-1997+Fulltext%29&edition=&startpage=D.10&desc=Howard+to+Bullets%3A+%60It%27s+My+Turn%27|title=Howard to Bullets: 'It's My Turn'|accessdate=May 20, 2010|date=April 21, 1996|work=[[The Washington Post]]|author=Justice, Richard|page=D10}}</ref>\n\nAfter averaging 17&nbsp;points per game as a rookie and more than 22&nbsp;per game in his second season, Howard became a free agent when the Bullets made some salary cap transactions. The Bullets offered Howard an $89&nbsp;million contract, but the [[Miami Heat]] outbid them with a seven-year deal estimated to be worth  $98 to $101&nbsp;million. However, according to the NBA league office, the Heat miscalculated their available salary under the [[salary cap]] by excluding performance bonuses for [[Tim Hardaway]] and [[P. J. Brown]] and failing to account for the impact of renegotiating [[Alonzo Mourning]]'s contract before coming to terms with Howard.<ref name=NRHD/> The league rejected the contract on July 31 because Howard's $9&nbsp;million for the [[1996\u201397 NBA season|1996\u201397 season]] placed the Heat over the cap.<ref name=NRHD>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/08/01/sports/nba-rejects-howard-deal.html|title=N.B.A. Rejects Howard Deal|accessdate=May 20, 2010|date=August 1, 1996|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref><ref name=HATRtB>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/08/05/sports/howard-attempting-to-return-to-bullets.html|title=Howard Attempting To Return to Bullets|accessdate=May 20, 2010|date=August 5, 1996|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> Howard then re-signed with the Bullets on August 5. He became the first player in NBA history to sign a contract worth more than $100&nbsp;million;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://athletes-celebrities.tseworld.com/sports/basketball/juwan-howard.php|title=Juwan Howard|accessdate=May 21, 2010|publisher=Premiere Global Sports|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717111947/http://athletes-celebrities.tseworld.com/sports/basketball/juwan-howard.php#|archive-date=July 17, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.truthaboutit.net/2010/04/cardboard-bullets-juwan-howard-the-original-100-million-man.html|title=Cardboard Bullets: Juwan Howard, the original $100 million man|accessdate=May 21, 2010|date=April 28, 2010|author=Weidie, Kyle|publisher=Truth About It}}</ref> his seven-year contract was worth $105&nbsp;million. The league ruled on August 5 that the Bullets could re-sign Howard after having renounced his rights on July 15 to free up cap room to sign [[Tracy Murray]] and [[Lorenzo Williams (basketball, born 1969)|Lorenzo Williams]] if they forfeited their [[1997 NBA draft]] first-round selection rights.<ref name=H2D2T2M>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/08/06/sports/howard-2-deals-2-teams-200-million.html|title=Howard: 2 Deals, 2 Teams, $200 Million|accessdate=May 20, 2010|date=August 6, 1996|author=Brown, Clifton|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> The Bullets were not limited by the cap because they were re-signing their own player.<ref name=HATRtB/> The Heat pursued legal remedy in Florida state courts, seeking acknowledgment of the prior validity and superiority of their earlier contract.<ref name=H2D2T2M/>  Although an arbitration case involving the two contracts that Howard had signed appeared likely, [[ESPN]] reported that the Heat dropped their legal pursuit of Howard.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/08/07/sports/where-will-howard-play-next-season.html|title=Where Will Howard Play Next Season?|accessdate=May 20, 2010|date=August 7, 1996|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> The league moved for federal jurisdiction although the case remained on the docket for [[New York University]] law professor Daniel Collins to serve as arbitrator on three issues: \"1.) Did the Heat circumvent the cap in first signing Mourning?; 2.) Did the Heat miscalculate bonus money for forward P. J. Brown and guard Tim Hardaway that was not counted correctly against the cap.?; 3.) Did the Heat add an illegal performance clause to Brown's contract?.\" Meanwhile, the Heat's contract was protected by a [[temporary injunction]] in Florida state court, which forbade any newer contract by Howard from abrogating his Miami contract.<ref name=BaHdHwfa/> The Heat eventually dropped their case but the team, especially head coach [[Pat Riley]], continued to vehemently claim that their case of wrongdoing in the form of erroneous rulings by the league had been very solid.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/08/13/sports/an-angry-pat-riley-insists-the-heat-broke-no-salary-cap-rules.html|title=An Angry Pat Riley Insists the Heat Broke No Salary Cap Rules|accessdate=May 1, 2013|date=August 13, 1996|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Brown, Clifton}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/08/15/sports/hoop-it-up-free-agents-costly-errors.html|title=Hoop It Up: Free Agents, Costly Errors|accessdate=May 1, 2013|date=August 15, 1996|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Brown, Clifton}}</ref> If the Heat had pursued arbitration and had been found guilty of violating the salary cap, the team could have been fined $5&nbsp;million and Heat coach Riley could have been suspended for the season. By dropping their actions, the Heat avoided any possible penalties.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/08/11/sports/howard-will-remain-a-bullet-after-all.html|title=Howard Will Remain a Bullet, After All|accessdate=May 20, 2010|date=August 11, 1996|author=Brown, Clifton|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref>  In addition to signing free agents Murray and Williams, the Bullets traded for [[Rod Strickland]] and [[Harvey Grant]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/11/10/sports/bullets-open-up-their-gifts-and-run.html|title=Bullets Open Up Their Gifts and Run|accessdate=May 21, 2010|date=November 10, 1996|author=Brown, Clifton|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref>\n\nAs a statement against gun violence, Bullets owner [[Abe Pollin]] sought to change the franchise's name.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/dcsportsbog/2010/02/why_abe_pollin_went_from_bulle.html|title=Why Abe Pollin went from Bullets to Wizards|accessdate=July 12, 2012|date=February 2, 2010|author=Steinberg, Dan|work=[[The Washington Post]]}}</ref> The Bullets became the {{NBA Year|1996|team=Washington Wizards|title=Washington Wizards}} after asking fans to vote on the name.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/02/23/sports/sports-people-pro-basketball-bullets-will-be-wizards.html|title=Sports People: Pro Basketball;Bullets Will Be Wizards|accessdate=May 21, 2010|date=February 23, 1996|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> Although before the [[1996\u201397 NBA season]] the Bullets/Wizards were expected to make the playoffs with Webber, Howard, and Strickland, there were rumors that Webber had difficulty adjusting to being a less important part of the offensive game plan in the presence of All-Star Howard.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1996-10-31/sports/1996305024_1_chris-webber-webber-award-juwan-howard|title=Injuries a sore spot for Webber Limited past 2 years, forward eager to reap benefits of hard work|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=October 31, 1996|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|author=Bembry, Jerry }}</ref> Howard was plagued with [[shin splints]], causing him to miss several preseason games.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1996-10-20/sports/1996294078_1_bullets-juwan-howard-murray|title=Bullets' Murray takes step up on home turf Ex-UCLA star scores 22 to beat 76ers, 119\u2013104|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=October 20, 1996|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|author=Bembry, Jerry }}</ref> On November 11, 1996, Howard failed a sobriety test when he was caught [[speeding]] and was charged with [[driving while intoxicated]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1996-11-12/sports/1996317060_1_howard-foundation-juwan-howard-bullets|title=Howard apologizes after DWI arrest Bullets All-Star due in court Dec. 6|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=November 12, 1996|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|author=Bembry, Jerry }}</ref> The following month he pleaded not guilty and committed to enter an alcohol rehabilitation and education program.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.apnewsarchive.com/1996/Howard-Pleads-Not-Guilty-Enters-Alcohol-Education-Program/id-170f198c08cee08b4b1f7bf70617ebee|title=Howard Pleads Not Guilty, Enters Alcohol Education Program|accessdate=March 12, 2013|date=December 3, 1996|agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref> After Lynam coached the Bullets to a 22\u201324 record, he was fired and the Bullets hired [[Bernie Bickerstaff]], who posted a 22\u201313 record.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/teams/WSB/1997.html|title=1996\u201397 Washington Bullets Roster and Statistics|accessdate=May 21, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref>  Over the course of the 1996\u201397 season, Howard accumulated 24&nbsp;double&nbsp;doubles in 82&nbsp;games,<ref name=JH97GL>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/h/howarju01/gamelog/1997/|title=Juwan Howard 1996\u201397 Game Log|accessdate=May 20, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref> while averaging 19.1&nbsp;points and 8.1&nbsp;rebounds.<ref name=JHNBASTATS/> Although Howard averaged over 19&nbsp;points per game and played all 82&nbsp;games,<ref name=JHNBASTATS/> he only scored 30 or more points twice during the regular season.<ref name=JH97GL/>   The team finished its regular season with a 44\u201338 record but was swept in three games in the [[Eastern Conference (NBA)|Eastern Conference]] first round by the [[1996\u201397 Chicago Bulls season|Chicago Bulls]], who went on to win their second consecutive NBA championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/teams/WSB/1997.html|title=1996\u201397 Washington Bullets Roster and Statistics|accessdate=May 20, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref> The [[1997 NBA Playoffs]] were Howard's only NBA playoff appearance in his six-plus seasons with the Washington franchise, and he averaged 18.7&nbsp;points and 6&nbsp;rebounds while playing 43&nbsp;minutes per game.<ref name=JHNBASTATS/> The playoff appearance marked the franchise's first playoff appearance since the [[1988 NBA Playoffs]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1997-04-26/sports/7901011233_1_chicago-bulls-bullets-webber|title=Bulls Strike First, 98\u201386: Jordan, Playoff Savvy Get 1\u20130 Lead On Bullets As Webber Struggles|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=April 26, 1997|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]}}</ref>\n\nThe {{NBA Year|1997|team=Washington Wizards|title=Wizards}} relocated from the [[US Airways Arena (Washington, D.C.)|US Airways Arena]] to the [[MCI Center]] for the  [[1997\u201398 NBA season|1997\u201398 season]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/11/30/sports/nba-last-night-wizards-farewell-party-is-ruined-by-the-bulls.html|title=N.B.A: Last Night; Wizards' Farewell Party Is Ruined by the Bulls|accessdate=May 21, 2010|date=November 30, 1997|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> during which Howard totaled 11&nbsp;double-doubles in 64&nbsp;games,<ref name=JH98GL>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/h/howarju01/gamelog/1998/|title=Juwan Howard 1997\u201398 Game Log|accessdate=May 20, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref> while averaging 18.5&nbsp;points and 8.0&nbsp;rebounds.<ref name=JHNBASTATS/>  He scored between 20 and 29 points 31 times that season but failed to score 30&nbsp;points in any game.<ref name=JH98GL/>  Howard injured his ankle and was unable to play between February 5 and March 17.<ref name=JH98GL/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1998-02-22/sports/9802220216_1_bulls-washington-coach-bernie-bickerstaff-webber-and-howard|title=Bulls 94, Wizards 88: The Wiz End Up As A Fizz: Clinton On Hand For Latest Defeat|accessdate=May 21, 2010|date=February 22, 1998|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Armour, Terry}}</ref>  During Bickerstaff's only full season as the Washington coach, the team posted a 42\u201340 record.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/teams/WAS/1998.html|title=1997\u201398 Washington Wizards Roster and Statistics|accessdate=May 21, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref>\n\nOn April 6, 1998, Melissa Reed filed a sexual assault complaint against Howard and Webber after a party at Howard's house. Lawyers for both offered different accounts.  Howard's lawyer said that Reed had initiated an unspecified consensual sex act with one of the men, but Reed, who could not afford a lawyer,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.apnewsarchive.com/1998/Wizards-Howard-Wins-Lawsuit/id-b3c0158a21aa80d7623631219fd0188b|title=Wizards' Howard Wins Lawsuit|accessdate=July 12, 2012|date=November 12, 1998|agency=Associated Press|author=Zuckerbrod, Nancy}}</ref> claimed to have entered a room with Webber before being struck and restrained prior to being sexually assaulted.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/basketball/nba/news/1998/09/18/howard_suit/|title=Wizards' Howard moves ahead with lawsuit against accuser|accessdate=July 12, 2012|date=September 18, 1998|work=[[CNN Sports Illustrated]]}}</ref> Neither Howard nor Webber testified in the case, and although the accuser and approximately 40 of the party attendees appeared before a grand jury, the [[Montgomery County, Maryland|Montgomery County]] [[State's Attorney]] announced that prosecution was not warranted and closed the case in May.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/05/22/sports/nba-last-night-webber-and-howard-case-closed.html|title=N.B.A.: Last Night; Webber And Howard Case Closed|accessdate=May 20, 2010|date=May 22, 1996|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> This came just after the Wizards' general manager [[Wes Unseld]] separated Webber and Howard on May 15 by trading Webber to the [[Sacramento Kings]], receiving [[Mitch Richmond]] and [[Otis Thorpe]] in exchange.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/05/15/sports/nba-webber-traded-to-sacramento.html|title=N.B.A.; Webber Traded to Sacramento|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=May 15, 1996|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref>  In June, Howard filed suit against Reed, seeking compensation for emotional distress for damage to his reputation and image.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/06/27/sports/plus-in-the-news-howard-sues-his-accuser.html|title=Ps: In The News; Howard Sues His Accuser|accessdate=May 20, 2010|date=June 27, 1996|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref>  The accuser was absent during the proceeding and failed to respond to the lawsuit for [[defamation]]. In November, Howard was awarded the $1 in [[compensatory damages]] that he sought to clear his name and $100,000 in [[punitive damages]] plus legal costs.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/11/13/sports/nba-roundup-wizards-court-awards-100000-to-howard.html|title=N.B.A: Roundup \u2013 Wizards; Court Awards $100,000 to Howard|accessdate=May 20, 2010|date=November 13, 1996|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref>\n\nAfter the [[1998\u201399 NBA lockout]], the {{NBA Year|1998|team=Washington Wizards|title=Wizards}} posted an 18\u201332 record in the shortened season. The team started out 13\u201319 under Bickerstaff and was 5\u201313 under [[Jim Brovelli]] after Bickerstaff was fired.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/teams/WAS/1999.html|title=1998\u201399 Washington Wizards Roster and Statistics|accessdate=May 21, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref>  Howard was a vocal critic of Bickerstaff throughout his tenure, stating the coach was unable to make proper in-game adjustments.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1999-04-08/sports/9904080312_1_all-stars-timeouts-bernie-bickerstaff|title=Bickerstaff Firing Shows Equality Thrives In Nba|accessdate=May 21, 2010|date=April 8, 1999|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Smith, Sam}}</ref> Howard, who again had an ankle injury,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1999-04-17/sports/9904170247_1_wizards-opponent-mci-center-washington-wizards|title=Bulls End Misery (for Washington): Wizards Look Miraculously Healed|accessdate=May 21, 2010|date=April 17, 1999|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Armour, Terry}}</ref> missed the last 14&nbsp;games of the season. Over the course of the [[1998\u201399 NBA season|1998\u201399 season]], he posted 11&nbsp;double-doubles and two 15-rebound performances in 36&nbsp;games,<ref name=JH99GL>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/h/howarju01/gamelog/1999/|title=Juwan Howard 1998\u201399 Game Log|accessdate=May 20, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref> while averaging 18.9&nbsp;points and 7.0&nbsp;rebounds.<ref name=JHNBASTATS/>\n\nDuring the [[1999\u20132000 NBA season|1999\u20132000 season]], Howard accumulated 10&nbsp;double-doubles in 82&nbsp;games,<ref name=JH00GL>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/h/howarju01/gamelog/2000/|title=Juwan Howard 1999\u20132000 Game Log|accessdate=May 20, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref> while averaging 14.9&nbsp;points and 8.1&nbsp;rebounds.<ref name=JHNBASTATS/>  The {{NBA Year|1999|team=Washington Wizards|title=Wizards}} endured a 14\u201330 start under head coach [[Gar Heard]] before going 15\u201323 under Heard's replacement, [[Darrell Walker]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/teams/WAS/2000.html|title=1999\u201300 Washington Wizards Roster and Statistics|accessdate=May 21, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref>  According to [[Sam Smith (sportswriter)|Sam Smith]] from the ''Chicago Tribune'', Howard had become unpopular and a bit of a disappointment by his sixth season in Washington.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2000-01-07/sports/0001070183_1_juwan-howard-biggest-loser-million-contract-howard|title=Big Money Turns Howard Into Big Loser|accessdate=May 22, 2010|date=January 7, 2000|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Smith, Sam}}</ref>  He posted 30&nbsp;points twice,<ref name=JH00GL/> including a season-high 36 in a fourth-quarter comeback to end a five-game losing streak in January.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2000-01-22/sports/0001220154_1_juwan-howard-washington-wizards-indiana|title=Jordan Misses Wizards' Rally As Howard Helps Beat Pacers|accessdate=May 22, 2010|date=January 22, 2000|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]}}</ref> During the offseason, Howard's name surfaced in trade rumors that had him going to the New York Knicks in exchange for Ewing because the Wizards' management thought that the trade would better position the team for the 2001 free agent market.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/08/31/sports/pro-basketball-ewing-for-howard-is-latest-talk.html|title=Pro Basketball; Ewing for Howard Is Latest Talk|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=August 31, 2009|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Broussard, Chris}}</ref> Following the season, Walker was replaced by [[Leonard Hamilton]], becoming the team's sixth head coach since last making the [[NBA Playoffs]] four years earlier.<ref name=WboHac/>\n\nAlthough it had been five years since his only All-Star appearance, Howard was the fourth-highest-paid player in the NBA during the [[2000\u201301 NBA season|2000\u201301 season]], behind [[Kevin Garnett]], [[Shaquille O'Neal]] and Mourning.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2000-11-24/sports/0011240346_1_overpaid-patrick-ewing-scottie-pippen|title=The Nba's Top 20 Salaries|accessdate=May 22, 2010|date=November 24, 2000|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Smith, Sam}}</ref> Howard, along with Strickland and Richmond, were marquee names on the team under contract to earn at least $10 million.<ref name=WboHac>{{cite news|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2000-06-15/sports/0006150103_1_wizards-hamilton-college-coaches|title=Wizards bring on Hamilton as coach: Deal believed to be $10 million, 5 seasons Pro Basketball|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=June 15, 2000|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|author=Ewell, Christian}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2000-10-12/sports/0010120082_1_wizards-hamilton-juwan-howard|title=Questions hang in air as Wizards exit camp: But nothing's new about No. 1: How to turn around loser?|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=October 12, 2000|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|author=Kent, Milton}}</ref> On December 31, 2000, Howard, posted his career high of 15&nbsp;made&nbsp;free&nbsp;throws in a game against the {{NBA Year|2000|team=Detroit Pistons|title=Detroit Pistons}}.<ref name=JHNBASTATS/> Despite the fact that the February 11, [[2001 NBA All-Star Game]] was hosted by Washington at the MCI Center, Howard was not included on the Eastern Conference team even when it had to make two late additions ([[Anthony Mason (basketball)|Anthony Mason]] and [[Latrell Sprewell]]). According to Milton Kent of ''The Baltimore Sun'', not only did Howard's statistics (approximately 18 points, 7 rebounds and 2.8 assists) compare favorably to both players, but his role as his team's primary scoring option made his statistics more significant than those of Mason and Sprewell.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2001-02-04/sports/0102040234_1_juwan-howard-wizards-signed-howard|title=Howard merits nod as All-Star: Pro Basketball|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=February 4, 2001|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|author=Kent, Milton}}</ref>\n\n===Dallas Mavericks (2001\u20132002)===\nJordan, who had become the Wizards' head of basketball operations the prior season, traded Howard, [[Obinna Ekezie]], and [[Calvin Booth]] to the {{NBA Year|2000|team=Dallas Mavericks|title=Dallas Mavericks}} for Laettner, [[Loy Vaught]], [[Etan Thomas]], [[Hubert Davis]], [[Courtney Alexander]] and $3&nbsp;million on February 22, 2001, at the NBA trade deadline.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2001-02-23/sports/0102230352_1_bulls-trading-nba-finals|title=Mutombo Deal Highlights Busy Day: Sixers Swap Ratliff, Kukoc To Hawks Bulls Remain Quiet|accessdate=May 22, 2010|date=February 23, 2001|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Smith, Sam}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/02/23/sports/pro-basketball-76ers-hope-mutombo-will-deliver-the-title.html|title=Pro Basketball; 76ers Hope Mutombo Will Deliver the Title|accessdate=May 22, 2010|date=February 23, 2001|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Wise, Mike}}</ref>  Jordan's move was praised for freeing up salary cap space in advance of the NBA's first season with a luxury tax.<ref name=PBNTTTFaBT>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/02/25/sports/pro-basketball-notebook-trading-talent-today-for-a-better-tomorrow.html|title=Pro Basketball; Notebook; Trading Talent Today For a Better Tomorrow|accessdate=May 22, 2010|date=February 25, 2001|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Wise, Mike}}</ref> The trade served the Mavericks by giving them a new offensive weapon and enabling them to match up defensively against the [[NBA Western Conference]] power forwards such as Wallace, [[Tim Duncan]], [[Karl Malone]] and Webber.<ref name=PBNTTTFaBT/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/02/23/sports/pro-basketball-76ers-hope-mutombo-will-deliver-the-title.html|title=Pro Basketball; 76ers Hope Mutombo Will Deliver the Title|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=February 23, 2001|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Wise, Mike}}</ref> Washington finished the year with a 19\u201363 record under coach Hamilton.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/teams/WAS/2001.html|title=2000\u201301 Washington Wizards Roster and Statistics|accessdate=May 21, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 2000\u201301 season, the Mavericks finished 53\u201329 under coach [[Don Nelson]].<ref name=01MAVS>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/teams/DAL/2001.html|title=2000\u201301 Dallas Mavericks Roster and Statistics|accessdate=May 21, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref>  Howard provided the Mavericks with a back-to-the-basket player who moved into the starting power-forward position, enabling [[Dirk Nowitzki]] to play small forward and [[Shawn Bradley]] to play center.<ref name=PBMHHSoS/> During the season, Howard tallied 16&nbsp;double-doubles and five 30-point performances in 81&nbsp;games,<ref name=JH01GL>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/h/howarju01/gamelog/2001/|title=Juwan Howard 2000\u201301 Game Log|accessdate=May 22, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref> while averaging 18.0&nbsp;points and 7.1&nbsp;rebounds.<ref name=JHNBASTATS/>  On a team with All-Star [[Michael Finley]] and future MVPs [[Steve Nash]] and Nowitzki, Howard was the highest-paid player.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/dallas/mavericks/post/_/id/4669018/50-for-10-new-unis-new-tude-in-2001-02|title=50 for 10: New unis, new 'tude in 2001\u201302|accessdate=May 21, 2010|date=May 10, 2010|author=Caplan, Jeff|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref>  On March 20, Howard blocked five shots, his career high, against the {{NBA Year|2000|team=Portland Trail Blazers|title=Portland Trail Blazers}}.<ref name=JHNBASTATS/>  In the [[2001 NBA Playoffs]], the Mavericks advanced past the {{NBA Year|2000|team=Utah Jazz|title=Utah Jazz}} 3 games to 2 before losing to the {{NBA Year|2000|team=San Antonio Spurs|title=San Antonio Spurs}}, 4 games to 1.<ref name=01MAVS/> The Utah games marked the first time Howard played for a team that won an NBA playoff series.<ref name=JHBR/> In the first game of the series against the Spurs, Howard slammed Spurs guard [[Derek Anderson (basketball)|Derek Anderson]] to the floor while trying to block Anderson's layup late in the game.<ref name=AndersonInjury>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/nba/01playoffs/confsemis/2001-05-05-spurs-mavs-game-1.htm|title=Spurs roll to Game 1 victory, but it's costly|last=Koidin|first=Michelle|work=[[USA Today]]|accessdate=July 14, 2010 | date=May 5, 2001}}</ref> Anderson suffered a separated shoulder on the play, and Howard received a flagrant foul and was ejected.<ref name=AndersonInjury /> After the game, Howard, Spurs coach [[Gregg Popovich]], and Mavs owner [[Mark Cuban]] all said the foul was committed without malice or intent to injure Anderson.<ref name=AndersonInjury /> In the Mavericks' 10 playoff games, Howard totaled three double-doubles while averaging 13.4&nbsp;points and 8.3&nbsp;rebounds in 39.1&nbsp;minutes.<ref name=JHBR/><ref name=JH01GL/>\n\nDuring the [[2001\u201302 NBA season|2001\u201302 season]], he posted 17&nbsp;double-doubles and three 30-point performances in 81&nbsp;games (72&nbsp;starts),<ref name=JH02GL>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/h/howarju01/gamelog/2002/|title=Juwan Howard 2001\u201302 Game Log|accessdate=May 22, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref> while averaging 14.6&nbsp;points and 7.6&nbsp;rebounds.<ref name=JHBR/>  This was the first time since his rookie holdout season that he did not start every game he played in.<ref name=JHBR/>  All reserve appearances occurred between November 21 and December 11, and eight of them were in consecutive games between November 21 and December 5.<ref name=JH02GL/> On January 31, he posted a career-high 16&nbsp;rebounds against the {{NBA Year|2001|team=Houston Rockets|title=Houston Rockets}}.<ref name=JHNBASTATS/>\n\n===Denver Nuggets (2002\u20132003)===\nThe Mavericks traded him with [[Donnell Harvey]], Hardaway and a 2002 first-round pick to the {{NBA Year|2001|team=Denver Nuggets|title=Denver Nuggets}} for [[Raef LaFrentz]], [[Avery Johnson]], Van Exel and [[Tariq Abdul-Wahad]] on February 21, 2002.<ref name=JHBR/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2002-02-22/sports/0202220344_1_frontier-league-contract-international-league|title=Baseball Major League Baseball MLB: Named Bob&nbsp;... |accessdate=May 24, 2010|date=February 22, 2002|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]}}</ref>  At the time of the trade, Howard was considered the Mavericks' best low-post defender.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2002-02-25/sports/0202250183_1_mavs-nick-van-exel-los-angeles-lakers|title=Little 'D' in Big D is OK|accessdate=May 24, 2010|date=February 25, 2002|author=Smith, Sam|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]}}</ref> On March 25, 2002, he scored his 10,000th&nbsp;career point at [[Madison Square Garden]] against the [[2001\u201302 New York Knicks season|New York Knicks]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/playerfile/juwan_howard/career_statistics.html?nav=TextNavBar|title=Juwan Howard-5|accessdate=June 12, 2012|publisher=National Basketball Association|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140910063823/http://www.nba.com/playerfile/juwan_howard/career_statistics.html?nav=TextNavBar|archivedate=September 10, 2014}}</ref> Howard started all 28&nbsp;games that he played for the Nuggets.<ref name=JH02GL/> Don Nelson's Mavericks went to the second round of the [[2002 NBA Playoffs]] after trading Howard,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/teams/DAL/2002.html|title=2001\u201302 Dallas Mavericks Roster and Statistics|accessdate=May 24, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref> while the Nuggets failed to make the playoffs under coaches [[Dan Issel]] and [[Mike Evans (basketball)|Mike Evans]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/teams/DEN/2002.html|title=2001\u201302 Denver Nuggets Roster and Statistics|accessdate=May 24, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref> By the end of the season, Nuggets general manager Vandeweghe had cleared almost $20 million of salary cap space, leaving the team with few veterans and only Howard and [[Marcus Camby]] as well-known players. This made the team an undesirable coaching assignment for veteran coaches.<ref name=Accim/> In the offseason, the Nuggets replaced Evans with the relatively unknown [[Jeff Bzdelik]].<ref name=Accim>{{cite web|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2003-02-01/sports/0302010045_1_jeff-bzdelik-denver-nuggets-umbc|title=At center court, invisible man: NBA: Jeff Bzdelik's coaching career has taken him from UMBC to the Denver Nuggets, but one thing hasn't changed: his obscurity.|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=February 1, 2003|author=Markus, Don|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]}}</ref>\n\nDuring a preseason game, Howard attempted to punch [[Al Harrington]] and [[Jermaine O'Neal]], which earned him a suspension on October 25, 2002. As a result, Howard missed the {{NBA Year|2002|team=Denver Nuggets|title=Nuggets}}' first two games of the regular season, and this cost him $458,000 in salary.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/10/26/sports/plus-pro-basketball-nuggets-howard-suspended-and-fined.html|title=Plus: Pro Basketball; Nuggets' Howard Suspended and Fined|accessdate=May 25, 2010|date=October 26, 2002|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> Howard first attempted to hit Harrington late in the fourth quarter on a night when Howard had missed nine of ten shots. When O'Neal intervened, the two pushed and shoved each other before Howard started punching again.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.upi.com/Sports_News/2002/10/25/Juwan-Howard-suspended-two-games/UPI-57721035590392/|title=Juwan Howard suspended two games|accessdate=June 12, 2012|date=October 25, 2002|agency=[[United Press International]]}}</ref> At around the same time, the University of Michigan basketball scandal investigation came to an end with many of the accomplishments of the Fab Five being rescinded through [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] sanctions.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/11/08/sports/sports-of-the-times-forgetting-the-fab-five-is-impossible.html|title=Sports of The Times; Forgetting The Fab Five Is Impossible|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=November 8, 2002|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Rhoden, William C.}}</ref> Although many of the records of the Fab Five were erased, Howard's and teammate Rose's 1994 All-American recognitions were unaffected by the scandal.<ref name=\"MB07-8p13-21\"/><ref name=MB07-8p154-5>{{cite book|title=2007\u201308 Men's Basketball Media Guide|publisher=University of Michigan|pages=144\u20135|year=2007}}</ref> During the [[2002\u201303 NBA season|2002\u201303 regular season]], he accumulated 18&nbsp;double-doubles, two 30-point performances, and three 15-rebound performances in 77&nbsp;games,<ref name=JH03GL>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/h/howarju01/gamelog/2003/|title=Juwan Howard 2002\u201303 Game Log|accessdate=May 24, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref> while averaging 18.4&nbsp;points and 7.6&nbsp;rebounds.<ref name=JHBR/> The 2002\u201303 Nuggets were 17\u201365 under Bzdelik.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/teams/DEN/2003.html|title=2002\u201303 Denver Nuggets Roster and Statistics|accessdate=May 24, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref> The team struggled with the league's lowest payroll and three rookies in the starting lineup.<ref name=Accim/>  Howard started all 77&nbsp;games in which he played.<ref name=JH03GL/>\n\n===Orlando Magic (2003\u20132004)===\nHoward signed what was believed to be a five-year, $28&nbsp;million contract as a free agent with the {{NBA Year|2003|team=Orlando Magic|title=Orlando Magic}} on July 16, 2003; he had been expected to sign with either Detroit or [[Minnesota Timberwolves|Minnesota]].<ref name=JHBR/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2003-07-14/sports/0307140234_1_juwan-howard-magic-play-in-orlando|title=Howard Set To Join Magic: Veteran Forward Juwan Howard Reached An Oral Agreement With Orlando For A Five-year Contract.|accessdate=June 12, 2012|date=July 13, 2003|work=[[Orlando Sentinel]]|author=Brewer, Jerry}}</ref> During the season, teammate [[Tracy McGrady]] successfully defended his [[List of National Basketball Association annual scoring leaders|scoring championship]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/playerfile/tracy_mcgrady/bio.html |title=Tracy McGrady |accessdate=March 3, 2013 |publisher=National Basketball Association |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130419063942/http://www.nba.com/playerfile/tracy_mcgrady/bio.html |archivedate=April 19, 2013 }}</ref> while Howard attempted to be a positive influence when the situation arose, such as when he attempted to stop McGrady from kicking the [[basketball (ball)|basketball]] into the stands twice in a row.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/sports/basketball/games/2004-02-21-magic-nuggets_x.htm|title=Magic put a spell on Nuggets in 102\u201398 win|accessdate=March 3, 2013|date=February 21, 2004|work=[[USA Today]]|author=Branom, Mike}}</ref> McGrady missed the last 10 games of the season with knee problems (ending his season on March 24),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/m/mcgratr01/gamelog/2004/|title=Tracy McGrady 2003\u201304 Game Log|accessdate=March 3, 2013|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref> leading to Howard's best performances of the season: Howard had 33 points and 11 rebounds on April 2 against the {{NBA Year|2003|team=Atlanta Hawks|title=Atlanta Hawks}},<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nba/recap?id=240402019|title=Atlanta 95, Orlando 87|accessdate=March 3, 2013|date=April 2, 2004|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> and he had 38 points on April 12 against the {{NBA Year|2003|team=Chicago Bulls|title=Chicago Bulls}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=240412004|title=Fizer has 30 points, 20 boards in loss|accessdate=March 3, 2013|date=April 12, 2004|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> Over the course of the [[2003\u201304 NBA season|2003\u201304 season]], he had 16&nbsp;double-doubles and two 30-point performances in 81&nbsp;games (77&nbsp;starts),<ref name=JH04GL>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/h/howarju01/gamelog/2004/|title=Juwan Howard 2003\u201304 Game Log|accessdate=May 24, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref> while averaging 17.2&nbsp;points and 7.1&nbsp;rebounds.<ref name=JHBR/>  The team compiled a 21\u201361 record, the worst in the NBA, under coaches [[Doc Rivers]] and [[Johnny Davis (basketball)|Johnny Davis]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/teams/ORL/2004.html|title=2003\u201304 Orlando Magic Roster and Statistics|accessdate=May 24, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/06/30/sports/pro-basketball-notebook-mcgrady-gets-wish-in-trade-to-rockets.html|title=Pro Basketball: Notebook; McGrady Gets Wish In Trade To Rockets|accessdate=May 25, 2010|date=June 30, 2004|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Broussard, Chris}}</ref>\n\n===Houston Rockets (2004\u201307)===\n{{multiple image\n| align     = right\n| direction = horizontal\n| header    = Howard as a [[Houston Rockets|Houston Rocket]]\n| header_align = left/right/center\n| header_background =\n| footer    = Right: Shooting over [[Antawn Jamison]] as [[Yao Ming]] looks on\n| footer_align = left/right/center\n| footer_background =\n| width     =\n| image1    = 20061210 Juwan Howard.jpg\n| width1    = 150\n| alt1      = a Black athlete who is leaning forward and gazing to the side\n| caption1  =\n| image2    = 20061210 Juwan Howard shooting over Antwan Jamison.jpg\n| width2    = 150\n| alt2      = a Black athlete is shooting a basketball over another Black athlete while an Asian athlete watches.\n| caption2  =\n}}\n\nOn June 29, 2004, Howard and Magic teammates McGrady, [[Tyronn Lue]] and [[Reece Gaines]] were part of a seven-player trade that sent {{NBA Year|2003|team=Houston Rockets|title=2003\u201304 Houston Rockets}} [[starting lineup|starting]] guards [[Steve Francis]] and [[Cuttino Mobley]], plus [[Kelvin Cato]], to the Magic.<ref name=JHBR/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/basketball/nba/2004-06-29-mcgrady-francis-deal_x.htm|title=McGrady-Francis swap official, finally|author=Denton, John Denton|date=June 30, 2004|accessdate=May 24, 2010|work=[[USA Today]]}}</ref> In late November, as a short term experiment,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chron.com/default/article/To-Van-Gundy-lack-of-praise-beats-feint-praise-1505420.php|title=To Van Gundy, lack of praise beats feint praise|accessdate=March 2, 2013|date=December 2, 2004|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|author=Feigan, Jonathan}}</ref> head coach  [[Jeff Van Gundy]] decided to reduce Howard's playing time so that [[Scott Padgett]] could move up in the rotation to backup power forward.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chron.com/default/article/Situation-has-Van-Gundy-Rockets-at-a-loss-1955540.php|title=Situation has Van Gundy, Rockets at a loss|accessdate=March 2, 2013|date=November 29, 2004|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|author=Feigan, Jonathan}}</ref> Meanwhile, [[Maurice Taylor]] started the first 16&nbsp;games of the season for the {{NBA Year|2004|team=Houston Rockets|title=Rockets}} at power forward.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/t/tayloma01/gamelog/2005/|title=Maurice Taylor 2004\u201305 Game Log|accessdate=May 26, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref>  Van Gundy was unsatisfied with his power forward rotation, so he made the first starting lineup change of the season not mandated by injury by putting Howard into the starting lineup ahead of Taylor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chron.com/default/article/Talk-with-Van-Gundy-brings-out-best-in-T-Mac-1516767.php|title=Talk with Van Gundy brings out best in T-Mac|accessdate=March 2, 2013|date=December 4, 2004|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|author=Feigan, Jonathan}}</ref> Although Taylor was available and played,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nba/boxscore?gameId=241202006|title=Rockets 106 (6\u201311, 4\u20136 away), Mavericks 113 (11\u20136, 6\u20133 home)|accessdate=May 26, 2010|date=December 2, 2004|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> Howard became the regular starter on December 2 and started for the rest of the season,<ref name=JH05GL/> and the team traded Taylor before the trade deadline in February.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/news/story?id=1998814|title=Knicks land Rose, Taylor, draft picks|accessdate=March 3, 2013|date=February 24, 2005|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref>\n\nThe 2004\u201305 Rockets were 51\u201331 under Van Gundy and lost in the first round of the [[2005 NBA Playoffs]] to the {{NBA Year|2004|team=Dallas Mavericks|title=Dallas Mavericks}}, four games to three.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/teams/HOU/2005.html|title=2004\u201305 Houston Rockets Roster and Statistics|accessdate=May 25, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref>  Although the Rockets made the playoffs, Howard's season ended on March 14, when he left a game with a sprained [[medial collateral ligament]] (MCL) in his right knee.<ref name=JH05GL/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2005-03-15/sports/0503150291_1_injury-report-tracy-mcgrady-rasheed-wallace|title=Nugget OK with benching|accessdate=May 25, 2010|date=March 15, 2005|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]}}</ref> Initially, the injury was supposed to sideline Howard for four weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chron.com/default/article/Howard-feels-lost-without-Rockets-1946051.php|title=Howard feels lost without Rockets|accessdate=March 2, 2013|date=March 17, 2005|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|author=Manfull, Megan}}</ref> The injury coincided with a period in which he developed symptoms of [[viral myocarditis]], including heart [[palpitation]]s, mild chest pains and fever and was diagnosed with a viral infection in his heart. His limited physical activity impaired his MCL rehabilitation.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2005-04-07/sports/0504070359_1_viral-infection-rockets-juwan-howard|title=Season over for Howard: Rockets forward shut down by viral infection in heart|accessdate=May 25, 2010|date=April 7, 2005|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]}}</ref> Over the course of the [[2004\u201305 NBA season|2004\u201305 season]], Howard achieved seven double-doubles in 61&nbsp;games (47&nbsp;starts),<ref name=JH05GL>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/h/howarju01/gamelog/2005/|title=Juwan Howard 2004\u201305 Game Log|accessdate=May 25, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref> while averaging 9.6&nbsp;points and 5.7&nbsp;rebounds.<ref name=JHBR/>  His 26.6&nbsp;minutes per game marked the first season that he played less than 32&nbsp;minutes per game.<ref name=JHBR/>\n\nDuring the [[2005\u201306 NBA season|2005\u201306 season]], Howard recorded 10&nbsp;double-doubles and two 30-point performances in 80&nbsp;games (all as a starter),<ref name=JH06GL>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/h/howarju01/gamelog/2006/|title=Juwan Howard 2005\u201306 Game Log|accessdate=May 25, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref> while averaging 11.8&nbsp;points and 6.7&nbsp;rebounds.<ref name=JHBR/>  He played 31.7&nbsp;minutes per game, and this was the last season in which he averaged 30&nbsp;minutes per game; this was also the final season in which Howard started at least half of the games in which he played.<ref name=JHBR/> The {{NBA Year|2005|team=Houston Rockets|title=Rockets}} were 34\u201348 under Van Gundy and missed the playoffs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/teams/HOU/2006.html|title=2005\u201306 Houston Rockets Roster and Statistics|accessdate=May 25, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref> Howard was suspended one game without pay in January for shoving the basketball into the face of Toronto guard [[Mike James (basketball, born 1975)|Mike James]] in an exchange that occurred after Howard fouled James on a drive to the basket.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2006-01-08/sports/0601080409_1_shoving-juwan-howard-rockets|title=NBA orders Howard to sit 1 game|accessdate=June 10, 2012|date=January 8, 2006|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]}}</ref> On April 10, [[Yao Ming]] suffered a season-ending broken foot.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chron.com/default/article/Broken-foot-ends-Yao-s-year-1864532.php|title=Broken foot ends Yao's year|accessdate=March 2, 2013|date=April 11, 2006|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|author=Feigen, Jonathan}}</ref> In Yao's absence, Howard posted a season-high 31 points on April 17 against the [[Denver Nuggets]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chron.com/default/article/Howard-shines-as-Rockets-edge-Nuggets-1657775.php|title=Howard shines as Rockets edge Nuggets|accessdate=March 2, 2013|date=April 17, 2006|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|author=Pells, Eddie}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2006\u201307 NBA season|2006\u201307 season]], Howard achieved nine double-doubles in 80&nbsp;games played (37&nbsp;starts),<ref name=JH07GL>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/h/howarju01/gamelog/2007/|title=Juwan Howard 2006\u201307 Game Log|accessdate=May 25, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref> while averaging 9.7&nbsp;points and 5.9&nbsp;rebounds.<ref name=RctrgJfH>{{cite web|url=http://www.chron.com/default/article/Rockets-close-to-re-acquiring-guard-James-for-1604258.php|title=Rockets close to re-acquiring guard James for Howard|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=June 13, 2007|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|author=Feigen, Jonathan}}</ref> During the season, he lost the starting power forward position to [[Chuck Hayes]], but got back in the starting lineup when Yao got injured.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chron.com/default/article/Rockets-complete-trade-to-bring-James-back-1793964.php|title=Rockets complete trade to bring James back|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=June 14, 2007|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|author=Elliot, Christopher}}</ref>  His 26.5&nbsp;minutes per game marked a new career low.<ref name=JHBR/> Howard only started 38 games,<ref name=RctrgJfH/> including 32 consecutive starts between December 26, 2006, and March 3, 2007,<ref name=JH07GL/> while center Yao was recovering from his fractured right leg.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/m/mingya01/gamelog/2007/|title=Yao Ming 2006\u201307 Game Log|accessdate=May 25, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chron.com/default/article/Rockets-rout-Nets-to-halt-two-game-skid-1868729.php|title=Rockets rout Nets to halt two-game skid: Battier makes career-high seven three-pointers, leads Rockets with 23 points|accessdate=June 17, 2012|date=December 27, 2006|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|author=Feigen, Jonathan}}</ref> The 2006\u201307 Rockets were 52\u201330 under Van Gundy for the regular season.<ref name=HOU07/> The Rockets entered the [[2007 NBA Playoffs]] with little experience; Howard was one of only three players on the team (along with [[Rafer Alston]] and [[Dikembe Mutombo]]) to have previously won any NBA playoff series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chron.com/default/article/Rockets-open-postseason-hungry-for-series-win-1844893.php|title=Rockets open postseason hungry for series win|accessdate=March 2, 2013|date=April 21, 2007|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|author=Feigen, Jonathan}}</ref> Once the playoffs began, Howard served as a key reserve on the Rockets' short bench rotation that also included [[Luther Head]] and Mutombo.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chron.com/default/article/ROCKETS-NOTES-Yao-says-team-lacked-intensity-1830685.php|title=Rockets Notes: Yao says team lacked intensity|accessdate=March 2, 2013|date=April 30, 2007|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|author1=Blinebury, Fran  |author2=Jonathan Feigen}}</ref> The Rockets managed to split the first 4 games even though Head and Howard only combined to average 7.6 points,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chron.com/default/article/Rockets-know-they-were-outworked-by-Jazz-1825653.php|title=Rockets know they were outworked by Jazz|accessdate=March 2, 2013|date=April 30, 2007|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|author=Feigen, Jonathan}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chron.com/default/article/NOTES-Rockets-guard-against-looking-ahead-1543958.php|title=Notes: Rockets guard against looking ahead|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=May 1, 2007|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|author=Feigen, Jonathan}}</ref> including a combined pointless 0-for-10 game three.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chron.com/default/article/Rockets-reserves-unable-to-give-starters-any-1611859.php|title=Rockets reserves unable to give starters any support|accessdate=March 2, 2013|date=April 27, 2007|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|author=Solomon, Jerome}}</ref> Although Howard had a productive game five with 12 points and 6 rebounds which contributed to a Rockets victory,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chron.com/default/article/Howard-Head-team-up-to-outscore-Jazz-reserves-1793701.php|title=Howard, Head team up to outscore Jazz reserves|accessdate=March 2, 2013|date=May 1, 2007|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|author=Solomon, Jerome}}</ref> the team lost in the first round of the 2007 playoffs to the {{NBA Year|2006|team=Utah Jazz|title=Utah Jazz}}, four games to three.<ref name=HOU07>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/teams/HOU/2007.html|title=2006\u201307 Houston Rockets Roster and Statistics|accessdate=May 25, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref>  In the playoffs, reserve Howard averaged 5.0&nbsp;points and 4.4&nbsp;rebounds in 22.4&nbsp;minutes.<ref name=JHBR/><ref name=JH07GL/> Although Howard was described as a consistent role player and locker-room leader,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chron.com/CDA/archives/archive.mpl?id=2007_4366410|title=James makes Rockets return / Alston will vie with childhood pal for point guard role; Howard heading to Timberwolves|accessdate=May 25, 2010|date=June 15, 2007|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|author=Elliott, Chris|page=13, sports section}}</ref> his salary continued to be perceived as outrageous by sportswriters such as the ''[[Houston Chronicle]]''{{'s}} Jerome Solomon.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chron.com/CDA/archives/archive.mpl?id=2007_4382516|title=No bones about it: Rockets being smart|accessdate=May 25, 2010|date=July 11, 2007|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|author=Solomon, Jerome|page=2, sports section|quote=Yes, the Rockets traded Juwan Howard and his ridiculous contract to bring Mike James back to his adopted home.}}</ref>\n\nOn June 14, 2007, Howard was traded to the [[2007\u201308 Minnesota Timberwolves season|Minnesota Timberwolves]] for James and [[Justin Reed]].<ref name=\"rocketstrade\">{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/news/story?id=2903593|title=Wolves, Rockets agree to Howard-James trade|author=Stein, Mark|publisher=[[ESPN]]|accessdate=May 25, 2010|date=June 14, 2007}}</ref>  According to ESPN, he regretted not choosing Minnesota the last time he had been a free agent and was looking forward to playing with Garnett.<ref name=\"noyouth\">{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/news/story?id=3086024|title=Wolves get younger with buyout of Howard's contract|publisher=[[ESPN]]|accessdate=May 25, 2010|date=October 29, 2007}}</ref>  Soon after Howard signed with Minnesota, the team traded Garnett to the [[2007\u201308 Boston Celtics season|Boston Celtics]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/g/garneke01.html|title=Kevin Garnett|accessdate=May 25, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref> Howard made it clear he was not interested in being on a team in Minnesota that was focused on developing young talent and consequently requested a trade once Garnett was no longer a member of the team.<ref name=\"noyouth\" /><ref>{{cite web|author=Zgoda, Jerry|url=http://www.startribune.com/sports/wolves/11695546.html?elr=KArksUUUoDEy3LGDiO7aiU|title=Juwan Howard: A reluctant \u2013 but respectful \u2013 Wolf: Juwan Howard would like to be traded. But if the Wolves can't make a deal, the veteran will be a mentor to his young teammates|work=[[Star Tribune]]|accessdate=October 8, 2010|date=September 28, 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121013124622/http://www.startribune.com/sports/wolves/11695546.html?elr=KArksUUUoDEy3LGDiO7aiU|archivedate=October 13, 2012}}</ref>  Howard still had $6.88&nbsp;million and $7.38&nbsp;million in salary owed to him over the next two seasons, which made him difficult to trade.<ref name=\"noyouth\"/> Timberwolves owner [[Glen Taylor]] noted that the team would attempt to accommodate his wishes but acknowledged that doing so would be difficult.<ref>{{cite news|title=Wolves Trying To Trade Howard|work=[[St. Paul Pioneer Press]]|date=August 23, 2007|page=D2}}</ref> On October 29, 2007, the Timberwolves [[NBA Salary Cap#Waivers|waived]] Howard after agreeing to a contractual buyout agreement<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/nba/news?slug=txtimberwolveshoward&prov=st&type=lgns |title=Timberwolves waive F Howard after reaching buyout |date=October 29, 2007 |publisher=[[Yahoo!]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071030074044/https://sports.yahoo.com/nba/news?slug=txtimberwolveshoward&prov=st&type=lgns |archive-date=October 30, 2007 |access-date=May 25, 2010}}</ref> worth $10&nbsp;million spread over four years instead of the roughly $14.25&nbsp;million ($6.88&nbsp;million plus $7.38&nbsp;million) that Minnesota would otherwise have owed him.<ref name=FkwW>{{cite web|author=Youngblood, Kent|url=http://www.startribune.com/511/story/1516287.html|title=Foye's knee worries Wolves|work=[[Star Tribune]]|accessdate=May 25, 2010|date=October 30, 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081203152252/http://www.startribune.com/511/story/1516287.html|archivedate=December 3, 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Return To Dallas Mavericks (2007\u20132008)===\n[[File:20080125 Juwan Howard signing autographs.jpg|thumb|left|Howard signing [[autograph]]s as a [[Dallas Maverick]]|alt=Black man mingles with the fans]]\nHoward agreed to terms with the [[2007\u201308 Dallas Mavericks season|Dallas Mavericks]] on October 30, 2007, but was not able to officially sign until the next day, when he cleared waivers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/news/story?id=3087419|title=Mavs agree to terms with free-agent forward Juwan Howard|accessdate=May 25, 2010|date=October 30, 2007|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chron.com/CDA/archives/archive.mpl?id=2007_4452643|title=NBA Notes|accessdate=May 25, 2010|date=October 31, 2007|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|page=4, sports section}}</ref> Terms of the deal were not disclosed publicly. During the [[2007\u201308 NBA season|2007\u201308 season]], he played in 50&nbsp;games and made no starts,<ref name=JH08GL>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/h/howarju01/gamelog/2008/|title=Juwan Howard 2007\u201308 Game Log|accessdate=May 25, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref> while averaging 1.1&nbsp;points and 1.6&nbsp;rebounds.<ref name=JHBR/> In his limited role he never played more than 18&nbsp;minutes and had season-highs of seven rebounds and six points.<ref name=JH08GL/>  The 2007\u201308 Mavericks were 51\u201331 under coach Johnson and lost in the first round of the [[2008 NBA Playoffs]] to the [[2007\u201308 New Orleans Hornets season|New Orleans Hornets]] four games to one.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/teams/DAL/2008.html|title=2007\u201308 Dallas Mavericks Roster and Statistics|accessdate=May 25, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref> In the playoffs, Howard only appeared for a total of 11&nbsp;minutes in three games.<ref name=JHBR/> This was the first season in Howard's career in which he did not start in a single game.<ref name=JHBR/>\n\n===Return To Denver Nuggets (2008)===\nOn October 3, 2008,<ref name=JHBR/> Howard rejoined the [[2008\u201309 Denver Nuggets season|Denver Nuggets]], but was later released when the Nuggets made a three-for-one trade of [[Allen Iverson]] for [[Chauncey Billups]], [[Antonio McDyess]] and [[Cheikh Samb]] on November 3 that put them over the 15-man roster size limit.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2008-11-04/sports/0811030532_1_varsity-softball-coach-football-coach-options|title=Transactions|accessdate=May 25, 2010|date=November 4, 2008|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]}}</ref>  When he was waived, Howard was the only player on the Nuggets' roster without a guaranteed contract.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2008-11-04/sports/0811030510_1_cheikh-samb-nuggets-pistons|title=Allen Iverson trade brings extra challenge for Derrick Rose|accessdate=May 25, 2010|date=November 4, 2008|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Johnson, K. C.}}</ref> Before the trade, Howard had played in three games during the [[2008\u201309 NBA season|2008\u201309 season]]. His appearances had all come from off the bench and lasted between 7 and 8 minutes.<ref name=JH09GL>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/h/howarju01/gamelog/2009/|title=Juwan Howard 2008\u201309 Game Log|accessdate=May 25, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref>  After Howard departed, the Nuggets went on to post a 54\u201328 record and reach the Western Conference finals under [[George Karl]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/teams/DEN/2009.html|title=2008\u201309 Denver Nuggets Roster and Statistics|accessdate=May 25, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref>\n\n===Charlotte Bobcats (2008\u20132009)===\nOn December 12, 2008, he was signed by the [[2008\u201309 Charlotte Bobcats season|Charlotte Bobcats]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/bobcats/release_howard_signed_081212.html |title=Bobcats Sign Juwan Howard |accessdate=December 12, 2008 |publisher=National Basketball Association |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081214155251/http://www.nba.com/bobcats/release_howard_signed_081212.html |archivedate=December 14, 2008 }}</ref> During the 2008\u201309 season, he played in 42&nbsp;games, making two starts;<ref name=\"JH09GL\"/> Howard averaged 4.1&nbsp;points and 1.8&nbsp;rebounds.<ref name=JHBR/>  In his reserve role, he played more than 20&nbsp;minutes five times, including four straight appearances from January 28 to February 8, and had season-highs of five rebounds and 14&nbsp;points. He posted 10 or more points five times.<ref name=JH09GL/>  Howard played extended minutes on January 28, the night after [[Gerald Wallace]] suffered a left-lung collapse and a non-displaced fracture of the fifth rib from a [[flagrant foul]] by [[Andrew Bynum]]; in 24 minutes of action, he scored 9 points.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=290128022|title=Aldridge helps Blazers win third straight contest|accessdate=May 25, 2010|date=January 28, 2009|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref><ref name=WiicwB>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/news/story?id=3866849|title=Wallace injured in collision with Bynum|accessdate=June 19, 2012|date=January 29, 2009|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/nba/boxscore?gameId=290128022|title=Bobcats 74 (19\u201327, 6\u201314 away); Trail Blazers 88 (28\u201317, 17\u20135 home)|accessdate=June 19, 2012|date=January 28, 2009|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> During Howard's streak of 20-minute appearances,<ref name=\"JH09GL\"/> he sat out one intervening game on February 6 with a toe injury.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=290206030|title=Hawks rally from 17-point deficit to drop slumping Bobcats|accessdate=May 25, 2010|date=February 6, 2009|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> On February 8, in only his second start as a Bobcat, he played a season-high 30 minutes, 39 seconds and posted a season-high 14&nbsp;points.<ref name=JH09GL/>  The subsequent night, Howard was out of the lineup again with a toe injury.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=290209030|title=Radmanovic hits 3 late 3s in debut as Bobcats end 5-game slide|accessdate=May 25, 2010|date=February 9, 2009|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref>  The 2008\u201309 Bobcats were 35\u201347 under coach [[Larry Brown (basketball)|Larry Brown]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/teams/CHA/2009.html|title=2008\u201309 Charlotte Bobcats Roster and Statistics|accessdate=May 25, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref>\n\n===Portland Trail Blazers (2009\u20132010)===\n[[File:20100425 Juwan Howard against Amar'e Stoudemire.jpg|thumb|Howard as a [[Portland Trail Blazers|Portland Trail Blazer]] against [[Amar'e Stoudemire]]|alt=Black athlete holds a basketball while a defender with his back to the camera plays defense]]\nOn September 17, 2009, Howard signed a one-year contract with the [[2009\u201310 Portland Trail Blazers season|Portland Trail Blazers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/2009/news/09/17/blazers.howard.ap/index.html |title=Trail Blazers sign Juwan Howard to one-year deal |publisher=National Basketball Association |accessdate=September 17, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090922170541/http://www.nba.com/2009/news/09/17/blazers.howard.ap/index.html |archivedate=September 22, 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.nba.com/blazers/news/trail_blazers_sign_juwan_howar_2009_09_17.html|title=Trail Blazers Sign Juwan Howard|publisher=Portland Trail Blazers\n|date=September 17, 2009|accessdate=September 17, 2009}}</ref>  On December 22, center [[Joel Przybilla]] injured his knee in the first quarter, allowing Howard to play additional minutes,<ref name=TBrbRAtoMiDr>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=291222006|title=Trail Blazers rally behind Roy, Aldridge to overcome Mavs in Dirk's return|accessdate=May 25, 2010|date=December 22, 2009|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref>  which allowed Howard his first double-double since April 6, 2007.<ref name=TBrbRAtoMiDr/>  He had his other double-double of the 2009\u201310 season the next night when he made his first start of the season.<ref name=JH08GL/>  All of Howard's performances with 10&nbsp;rebounds or more occurred between December 22 and February 3. December 23 marked the start of 14 consecutive starting appearances and 24&nbsp;starts in 26&nbsp;appearances (ending on February 16) for him.<ref name=JH10GL/> Having lost Przybilla and [[Greg Oden]] for the season, Portland acquired Camby from the [[Los Angeles Clippers]] for [[Steve Blake]] and [[Travis Outlaw]] on February 17 prior to the trade deadline.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/news/story?id=4918893|title=Clippers get two players for Camby|accessdate=March 2, 2013|date=February 17, 2010|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> During the [[2009\u201310 NBA season|2009\u201310 season]], he accumulated two double-doubles, played in 73&nbsp;games, and made 27&nbsp;starts,<ref name=JH10GL>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/h/howarju01/gamelog/2010/|title=Juwan Howard 2009\u201310 Game Log|accessdate=May 25, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref> while averaging 6.0&nbsp;points and 4.6&nbsp;rebounds.<ref name=JHNBASTATS/>  The 2009\u201310 Trail Blazers were 50\u201332 under coach [[Nate McMillan]] and lost in the first round of the [[2010 NBA Playoffs]] to the [[2009\u201310 Phoenix Suns season|Phoenix Suns]], four games to two.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/teams/POR/2010.html|title=2009\u201310 Portland Trail Blazers Roster and Statistics|accessdate=May 25, 2010|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref>  Howard appeared in all six games, averaging 3.3&nbsp;points and 2.7&nbsp;rebounds in 14.5&nbsp;minutes.<ref name=JHBR/> He played the most minutes (17:51) in game 4,<ref name=JH10GL/> when he added 8 points and 7 rebounds to help even the series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nba/boxscore?gameId=300424022|title=Suns 87 (2\u20132, 1\u20131 away); Trail Blazers 96 (2\u20132, 1\u20131 home)|accessdate=March 2, 2013|date=April 24, 2010|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref>\n\n===Miami Heat (2010\u20132013)===\nOn July 20, 2010, Howard came to terms for the [[2010\u201311 NBA season]] with the [[2010\u201311 Miami Heat season|Miami Heat]] on a one-year contract for the veteran's minimum salary, which was $1,352,181.<ref name=JHBR/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/news/story?id=5396136|title=Howard signs with Heat \u2013 again|accessdate=July 21, 2010|date=July 20, 2010|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/heat/roster/heat_signs_juwan_howard_2010_07_20.html|title=Heat Signs Juwan Howard|accessdate=July 20, 2010|publisher=National Basketball Association}}</ref>  Although he was only paid the minimum by the Heat, he was in the final year of his four-year buyout from the Timberwolves.<ref name=FkwW/> By joining the Heat, Howard joined a team that by the time of the [[2011 NBA playoffs]], included former champion [[Dwyane Wade]] as well as a group of players such as [[LeBron James]] and [[Chris Bosh]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://offthedribble.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/06/02/keeping-score-they-won-a-lot-of-games-and-soon-a-title/|title=Keeping Score: They Won a Lot of Games, and Soon a Title|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=June 2, 2011|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Paine, Neil}}</ref> In March, he was featured in the documentary film ''[[The Fab Five (film)|The Fab Five]]'', which was about his time as a Wolverine, that reignited controversy and reinvigorated the [[Duke\u2013Michigan basketball rivalry]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thequad.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/03/14/documentary-rekindles-fab-five-memories/|title=Documentary Rekindles 'Fab Five' Memories|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=March 14, 2011|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Gerstner, Joanne C.}}</ref> On March 31, Howard was fined $35,000 for escalating an altercation the night before. Howard was ejected for pushing [[JaVale McGee]], who was attempting to break up a dispute between [[Zydrunas Ilgauskas]] and [[John Wall (basketball)|John Wall]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.chicagotribune.com/merge/tsnform.aspx?c=chicagosports&page=nba/news/newstest.aspx?id=4393018|title=Wall suspended one game for altercation with Ilgauskas|accessdate=June 20, 2012|date=March 31, 2011|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407091014/http://sports.chicagotribune.com/merge/tsnform.aspx?c=chicagosports&page=nba%2Fnews%2Fnewstest.aspx%3Fid%3D4393018|archivedate=April 7, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=310330027|title=John Wall ejected for fracas in Wizards' loss vs. Heat|accessdate=June 20, 2012|date=March 30, 2011|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> For the season, Howard played 57 games for the [[2010\u201311 Miami Heat season|2010\u201311 Heat]], all as a reserve. He averaged 2.4 points and 2.1 rebounds with season highs of 18 points and 7 rebounds.<ref name=JH11GL>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/h/howarju01/gamelog/2011/|title=Juwan Howard 2010\u201311 Game Log|accessdate=June 20, 2012|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref> The Heat reached the NBA Finals, losing to the Dallas Mavericks four games to two.<ref name=\"MVP\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/2011/news/06/12/nowitzki-finals-mvp.ap/index.html |title=Gutty performance earns Nowitzki Finals MVP honors |date=June 12, 2011 |publisher=National Basketball Association |accessdate=June 13, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110616090307/http://www.nba.com/2011/news/06/12/nowitzki-finals-mvp.ap/index.html |archivedate=June 16, 2011 }}</ref><ref name=\"Washington Post\">{{cite news|title=NBA Finals: Dirk Nowitzki and the Dallas Mavericks complete stunning run to the championship|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/wizards/nba-finals-dirk-nowitzki-and-the-dallas-mavericks-complete-stunning-run-to-the-championship/2011/06/12/AGrwtPSH_story.html|accessdate=June 13, 2011|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |last=Lee |first=Michael |date=June 12, 2011}}</ref> Howard averaged 1.5 points and .9 rebounds per game during the postseason.<ref name=JHBR/>\n\n[[File:JuwanHowardMiami.jpg|thumb|left|Howard with the Heat in 2011]]\nOn December 10, 2011, Howard re-signed with the Heat for the same veteran's minimum salary as the year before.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/truehoop/miamiheat/post/_/id/10494/the-heats-big-void-lingers-front-and-center|title=The Heat's big void lingers, front and center|accessdate=December 12, 2011|date=December 10, 2011|publisher=[[ESPN]]|author=Windhorst, Brian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/SpearsNBAYahoo/status/145244461851619328|title=@SpearsNBAYahoo status|accessdate=December 12, 2011|date=December 9, 2011|publisher=[[Twitter]]|author=Spears, Marc J.}}</ref> Howard appeared in 28 regular season games as a reserve with limited minutes.<ref name=JH12GL>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/h/howarju01/gamelog/2012/|title=Juwan Howard 2011\u201312 Game Log|accessdate=June 20, 2012|publisher=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref> At age 39, Howard was the third-oldest active player in the league during the [[2011\u201312 NBA season]], behind [[Kurt Thomas (basketball)|Kurt Thomas]] and [[Grant Hill]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/dallas/mavericks/post/_/id/4685166/six-pack-vince-carter-moves-up-scoring-list|title=Six-Pack: Vince Carter moves up scoring list|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=February 16, 2012|publisher=[[ESPN]]|author=Stein, Marc}}</ref> Before Game 4 of an [[2012 NBA playoffs]] series against the [[2011\u201312 Indiana Pacers season|Indiana Pacers]], Howard engaged in pregame verbal sparring with [[Lance Stephenson]] after Stephenson mocked Howard's teammate James.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbssports.com/nba/blog/eye-on-basketball/19104550/juwan-howard-and-lance-stephenson-in-game-4-pregame-verbal-altercation|title=Juwan Howard and Lance Stephenson in Game 4 pregame verbal altercation|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=May 20, 2012|author=Young, Royce|publisher=[[CBS Sports]]}}</ref> Despite this incident, Howard was a maturing influence on the team during the playoffs; according to David Neal of ''[[The Miami Herald]]'', \"More often, Howard stood as the body of reason \u2014 getting between Dwyane Wade and [[Erik Spoelstra|Spoelstra]] against Indiana in Game 3 of the second round, pulling [[Mario Chalmers]] away from [[2011\u201312 Oklahoma City Thunder season|Oklahoma City]] star [[Kevin Durant]].\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/2012/06/27/2868195/miami-heats-juwan-howard-finally.html|title=Miami Heat's Juwan Howard finally captures a title for the Michigan Fab Five|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=June 27, 2012|work=[[The Miami Herald]]|author=Neal, David J.}}</ref> On June 21, 2012, Howard became the first and only member of the Fab Five to win an NBA championship, as a role player on the [[2011\u201312 Miami Heat season|2011\u201312 Miami Heat]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://collegebasketballtalk.nbcsports.com/2012/06/23/juwan-howard-is-first-member-of-michigans-fab-five-to-win-nba-title/|title=Juwan Howard is first member of Michigan's \"Fab Five\" to win NBA title|accessdate=June 24, 2012|date=June 23, 2012|publisher=[[NBC Sports]]|author=Martin, Daniel}}</ref> Howard was on the court as time expired in the series-clinching game because the three stars of the Heat (James, Wade and Bosh) had arranged it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/2012/06/27/2868194_p3/miami-heat-2012-roster-breakdown.html|title=Miami Heat 2012 roster breakdown|accessdate=March 2, 2013|date=June 27, 2012|work=[[The Miami Herald]]|author=Jackson, Barry}}</ref> Howard spoke about representing the Fab Five after the Heat won the [[2012 NBA Finals]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/truehoop/post/_/id/46563/juwan-howard-the-fab-age-patch|title=Juwan Howard: The Fab-age Patch|accessdate=June 26, 2012|date=June 25, 2012|publisher=[[ESPN]]|author=Adande, J.A.}}</ref> A teammate with the Heat was [[Shane Battier]], who grew up in Detroit as a fan of the [[Fab Five (University of Michigan)|Fab Five]] and idolized Howard. In his early teens, Battier sought Howard's [[autograph]] on a pair of sneakers and a few years later became a part of the Duke\u2013Michigan basketball rivalry when he turned down the local scholarship offer from Michigan to play for [[Duke Blue Devils men's basketball]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/06/20/sports/basketball/nba-finals-battier-and-howard-united-in-bid-for-championship-ring.html?ref=juwanhoward&_r=0|title=Split by Rivalry, United in Bid for a Ring|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=June 19, 2012|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Araton, Harvey}}</ref> Following the season, Howard became an unrestricted free agent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/2012/07/01/2875839/turiaf-opts-out-of-heat-contract.html|title=Ronny Turiaf opts out of Miami Heat contract, but Dexter Pittman will be retained|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=July 1, 2012|work=[[The Miami Herald]]|author=Jackson, Barry}}</ref> At the 20th annual [[ESPY Awards]], Howard and Heat teammate [[Mike Miller (basketball player)|Mike Miller]] took to the stage to accept the award for Team of the Year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/2012/07/15/2895813_p2/lets-just-say-us-wont-win-gold.html|title=Let's just say U.S. won't win gold for its uniforms|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=July 15, 2012|work=[[The Miami Herald]]|author=Cote, Greg}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Miami Heat Championship Parade 2012 2.jpg|thumb|right|Howard holding the [[Larry O'Brien Championship Trophy|Larry O'Brien Trophy]] at the Heat's 2012 championship parade]]\nOn February 21, 2013, the Heat traded [[Dexter Pittman]] to create space on the roster to pursue a more experienced big man.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/blogs/nba-ball-dont-lie/miami-heat-trade-dexter-pittman-2013-2nd-round-201748524--nba.html|title=Miami Heat trade Dexter Pittman, 2013 2nd-round pick to Memphis Grizzlies for basically nothing|accessdate=March 3, 2013|date=February 21, 2013|publisher=[[Yahoo! Sports]]|author=Devine, Dan}}</ref> On March 2, 2013, Howard signed a 10-day contract with the [[2012\u201313 Miami Heat season|2012\u201313 Miami Heat]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/heat/roster/heat-signs-juwan-howard|title=HEAT Signs Juwan Howard|accessdate=March 2, 2013|date=March 2, 2013|publisher=National Basketball Association}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/2013/news/03/02/heat-sign-howard.ap/index.html|title=Veteran Howard returns to Heat on 10-day contract|accessdate=March 2, 2013|date=March 2, 2013|publisher=National Basketball Association|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130303130403/http://www.nba.com/2013/news/03/02/heat-sign-howard.ap/index.html|archive-date=March 3, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> On March 12, 2013, he signed a second 10-day contract with the Heat,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/heat/news/heat-signs-juwan-howard-second-10-day-contract|title=HEAT Signs Juwan Howard to Second 10-day Contract|accessdate=March 12, 2013|date=March 12, 2013|publisher=National Basketball Association}}</ref> and on March 22, 2013, he was signed for the remainder of the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/heat/heat-signs-juwan-howard|title=HEAT Signs Juwan Howard|accessdate=March 22, 2013|date=March 22, 2013|publisher=National Basketball Association}}</ref> He made his first appearance of the season for the Heat on March 24 against the [[2012\u201313 Charlotte Bobcats season|Charlotte Bobcats]] tallying two points, a rebound and two assists in three minutes of play as the Heat made their way to their 26th consecutive victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=400278761|title=Dwyane Wade-less Heat throttle Bobcats, run streak to 26|accessdate=March 26, 2013|date=March 24, 2013|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nba/boxscore?gameId=400278761|title=Bobcats 77 (16-54, 6-29 away); Heat 109 (55-14, 32-3 home)|accessdate=March 26, 2013|date=March 24, 2013|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> On April 15, he made his first start since April 14, 2010 as the Heat defeated the [[2012\u201313 Cleveland Cavaliers season|Cleveland Cavaliers]] without James, Wade, Bosh, Battier, Chalmers and [[Udonis Haslem]] in the penultimate game of the regular season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=400278924|title=Heat hold off Cavs as LeBron James sits|accessdate=April 16, 2013|date=April 15, 2013|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> Howard's April 17 start in the season finale against the [[2012\u201313 Orlando Magic season|Orlando Magic]] marked Howard's 900th career start.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=400278940|title=Heat close regular season with win against NBA-worst Magic|accessdate=April 19, 2013|date=April 17, 2013|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> On May 30, during halftime of game 5 of the Eastern Conference championship against the [[2012\u201313 Indiana Pacers season|Indiana Pacers]], Howard delivered a passionate speech that fired up the team in its clinching game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://probasketballtalk.nbcsports.com/2013/05/31/lebron-takes-over-heat-take-game-5-from-pacers/|title=LeBron takes over, Heat take Game 5 from Pacers|accessdate=June 21, 2013|date=May 31, 2013|publisher=[[NBCSports.com]]|author=Pollakoff, Brett}}</ref><ref name=LJgastHtahoG5>{{cite web|url=http://nba.si.com/2013/05/30/lebron-james-halftime-speech-miami-heat-indiana-pacers/|title=LeBron James gives animated speech to Heat teammates at halftime of Game 5|accessdate=June 21, 2013|date=May 31, 2013|work=[[Sports Illustrated]]|author=Golliver, Ben|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130610015215/http://nba.si.com/2013/05/30/lebron-james-halftime-speech-miami-heat-indiana-pacers/|archivedate=June 10, 2013}}</ref> With the retirement of [[Grant Hill]] on June 1, 2013, Howard became the oldest active player in the NBA at age 40.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/lakersnow/la-sp-ln-steve-nash-oldest-player-under-contract-next-season-20130603,0,941769.story|title=Steve Nash the NBA's oldest player under contract for next season|accessdate=June 11, 2013|date=June 3, 2013|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|author=Pincus, Eric}}</ref> During the playoffs, Howard did not play, but he served as a quasi-assistant coach.<ref name=LJgastHtahoG5/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxsportsflorida.com/nba/miami-heat/story/Juwan-Howard-hits-halfcourt-shot-with-ba?blockID=913759&feedID=3720|title=Juwan Howard hits halfcourt shot with back to basket|accessdate=June 21, 2013|date=June 20, 2013|work=[[FOX Sports]]}}</ref>\n\n==Player profile==\n[[File:Juwan Howard Heat.jpg|thumb|Howard diving for a loose ball in 2010]]\nIn college, Howard was regarded as one of the best defensive big men in the country.<ref name=HDICT>{{cite news|title=Howard's Dream Is Coming True|date=April 5, 1993|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Bickley, Dan|page=99}}</ref> According to Mariotti, he was also regarded as a \"rock-solid\" power forward who provided rebounds and defense, in contrast to his flamboyant teammate Webber.<ref>{{cite news|title=Should Muscle-less Bulls Eye Howard or Webber?|date=November 11, 1994|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Mariotti, Jay|page=143|quote=If Howard is considered a rock-solid, rebounds-and-defense power forward, Webber is the total showtime package, the transcendent franchise player.}}</ref> Fisher referred to Howard as his \"[[Rock of Gibraltar]]\".<ref name=HKMAH3P1RRT/> His consistency was described by ''Chicago Tribune'' journalist Skip Myslenski as Michigan's \"ballast, steadying them on those many occasions when they wavered. And their savior, rescuing them from their many follies\".<ref name=HKMAH3P1RRT/>\n\nAfter the 1994 draft, NBA analyst [[Doug Collins (basketball)|Doug Collins]] described Howard as a player who could \"play with his back to the basket\" and \"shoot from about 16 feet outside\" and who played \"with a lot of energy and emotion\".<ref name=CTHRD>{{cite web|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1994-06-30/sports/9406300233_1_national-basketball-association-draft-dallas-guard-tony-dumas|title=Chicagoans Thomas, Howard Realize Dreams|accessdate=September 12, 2010|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=June 30, 1994|author=Sakamoto, Bob}}</ref> The Bullets' [[general manager]], [[John Nash (basketball)|John Nash]], who was disappointed that [[Jason Kidd]] was no longer available at the fifth pick of the draft,<ref name=CU/> told Jerry Bembry of ''[[The Baltimore Sun]]'' that Howard was \"as fundamentally sound as any player in the draft\" and that he \"[had] a discipline about his game and [used] a high level of skill and technique\". Bembry said, \"Not only can Howard post up, he passes effectively and is able to hit a jumper up to 17 feet\", adding that he also was \"an excellent position defender\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1994-06-30/sports/1994181190_1_juwan-howard-bullets-shawn-kemp|title=Bullets say Howard is good deal|accessdate=September 12, 2010|date=June 30, 1994|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|author=Bembry, Jerry}}</ref>  Later Bembry noted that he was a power forward who was able to play center, adding that at Michigan he was \"most effective playing with his back to the basket\" but could also pass effectively and hit medium-range [[Jump shot (basketball)|jumpers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1994-07-06/sports/1994187031_1_howard-jim-mcilvaine-bullets|title=Howard's attitude wins over Bullets|accessdate=September 12, 2010|date=July 6, 1994|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|author=Bembry, Jerry}}</ref> The Bullets' head coach, [[Jim Lynam]], described Howard as a \"complete player\" and noted, \"[H]e can defend you and he can score over you\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1994-07-01/sports/1994182025_1_bullets-gheorghe-muresan-calbert|title=Bullets give defense 1\u20132 punch|accessdate=September 12, 2010|date=July 1, 1994|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|author=Bembry, Jerry}}</ref> Nash said that \"the things that impressed me most about him were his character, his intelligence and his insight. He's a leader type.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1994-06-30/sports/1994181182_1_jim-lynam-juwan-howard-john-nash|title=Underclass names change, but NBA teams remain predictably ecstatic|accessdate=September 12, 2010|date=June 30, 1994|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|author=Jackman, Phil}}</ref>\n\nWhen he first became a [[free agent]] in 1996, Howard was described as versatile enough to play all three front-line positions ([[small forward]], power forward and center), and [[Michael Jordan]] praised his \"game, work ethic and character\".<ref>{{cite news|title=The key to Bulls' future could be Juwan Howard |date=June 25, 1996|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Jackson, John|page=96}}</ref>  As a Dallas player in 2000\u201301, he was still regarded as a versatile offensive player who could \"take advantage of smaller defenders in the paint and then stretch his bigger defenders outside\" in addition to being a solid rebounder.<ref name=PBMHHSoS>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/03/14/sports/pro-basketball-mavericks-howard-has-smile-of-success.html|title=Pro Basketball; Mavericks' Howard Has Smile of Success|accessdate=May 22, 2010|date=March 14, 2001|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Robbins, Liz}}</ref>  By 2001, Lacy J. Banks from the ''Chicago Sun-Times'' regarded him as a high-priced, under-achieving player,<ref>{{cite news|title=The Man Who Drafted Jordan might finally get his due|date=November 18, 2001|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Banks, Lacy J.|page=118}}</ref>  but in 2002, Banks described him as a solid veteran at the four (power forward position).<ref>{{cite news|title=Dunleavy heads talented group of small forwards|date=June 23, 2002|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Banks, Lacy J.|page=114}}</ref> In the NBA, Howard developed a respected inside post-up game and a reputation as a veteran leader, according to [[Kiki Vandeweghe]], the general manager of the [[Denver Nuggets]], Howard's team in 2003.<ref>{{cite news|title=Van Exel reserves best for playoffs|date=May 18, 2003|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Banks, Lacy J.|page=105, sports section}}</ref>\n\nWhen he signed with the Heat in 2010, Howard was lauded for his ability to play the power forward and center positions and for his professionalism.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/heat/roster/heat_signs_juwan_howard_2010_07_20.html|title=HEAT Signs Juwan Howard|accessdate=September 12, 2012|date=July 20, 2010|publisher=National Basketball Association}}</ref> Howard also added frontcourt toughness.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2010/writers/ian_thomsen/07/21/east.contenders/|title=Sneak peek at East contenders|accessdate=September 12, 2012|date=July 21, 2010|work=[[Sports Illustrated]]|author=Thomsen, Ian}}</ref> As an elder statesman with the Heat, he was regarded as a future NBA coach or general manager.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/2012/06/27/2868195/miami-heats-juwan-howard-finally.html|title=Miami Heat's Juwan Howard finally captures a title for the Michigan Fab Five|accessdate=September 12, 2012|date=June 27, 2012|work=[[The Miami Herald]]|author=Neal, David J.}}</ref>\n\n==Coaching career==\nOn September 28, 2013, the Heat announced a reshuffling of their organization. The reshuffling included the announcement that Howard would remain with the Heat, moving officially into an assistant coaching role. The assistant coaching position was available after both [[Chad Kammerer]] and [[Keith Askins]] were moved from coaching to scouting positions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/heat/news_recap/heat-announce-front-office-promotions|title=HEAT Announce Front Office Promotions|accessdate=September 28, 2013|date=September 28, 2013|work=[[NBA.com]]}}</ref> This effectively indicated Howard's retirement as a basketball player, as league regulations prohibit one from holding a coaching position while being an active player.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nba.si.com/2013/09/28/juwan-howard-miami-heat-assistant-coach-michigan-fab-five/ |title=Juwan Howard hired as Heat assistant coach |accessdate=September 30, 2013 |date=September 28, 2013 |work=[[Sports Illustrated]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131001065658/http://nba.si.com/2013/09/28/juwan-howard-miami-heat-assistant-coach-michigan-fab-five/ |archivedate=October 1, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nOn May 22, 2019, Howard was named Men's Basketball Head Coach of the [[Michigan Wolverines men's basketball]] team,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bigten.org/news/2019/5/30/mens-basketball-juwan-howard-named-michigan-head-coach.aspx|title=Juwan Howard Named Michigan Head Coach|website=bigten.org|language=en|access-date=2019-06-06}}</ref> signing a five-year contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mgoblue.com/news/2019/5/22/former-michigan-great-juwan-howard-returns-as-mens-basketball-coach.aspx |title=Former Michigan Great Juwan Howard Returns as Men's Basketball Coach |accessdate=May 22, 2019 |date=May 22, 2019 |first=Tom |last=Wywrot |website=MGoBlue.com |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]}}</ref>\n\n==Head coaching record==\n{{CBB Yearly Record Start | type = | conference = | postseason = | poll = }}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Subhead\n | name       = [[Michigan Wolverines men's basketball|Michigan Wolverines]]\n | conference = [[Big Ten Conference]]\n | startyear  = 2019\n | endyear    = \n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | season       = [[2019\u201320 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2019\u201320]]\n | name         = [[2019\u201320 Michigan Wolverines men's basketball team|Michigan]]\n | overall      = 19\u201312\n | conference   = 10\u201310\n | confstanding = 9th\n | postseason   = [[2020 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|NCAA Division I Canceled]]\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Subtotal\n | name       = Michigan\n | overall    = 19\u201312 ({{Winning percentage|19|12}})\n | confrecord = 10\u201310 ({{Winning percentage|10|10}})\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record End\n | overall = 19\u201312 ({{Winning percentage|19|12}})\n}}\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Juwan Howard1-crop.jpg|left|thumb|Howard in 2008]]\nHoward remained a Chicago resident throughout his NBA playing career. In 1996, he bought a {{convert|3116|sqft|m2|1|adj=on}} [[town home]] for $490,000 in the South [[Loop, Chicago|Loop]] area.<ref name=\"house\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2010-01-03/news/0912310497_1_chicago-river-floor-bulls|title=NBA star Juwan Howard buys condo in Trump tower|accessdate=May 21, 2010|date=January 3, 2010|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Goldsborough, Bob}}</ref> In 2009, he paid $2.55&nbsp;million for a three-bedroom, {{convert|3080|sqft|m2|1|adj=on}} unit in the [[Trump International Hotel and Tower (Chicago)|Trump International Hotel & Tower]].<ref name=\"house\"/> In 2005, Howard bought a {{convert|3.5|acre|m2|adj=on}} $11.775 million property in South Florida's Gables Estates, where he intended to build a {{convert|15000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} home, with a dock for a newly purchased {{convert|54|ft|m|adj=on}} [[yacht]] named the Fab 5.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=MH&s_site=miami&p_multi=MH&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=10C2B98B0EEE3078&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|title=NBA Player Joining Ritzy Gables Enclave|work=[[The Miami Herald]]|accessdate=September 8, 2010|date=August 21, 2005|page=4A, Front section|url-access=subscription  }}</ref> After the Heat won the 2012 NBA championship, Howard sold the home within a week for about $10 million, but he continued to own at least one South Florida real estate property.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/2012/07/12/2892496/broward-commissioner-chip-lamarca.html|title=Broward commissioner Chip LaMarca facing foreclosure on house|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=July 12, 2012|work=[[The Miami Herald]]|author=Lambiet, Jose}}</ref>\n\nHoward has six children with four different women.  One of Howard's children, son Juwan Howard Jr. (born February 5, 1992),<ref name=JHJWMU>{{cite web|url=http://www.wmubroncos.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=4600&ATCLID=204997509|title=Juwan Howard Jr.|accessdate=October 6, 2010|publisher=[[Western Michigan University]]}}</ref> is the child of Markita Blyden, who was runner-up for Michigan's Miss Basketball when she and her twin sister led Detroit's [[Murray\u2013Wright High School]] to the 1990 Class A state championship game. Howard, Jr. finished his senior season at Detroit's [[Pershing High School]] in spring 2010.<ref name=Hfiff>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncaa/recruiting/basketball/mens/news/story?id=4848717|title=Howard follows in family's footsteps|author=Arnold, Jeff|publisher=[[ESPN]]|date=January 29, 2010|accessdate=July 7, 2010}}</ref> As a junior, he led his high school to the [[Michigan High School Athletic Association]] state championship. As a senior, he was named first team All-State by the Associated Press and ''[[Detroit Free Press]]''.<ref name=JHJWMU/>  He played his freshman season for the [[2010\u201311 Western Michigan Broncos men's basketball team|2010\u201311 Western Michigan Broncos]] before he transferred to the [[University of Detroit Mercy]] [[Detroit Titans men's basketball|Titans]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/id/7057951/juwan-howard-jr-transfers-detroit-titans-western-michigan-broncos|title=Juwan Howard Jr. to play at Detroit|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=October 4, 2011|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> As a [[redshirt (college sports)|redshirt]] sophomore for the [[2012\u201313 Detroit Titans men's basketball team|2012\u201313 Detroit Titans]], he became a regular starter and solid contributor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/2013/02/26/3255084/nba-sons-making-their-mark-in.html#storylink=misearch|title=NBA sons making their mark in college basketball|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=February 26, 2013|work=[[The Miami Herald]]|author=Beard, Aaron}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/mens-college-basketball/player/_/id/51634/juwan-howard-jr|title=Juwan Howard Jr.|accessdate=March 1, 2013|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref>\n\nOn July 6, 2002, Howard married Jenine Wardally. At the time, Howard was 29 and Wardally was 27. They have two sons: Jace, who was born in late September 2001,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=MH&s_site=miami&p_multi=MH&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0F61BBC171E9EC9E&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|title=Miamian Finds Niche In TV Role|work=[[The Miami Herald]]|accessdate=September 8, 2010|date=September 14, 2002|page=1B, Local section|url-access=subscription  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=RM&p_theme=rm&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0F733F8CD20B2918&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|title=Howard Tells Teammates He's Sorry, And Rarin' To Go|accessdate=September 8, 2010|date=November 5, 2002|work=[[Rocky Mountain News]]|author=Tomasson, Chris}}</ref> and Jett, who is two years younger.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=MH&s_site=miami&p_multi=MH&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=11A50587EDB0C700&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|title=An Old Restaurant Starts A New Casino|work=[[The Miami Herald]]|accessdate=September 8, 2010|date=July 4, 2007|page=4A, Front section|url-access=subscription  }}</ref> Both are high school basketball players with multiple [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] recruitment offers. Jace committed to University of Michigan on January 20th, 2020 and will play under his father. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.prephoops.com/2018/07/2020-f-jace-howard-discusses-his-transfer-to-university-recruitment-and-more/|title=2020 F Jace Howard discusses his transfer to University, recruitment and more}}</ref>\n\n===Philanthropy===\n\nAs a student athlete at the University of Michigan, Howard volunteered to visit patients at the [[University of Michigan Health System|University of Michigan Health System Hospitals]] in Ann Arbor, Michigan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1996-02-11/sports/1996042075_1_juwan-howard-bullets-michigan|title=Howard's impact is felt on, off court Uncertain future: Juwan Howard has made an impression on those whose lives he has touched, and on a Bullets team needing a spark. But he will become a free agent after this season.|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=February 11, 1996|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|author=Bembry, Jerry}}</ref> While juggling professional basketball duties and coursework as an NBA rookie/student-athlete, he continued to find time for charity work and hospital visits.<ref name=TADHKHPTHG/> His humanitarian works included a Stay in School Jam for 6,500 local area students that he participated in along with several teammates and R&B artist [[Usher (entertainer)|Usher]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1995-02-26/sports/1995057184_1_calbert-cheaney-baltimore-county-juwan-howard|title=Bullets at 'School Jam' tomorrow|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=February 26, 1995|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]}}</ref>\n\nHoward is active in fostering youth basketball activities through the Juwan Howard Foundation, which helps underprivileged youth in Washington, D.C. and Chicago. He was recognized in 2001 as one of the \"Good Guys in Sports\" by ''[[The Sporting News]]'' for his civic contributions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/playerfile/juwan_howard/bio.html |title=Juwan Howard # Forward |accessdate=September 6, 2010 |publisher=National Basketball Association |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100901182307/http://www.nba.com/playerfile/juwan_howard/bio.html |archivedate=September 1, 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/mavericks/news/good_guys_2001.html|title=Howard/Finley Named to TSN''s Good Guys List for 2001|accessdate=July 18, 2012|date=July 12, 2001|publisher=[[Dallas Mavericks]]}}</ref> In April 2010, Howard won the NBA Cares Community Assist Award for his community efforts, philanthropic work and charitable contributions.<ref name=PTBFCJHRNCCAAfA>{{cite web|url=http://www.iamatrailblazersfan.com/ArticleDisplay/tabid/120/ItemID/1442/Default.aspx|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101031051749/http://www.iamatrailblazersfan.com/ArticleDisplay/tabid/120/ItemID/1442/Default.aspx|url-status=dead|archive-date=October 31, 2010|title=Portland Trail Blazers Forward/Center Juwan Howard Receives NBA Cares Community Assist Award for April|accessdate=September 6, 2010|date=April 30, 2010|publisher=[[Portland Trail Blazers]]/NBA Media Ventures, LLC}}</ref> He runs a yearly free basketball camp for youth, which is made possible by a partnership between the Juwan Howard Foundation and the [[Chicago Public Schools]] (CPS), Jordan Brand, [[Dell Computers]], [[EMI Music]], [[Vitamin Water]] and the NBA.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maxpreps.com/news/a1HroHKyEd6OEwAcxJTdpg/illinois--former-chicago-star-juwan-howard-returns-with-camp.htm|title= Illinois: Former Chicago Star Juwan Howard Returns With Camp: Football heats up with Bolingbrook's annual passing jamboree.|accessdate=September 6, 2010|date=July 19, 2009|publisher=[[CBS Sports]]|work=[[MaxPreps]]|author=Bowker, Paul}}</ref> His foundation partners with the CPS for a reading challenge; the top 300 readers, out of 30,000 annually, attend his camp.<ref name=PTBFCJHRNCCAAfA/> During and after his time as a member of the Heat, Howard was active in South Florida community outreach, fundraising and humanitarian efforts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/2012/06/18/2856376/nba-partners-renovate-miami-springs.html|title=NBA, partners renovate Miami Springs community center|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=June 18, 2012|work=[[The Miami Herald]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/2012/10/26/3068996/was-scott-disick-shopping-for.html|title=Was Scott Disick shopping for a diamond?|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=October 26, 2012|work=[[The Miami Herald]]|author=Abravanel, Lesley}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/2012/12/29/3158627/heatnba-visit-to-the-springs-top.html|title=Heat/NBA visit to the Springs top story of 2012|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=December 29, 2012|work=River Cities Gazette|publisher=[[The Miami Herald]]|author1=Curtis, Tom  |author2=Bill Daley}}</ref>\n\n==Film and television appearances==\nHoward appeared in the 1994 basketball film ''[[Hoop Dreams]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blazersedge.com/2009/9/17/1035743/your-newest-blazer|title=Your Newest Blazer: Juwan Howard|accessdate=October 3, 2010|date=September 17, 2009|agency=Associated Press|author=Golliver, Ben}}</ref> He had a small role in the television drama ''[[The West Wing (TV series)|The West Wing]]'', appearing in a 1999 episode as a former [[Duke basketball]] player who served on [[Josiah Bartlet]]'s [[President's Council on Fitness, Sports, and Nutrition|Council on Physical Fitness]] and helped him win a game against his staff.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kTZsRcwe5mAC&pg=PA117&lpg=PA117&dq=Juwan+Howard+%22West+Wing%22#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Inside the West Wing: an unauthorized look at television's smartest show|accessdate=September 7, 2010|author=Challen, Paul|publisher=Ecw Press|isbn=1-55022-468-9|year=2001}}</ref>\n\nOther appearances include the August 15, 1999 \"The Art of Give and Take\" episode of ''[[Arli$$]]'', the season 5 (2005) \"Michigan's Fab 5\" episode of ''[[Beyond the Glory]]'', the November 9, 1996 season 2 \"Son-in-Law\" episode of ''[[Hang Time (TV series)|Hang Time]]'' and the 2011 documentary ''[[The Fab Five (film)|The Fab Five]]'', produced by his Michigan teammate Jalen Rose.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/juwan-howard/248685|title=Juwan Howard|accessdate=October 3, 2010|work=[[TV Guide]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite episode | title = Son-in-Law | series = Hang Time | serieslink = Hang Time (TV series) | network = [[NBC]] | airdate = November 9, 1996 | season = 2 | number = 10}}</ref><!--Actual refs are spam and non-RS so I cited the episode under the assumption he really appeared on the show<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvrage.com/shows/id-3783/printable/|title=Hang Time Episode Guide|accessdate=October 3, 2010|work=[[TVrage]]}}</ref> Only other sources are imdb.com and http://homepage.mac.com/ijball/TEXT_guides/HTime-guide.txt--> After his 18th season in the NBA, Howard worked with [[Rick Ross]] to produce a [[rap music|rap]] song entitled \"It's Time to Ball\" from an album Howard was working on entitled ''Full Court Press Volume 1''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbssports.com/nba/blog/eye-on-basketball/19998608/heat-f-juwan-howard-records-rap-song-with-rick-ross-plans-to-release-album|title=Heat F Juwan Howard records rap song with Rick Ross, plans to release album|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=August 31, 2012|publisher=[[CBS Sports]]|author=Golliver, Ben}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{NBA player statistics legend|champion=y}}\n\n===NBA===\n====Regular season====\n{{NBA player statistics start}}\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | {{nbay|1994}}\n| align=\"left\" | [[1994\u201395 Washington Bullets season|Washington]]\n| 65 || 52 || 36.1 || .489 || .000 || .664 || '''8.4''' || 2.5 || .8 || .2 || 17.0\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | {{nbay|1995}}\n| align=\"left\" | [[1995\u201396 Washington Bullets season|Washington]]\n| 81 || 81 || '''40.7''' || .489 || .308 || .749 || 8.1 || '''4.4''' || .8 || .5 || '''22.1'''\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | {{nbay|1996}}\n| align=\"left\" | [[1996\u201397 Washington Bullets season|Washington]]\n| '''82''' || '''82''' || 40.5 || .486 || .000 || .756 || 8.0 || 3.8 || 1.1 || .3 || 19.1\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | {{nbay|1997}}\n| align=\"left\" | [[1997\u201398 Washington Wizards season|Washington]]\n| 64 || 64 || 40.0 || .467 || .000 || .721 || 7.0 || 3.3 || '''1.3''' || .4 || 18.5\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | {{nbay|1998}}\n| align=\"left\" | [[1998\u201399 Washington Wizards season|Washington]]\n| 36 || 36 || 39.7 || .474 || .000 || .753 || 8.1 || 3