{"title_page": "Alliance of American Football", "text_new": "{{short description|former professional American football league}}\n{{Use American English|date=March 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox sports league\n| title           = Alliance of American Football\n| current_season  = \n| Formerly        = \n| last_season     = 2019 AAF season\n| logo            = Alliance of American Football logo.png\n| pixels          = 150\n| upcoming_season = \n| sport           = American football\n| founded         = {{start date|2018|3|20}}\n| headquarters    = [[San Francisco]], [[California]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://shop.aaf.com/media/|title=Media|publisher=}}</ref>\n| inaugural       = [[2019 AAF season|2019]]\n| folded          = April 17, 2019 (bankruptcy)<ref name=APchap7>{{cite |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/2019/04/17/aaf-alliance-american-football-files-bankruptcy/3500708002/ |title=AAF files for bankruptcy, officially closes down |agency=[[Associated Press|AP]] |website=[[USA Today]] |date=April 17, 2019 |accessdate=April 17, 2019}}</ref>\n| teams           = 8\n| country         = United States\n| website         = {{url|www.aaf.com}}\n| TV              = {{Plainlist|\n*[[CBS Sports]]\n*[[NFL Network]]\n*[[Turner Sports]]\n}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Alliance of American Football''' ('''AAF''') was a professional [[American football]] league that played a portion of one season in 2019.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Allen |first1=Kevin |title=AAF suspends football operations with two weeks left in regular season |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/2019/04/02/aaf-alliance-american-football-league-suspends-operations/3342451002/ |website=USA TODAY |publisher=Gannett Satellite Information Network, LLC. |accessdate=3 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=APchap7/><ref name=\"espnpostmortem\"/> The AAF consisted of eight centrally owned and operated teams in the southern and western United States, seven of which were located in metropolitan areas with at least one [[Major professional sports leagues in the United States and Canada|major professional sports franchise]].\n\nFounded by [[Charlie Ebersol]] and [[Bill Polian]] in 2018, the AAF began play on February 9, 2019, six days after the [[National Football League]]'s (NFL) [[Super Bowl LIII]] championship game. The league was scheduled to have a 10-week regular season and conclude with a championship game on April 27. After eight weeks of play, however, the league's football operations were suspended by controlling owner [[Thomas Dundon]] on April 2.<ref>{{cite news |author=Kercheval, Ben |title=AAF operations suspended, league's future in doubt after eight games of first season |url=https://www.cbssports.com/aaf/news/aaf-operations-reportedly-suspended-leagues-future-in-doubt-after-eight-games-of-first-season/ |website=cbssports.com |date=April 2, 2019 |accessdate=2019-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|agency=[[ESPN]]|url=http://www.espn.com/espn/story/_/id/26423928/source-aaf-immediately-suspend-operations|title=AAF to immediately suspend operations|publisher=[[ESPN]]|date=April 2, 2019|accessdate=April 2, 2019}}</ref> Two days later, the AAF allowed players to leave their contracts to sign with NFL teams.<ref name=\"Schwartz\">{{Cite web|url=https://ftw.usatoday.com/2019/04/aaf-keith-reaser-kansas-city-chiefs|title=AAF star Keith Reaser becomes first player to sign NFL deal after league shutdown|first=Nick|last=Schwartz|work=USA Today|date=April 4, 2019|accessdate=April 4, 2019}}</ref> The AAF filed for [[Chapter 7, Title 11, United States Code|Chapter 7]] bankruptcy on April 17, 2019, with the league's sole season left incomplete.<ref name=APchap7/><ref name=Chapter7/>\n\n==History==\nCharlie Ebersol, son of former NBC executive and XFL co-founder [[Dick Ebersol]], was inspired to create the AAF in late 2016 after producing the documentary ''This Was the XFL'' for [[ESPN Films]]' ''[[30 for 30]]'' series; upon researching and examining the history of the [[XFL (2001)|XFL]], he came to the conclusion that the concept was viable but that the finished product was both poorly executed and, from an on-field standpoint, bad football. He began developing the AAF in February 2017, about the same time that word had come out about XFL co-founder [[Vince McMahon]] possibly [[XFL (2020)|reviving the old XFL brand]] (which McMahon would indeed do in 2020).<ref name=ebersolprofile>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/aaf-2019-how-the-new-alliance-of-american-football-stands-out-in-an-ever-growing-pro-football-landscape/|title=AAF 2019: How the new Alliance of American Football stands out in a growing pro football landscape|first=Ben|last=Kercheval|work=CBS Sports|date=February 4, 2019|accessdate=February 4, 2019}}</ref> Exhibits in a lawsuit filed by Robert Vanech, who claimed to have co-founded the AAF, state that Ebersol had originally approached McMahon about relaunching the XFL but was unable to come to an agreement, as Ebersol wanted control of the XFL brand and was willing to pay $50 million for the trademark, which McMahon was unwilling to sell.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/sports/football/2019/02/25/aaf-robert-vanech-alliance-american-football-charlie-ebersol-lawsuit/2983124002/?cid=twitter_azcsports|title=More trouble for the AAF? Man reportedly suing league for 50 percent ownership stake|work=AZcentral.com|date=February 25, 2019|accessdate=February 25, 2019}}</ref> In December 2018, [[Charlie Ebersol]] asked Vince McMahon about merging the AAF (which was two months away from starting) with the XFL. McMahon turned him down.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/Journal/Issues/2019/04/08/Leagues-and-Governing-Bodies/AAF.aspx |title=XFL rejected merger with AAF, takes lessons from failed league |last=Kaplan |first=Daniel |date=April 8, 2019 |website=www.sportsbusinessdaily.com |publisher=Sports Business Journal |access-date=February 12, 2020 |quote=In mid-December 2018, Charlie Ebersol and his nascent Alliance of American Football was two months away from the kickoff of its inaugural season \u2014 and it was already running out of money. Ebersol had secured limited funding from venture capital firms when he unveiled the league nine months earlier, but the AAF was on life support. So Ebersol approached WWE chairman and XFL kingpin Vince McMahon about a merger, a key source said. McMahon, who is relaunching the XFL next year, turned him down, the source said. The XFL declined to comment.}}</ref>\n\nThe AAF was announced on March 20, 2018. Ebersol sought to focus on creating a solid football product in the hopes that it would attract fans. He hired a team of experienced football players, coaches and executives to prepare the league for launch.<ref name=ebersolprofile/> The AAF was overseen by former [[National Football League|NFL]] general manager [[Bill Polian]], former [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] safety [[Troy Polamalu]], and executive [[John McKay Jr.|J. K. McKay]]. Advisers also include former Steelers receiver [[Hines Ward]], former [[New York Giants]] and [[Oakland Raiders]] defensive end [[Justin Tuck]], retired referee and current [[Fox NFL]] [[rules analyst]] [[Mike Pereira]], and Ebersol's father, Dick Ebersol.<ref name=\"espn\">{{cite news|last1=Rovell|first1=Darren|title=Former NFLers involved in league to rival XFL|url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/22844453/xfl-documentary-maker-plans-own-football-league|accessdate=March 20, 2018|work=ESPN.com|date=March 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\nEbersol attended the first XFL game in Las Vegas in 2001, and remembered how disappointed his father was by the poor quality of play.<ref name=\"ap20190213\">{{Cite news |url=https://triblive.com/pghtrib/localsports/14610673-94/aafs-officials-pleased-with-opening-weekend-tv-ratings-but-remain-cautious |title=AAF's officials pleased with opening weekend TV ratings but remain cautious |date=2019-02-13 |work=Pittsburgh Tribune-Review |access-date=2019-02-14 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> To ensure professional-level football at launch, the AAF set out to hire coaches with professional football coaching and championship experience.<ref>{{cite web |title=Steve Spurrier to coach Orlando team in new spring league, Alliance of American Football |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/nfl-competitor-alliance-of-american-football-new-football-league-first-team-orlando-steve-spurrier-today/ |website=CBS News |accessdate=October 3, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> On April 7, 2018, the first team, Orlando, was announced with its coach [[Steve Spurrier]].<ref name=cbs>{{cite news|last1=Steimle|first1=Kevin|last2=Breech|first2=John|title=Steve Spurrier announced as first coach and Orlando first host city for Alliance of American Football|url=https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/steve-spurrier-announced-as-first-coach-and-orlando-first-host-city-for-alliance-of-american-football/|accessdate=April 7, 2018|work=CBSSports.com|date=April 7, 2018|language=en}}</ref> By June 2018, the league had announced its eight inaugural teams and their cities.<ref name=\"espn\" />\n\nOn July 30, 2018, the Alliance announced the league had signed 100 players.<ref name=\"mca\">{{cite news |last1=Munz |first1=Jason |title=Alliance of American Football announces Memphis team has signed 28 players |url= https://www.commercialappeal.com/story/sports/2018/08/01/alliance-american-football-memphis-signs-sec-standouts-ut-vols/882425002/ |accessdate=September 14, 2018 |work=The Memphis Commercial Appeal |date=August 1, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> In August 2018, the league held the Alliance Scouting Combine at three locations and four dates: August 4, 2018, in Los Angeles, California; August 18 in Houston, Texas; and August 25\u201326 in Atlanta, Georgia.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ward |first1=Brendan |title=Alliance of American Football hosting scouting combine for players |url=http://www.wmcactionnews5.com/story/38558071/alliance-of-american-football-hosting-scouting-combine-for-players/ |accessdate=September 14, 2018 |work=WMC Action News 5.com |date=July 2, 2018}}</ref> By August 24, 2018, 205 players were signed.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Froyd |first1=Crissy |title=Zach Mettenberger and Antonio Andrews reunite in new pro league |url=https://titanswire.usatoday.com/2018/08/27/zach-mettenberger-antonio-andrews-american-alliance-of-football/ |accessdate=September 14, 2018 |work=Titans Wire |date=August 27, 2018}}</ref> These dates provided an opportunity for players cut at the NFL roster deadline, and each player signed a non-guaranteed three-year contract worth a total of $250,000 ($70,000 in 2019; $80,000 in 2020; $100,000 in 2021),<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espn.com/espn/story/_/id/26423928/source-aaf-immediately-suspend-operations |title=Source: AAF to immediately suspend operations |first=Michael |last=Rothstein |website=[[ESPN]] |date=April 2, 2019 |accessdate=April 2, 2019}}</ref> with performance-based and fan-interaction incentives allowing for players to earn more.<ref name=\"AP news\">{{cite web |last1=Wilner |first1=Barry |title=Alliance signs players cut by NFL teams for spring league |url=https://apnews.com/3accb15c06bd4747acf8d57ffbb5fb42 |website=AP News |accessdate=October 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2018, [[Starter (clothing line)|Starter]], through G-III Sports, which manufactured NFL jerseys and apparel in the 1980s and 1990s, was named the official on-field apparel and game-day uniform supplier for the AAF, marking a return for the brand to professional football after an almost 20 year absence.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Benjamin |first1=Cody |title=Alliance of American Football strikes multi-year uniform, apparel deal with Starter |url=https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/alliance-of-american-football-strikes-multi-year-uniform-apparel-deal-with-starter/ |website=CBSSports.com |date= July 24, 2018  |accessdate=October 2, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> On September 20, the league announced four eastern inaugural franchises' names and logos.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Benjamin |first1=Cody |title=LOOK: Alliance of American Football unveils logos of four pro teams that will debut in 2019 |url=https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/look-alliance-of-american-football-unveils-logos-of-four-pro-teams-that-will-debut-in-2019/ |accessdate=September 21, 2018 |work=CBSSports.com |date=September 20, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> The four western teams' logos and names were revealed five days later.<ref name=\"cbs0\">{{cite news |last1=Benjamin |first1=Cody |title=LOOK: Here's a full list of team names and logos from the Alliance of American Football |url=https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/look-heres-a-full-list-of-team-names-and-logos-from-the-alliance-of-american-football/ |accessdate=October 3, 2018 |work=CBSSports.com |date=September 25, 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Inaugural season===\n{{Main|2019 AAF season}}\nOn October 16, 2018, the Alliance announced its schedule (indicating the day and location, but not the time, of each game) which had two games each on Saturday and on Sunday most weekends.<ref name=azc>{{cite news |title=Alliance of American Football schedule released for Arizona Hotshots, other 7 teams |url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/sports/football/2018/10/16/alliance-american-football-arizona-hotshots-2019-schedule/1658993002/ |accessdate=November 8, 2018 |work=AZ Central |publisher=USA Today |date=October 16, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> Quarterback skills training camps were held at the [[Alamodome]] in [[San Antonio]] on November 12 through 14. On November 27, the league held a four-round [[2019 AAF QB Draft|\"Protect or Pick\" quarterback draft]] in the Esports Arena at [[Luxor Las Vegas]] and broadcast on [[CBS Sports Network]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Scott |first1=Dana |title=Alliance of American Football league to hold 'Protect or Pick' quarterback draft |url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/sports/football/2018/10/31/aaf-hold-new-protect-pick-quarterback-draft/1835643002/ |accessdate=November 5, 2018 |work=AZ Central |publisher=USA Today Network |date=October 31, 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe AAF began [[2019 AAF season|its inaugural, 10-week season]] on February 9, 2019.<ref name=\"espn\" /> The first points in AAF regular season history were scored by kicker [[Younghoe Koo]] of the [[Atlanta Legends]], who made a 38-yard field goal against the [[Orlando Apollos]]. The first touchdown came in the same game with Orlando quarterback [[Garrett Gilbert]] connecting with [[Jalin Marshall]] for a 16-yard score.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbssports.com/aaf/news/aaf-week-1-scores-highlights-spurrier-calls-philly-special-for-td-orlando-and-san-antonio-win-openers/ |title=AAF Week 1 scores, highlights: Spurrier calls 'Philly Special' for TD, Orlando and San Antonio win openers |first=Ben |last=Kercheval |website=[[CBS Sports]] |date=February 9, 2019 |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref> The first shutout was recorded by the [[Birmingham Iron]] when they defeated the [[Memphis Express]], 26\u20130, in Week 1.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbs42.com/news/local/iron-shutout-express-in-aaf-season-opener/1771548771 |title=Iron shutout Express in AAF season opener |first=Simone |last=Eli |website=cbs42.com |date=February 10, 2019 |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref> The first onside conversion (see Rules section, below) was attempted during Week 3, with Atlanta successfully completing a 48-yard pass against Birmingham.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://brobible.com/sports/article/aaf-onside-conversion-rule-fans-love/ |title=The AAF\u2019s Alternative Rule To The Onside Kick Was Used For The First Time Sunday And Fans Are In Love |first=Matt |last=Keohan |website=brobible.com |date=February 25, 2019 |accessdate=February 28, 2019}}</ref> The first [[Safety (gridiron football score)|safety]] was registered by Atlanta against the [[Arizona Hotshots]] in Week 4.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://aaf.com/murray-leads-legends-to-win-over-hotshots |title=Murray leads Legends to win over Hotshots |first=Jaylon |last=Thompson |website=AAF.com |date=March 4, 2019 |accessdate=March 4, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190306043950/https://aaf.com/murray-leads-legends-to-win-over-hotshots |archive-date=March 6, 2019 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The first [[Overtime (sports)|overtime]] game occurred in Week 7, with Memphis defeating Birmingham.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://aaf.com/news/iron-fall-to-express-overtime |title=Iron fall to Express in first overtime game in Alliance history |first=Marq |last=Burnett |website=AAF.com |date=March 25, 2019 |accessdate=March 25, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190325045557/https://aaf.com/news/iron-fall-to-express-overtime |archive-date=March 25, 2019 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nA four-team playoff was to be capped with the league's championship game, initially scheduled to be held at [[Sam Boyd Stadium]] near [[Las Vegas]]. After Dundon took over league operations, he moved the game to the [[Ford Center at the Star]] in [[Frisco, Texas]].<ref>{{cite web|agency=[[Associated Press|AP]]|url=http://www.espn.com/espn/story/_/id/26316149/aaf-shifts-title-game-vegas-frisco-texas|title=AAF shifts title game from Vegas to Frisco, Texas|website=[[ESPN]]|date=March 20, 2019|accessdate=March 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Cessation of operations====\nOn April 2, 2019, the AAF suspended all football operations, on orders from AAF chairman [[Thomas Dundon|Tom Dundon]].<ref name=disappointed/> League co-founder [[Bill Polian]] stated:\n\n{{Quote|I am extremely disappointed to learn Tom Dundon has decided to suspend all football operations of the Alliance of American Football. When Mr. Dundon took over, it was the belief of my co-founder, Charlie Ebersol, and myself that we would finish the season, pay our creditors, and make the necessary adjustments to move forward in a manner that made economic sense for all. The momentum generated by our players, coaches and football staff had us well positioned for future success. Regrettably, we will not have that opportunity.<ref name=disappointed>{{cite news |url=http://www.espn.com/espn/story/_/id/26423928/aaf-suspends-operations-polian-disappointed |title=AAF suspends operations; Polian 'disappointed' |first=Michael |last=Rothstein |website=[[ESPN]] |date=April 3, 2019}}</ref>}}\n\nPlayers found out about the suspension through the Internet before their coaches confirmed the news.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/the-inside-story-of-the-aa-fs-final-day-through-the-eyes-of-its-players-041510929.html|title=The inside story of the AAF's final day, through the eyes of its players|first=Terez|last=Paylor|work=Yahoo! Sports|date=April 3, 2019|accessdate=April 3, 2019}}</ref> Players were evicted from the hotels where their teams were being housed\u2014with some being personally charged for unpaid hotel bills<ref name=OCRyan/>\u2014and required to pay their own way home; they also lost their health insurance and were forced to cover their own medical bills from injuries sustained during play.<ref name=\"medical\">{{cite web|url=https://www.foxbusiness.com/features/aaf-players-booted-from-hotels-left-to-pay-medical-costs-out-of-pocket-report|title=AAF players booted from hotels, left to pay medical costs out of pocket: Report|first=Thomas|last=Barrabi|work=[[Fox Business Network]]|date=April 4, 2019|accessdate=April 4, 2019}}</ref> League employees were notified via an April 2 letter from the AAF board, which did not give a reason for ending the season,<ref name=disappointed/> that their jobs were terminated as of April 3 with no [[Severance package|severance]].<ref name=OCRyan>{{cite news |url=https://www.ocregister.com/2019/04/05/aaf-goes-under-inside-the-sudden-collapse-of-the-alliance-of-american-football/ |title=AAF goes under: Inside the sudden collapse of the Alliance of American Football |first=Ryan |last=Kartje |website=[[Orange County Register]] |date=April 5, 2019 |accessdate=April 5, 2019}}</ref> Ebersol and Dundon refused public comment;<ref name=OCRyan/> Ebersol would eventually speak out on April 17, stating that he had been advised not to speak by his attorneys. He insisted that the money he raised was there and had been vetted up until immediately before the season, claimed that reports of players being saddled with hotel and medical bills were either [[fake news]] or fraudulent charges, and could not ensure that all those owed money would be paid.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/SB-Blogs/Newsletter-Media/2019/04/17.aspx|title=SBJ Media: Charlie Ebersol Speaks|first=John|last=Ourand|work=Sports Business Journal|date=April 17, 2019|accessdate=April 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn April 4, the AAF announced through their official [[Twitter]] account that players were eligible to leave their contracts to sign with NFL teams.<ref name=\"Schwartz\"/> The contracts that players had originally signed included a stipulation that they could leave to sign with NFL teams at the conclusion of an AAF season.<ref>{{cite news |author=Florio, Mike |title=AAF players finally receive authorization to sign with NFL teams |url=https://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2019/04/04/aaf-players-finally-receive-authorization-to-sign-with-nfl-teams/ |website=profootballtalk.com |date=April 4, 2019 |accessdate=2019-04-04}}</ref> The league did not issue any public statement until April 6, when the AAF.com website was updated with a statement, which read in part:\n\n{{Quote|This week, we made the difficult decision to suspend all football operations for the Alliance of American Football. We understand the difficulty that this decision has caused for many people and for that we are very sorry. This is not the way we wanted it to end, but we are also committed to working on solutions for all outstanding issues to the best of our ability. Due to ongoing legal processes, we are unable to comment further or share details about the decision.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://aaf.com |title=Alliance of American Football (homepage) |accessdate=April 6, 2019}}</ref>}}\n\nAt the time its football operations were suspended, the AAF had played eight weeks out of a scheduled ten-week regular season.\n\n====Bankruptcy liquidation====\nOn April 17, the league filed for [[Chapter 7, Title 11, United States Code|Chapter 7]] bankruptcy ([[liquidation]]) in [[United States District Court for the Eastern District of Texas|Texas\u2019 Eastern District]].<ref name=Chapter7>{{Cite web|url=https://deadspin.com/aaf-officially-pulls-the-plug-files-for-bankruptcy-1834121723|title=AAF Officially Pulls The Plug, Files For Bankruptcy|last=Redford|first=Patrick|website=Deadspin|language=en-US|date=2019-04-17|access-date=2019-04-17}}</ref> In the filing, the league claimed assets of $11.3 million, liabilities of $48.3 million, and approximately $536,000 in cash.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=frntofficesport |number=1118584049491152897 |title=BREAKING: @TheAAF has filed for Chapter 7 Bankruptcy. |date=April 17, 2019 |accessdate=April 17, 2019}}</ref> The AAF counted its player contracts among its assets in the bankruptcy filing, blocking players from joining the [[Canadian Football League]].<ref>{{cite news |author=Florio, Mike |title=AAF refuses to release players for possible CFL employment |url=https://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2019/04/12/aaf-refuses-to-release-players-for-possible-cfl-employment/ |website=NBCSports.com |date=April 12, 2019 |accessdate=October 4, 2019}}</ref> This block was lifted a day after the bankruptcy filing.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=BenKercheval |number=1118712875328135168 |date=April 18, 2019 |title=Yes, to correct a previous tweet, I am told by a source that #AAF players can sign with CFL teams. My apologies on not being up to date on that. That\u2019s the updated situation.}}</ref>\n\nThe league's uniforms and equipment were stored in a lot in [[San Antonio, Texas]] and eventually auctioned off in July 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.expressnews.com/business/local/article/XFL-wants-to-score-bankrupt-football-league-s-13884443.php|title=XFL wants to score bankrupt football league\u2019s assets stored in San Antonio warehouse|first=Patrick|last=Danner|work=San Antonio Express-News|date=May 23, 2019|accessdate=May 24, 2019}}</ref> Former [[Arena Football League]] commissioner [[Jerry Kurz]] made the winning bid at $455,000, beating out bids from (among others) the [[XFL (2020)|revived XFL]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2019/07/08/former-arena-league-commissioner-buys-aaf-equipment-at-auction/ |title=Former Arena League commissioner buys AAF equipment at auction |website=[[NBC Sports]] |date=July 8, 2019}}</ref> The perpetually postponed [[Major League Football]] claimed it had agreed to purchase the equipment.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.otcmarkets.com/filing/conv_pdf?id=13557319&guid=mR2IUqr3iO8vn3h |title=MAJOR LEAGUE FOOTBALL INC FORM 10-K: Filed 07/29/19 for the Period Ending 04/30/19 |website=OTCMarkets.com |date=July 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Teams==\n{| class=\"plainrowheaders wikitable\"\n!Team<ref name=\"cbs0\" />\n!City\n!Stadium\n!Capacity\n!Head coach<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wilson |first1=Ryan |title=Alliance of American Football QB Draft: Aaron Murray, Christian Hackenberg highlight QBs taken in AAF event |url=https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/alliance-of-american-football-qb-draft-aaron-murray-christian-hackenberg-highlight-qbs-taken-in-aaf-event/ |accessdate=November 29, 2018 |work=CBSSports.com |date=November 28, 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n|-\n!style=background:#CE1126 colspan=\"7\"| {{color|#FFFFFF|Eastern Conference}}\n|-\n|'''[[Atlanta Legends]]'''\n| [[Atlanta|Atlanta, Georgia]] \n| [[Georgia State Stadium]] \n| align=center|24,333\n| [[Kevin Coyle]]\n|-\n| '''[[Birmingham Iron]]'''\n| [[Birmingham, Alabama]]\n| [[Legion Field]]\n| align=center|71,594\n| [[Tim Lewis]]\n|-\n| '''[[Memphis Express]]'''\n| [[Memphis, Tennessee]]\n| [[Liberty Bowl Memorial Stadium]]\n| align=center|58,325\n| [[Mike Singletary]]\n|-\n| '''[[Orlando Apollos]]'''\n| [[Orlando, Florida]]\n| [[Spectrum Stadium]]\n| align=center|44,206\n| [[Steve Spurrier]]\n|-\n!style=background:#153769 colspan=\"7\"| {{color|#FFFFFF|Western Conference}}\n|-\n| '''[[Arizona Hotshots]]'''\n| [[Tempe, Arizona]]\n| [[Sun Devil Stadium]]\n| align=center|57,078\n| [[Rick Neuheisel]]\n|-\n| '''[[Salt Lake Stallions]]'''\n| [[Salt Lake City|Salt Lake City, Utah]]\n| [[Rice\u2013Eccles Stadium]]\n| align=center|45,807\n| [[Dennis Erickson]]\n|-\n|'''[[San Antonio Commanders]]'''\n| [[San Antonio|San Antonio, Texas]] \n| [[Alamodome]] \n| align=center|64,000\n| [[Mike Riley]]\n|-\n| '''[[San Diego Fleet]]'''\n| [[San Diego|San Diego, California ]]\n| [[SDCCU Stadium]]\n| align=center|70,561\n| [[Mike Martz]]\n|}\n\n{{Location map+ |United States |width=600 |float=center |caption=Locations of teams for the 2019 AAF season.<br />[[File:Red pog.svg|8px]] Eastern Conference [[File:Blue pog.svg|8px]] Western Conference|places=\n         {{Location map~ |United States |lat=33.426389 |long=-111.9325   |label=[[Arizona Hotshots|Hotshots]]           |position=bottom  |mark=blue pog.svg}}\n         {{Location map~ |United States |lat=33.735278 |long=-84.389444  |label=[[Atlanta Legends|Legends]]            |position=top     |mark=red pog.svg}}\n         {{Location map~ |United States |lat=33.511389 |long=-86.842778  |label=[[Birmingham Iron|Iron]]         |position=bottom  |mark=red pog.svg}}\n         {{Location map~ |United States |lat=35.121111 |long=-89.9775    |label=[[Memphis Express|Express]]            |position=top     |mark=Red pog.svg}}\n         {{Location map~ |United States |lat=28.6091   |long=-81.1924    |label=[[Orlando Apollos|Apollos]]            |position=bottom  |mark=Red pog.svg}}\n\t {{Location map~ |United States |lat=40.76     |long=-111.849    |label=[[Salt Lake Stallions|Stallions]] |position=bottom  |mark=blue pog.svg}}\n         {{Location map~ |United States |lat=29.4241   |long=-98.4936    |label=[[San Antonio Commanders|Commanders]] |position=top     |mark=blue pog.svg}}\n         {{Location map~ |United States |lat=32.783056 |long=-117.119444 |label=[[San Diego Fleet|Fleet]]          |position=top     |mark=blue pog.svg}}\n         }}\n\n==Rules==\nEbersol deliberately avoided making radical changes to the rules of the game so as to make it recognizable to the U.S. public. He stated that he used the average length of a feature film, slightly over two hours, as the basis for a typical fan's [[attention span]].<ref name=ebersolprofile/>\n\n* Teams had 52 players on each roster, with some selected by a territorial draft.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://aaf.com/all-eight-alliance-teams-determine-52-player-rosters|title=The Alliance of American Football sets final rosters|work=Alliance of American Football|date=January 29, 2019|accessdate=January 31, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190201013555/https://aaf.com/all-eight-alliance-teams-determine-52-player-rosters|archive-date=February 1, 2019|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The territory assigned to a team consisted of at least five colleges plus designated professional teams, one [[Canadian Football League]], and four NFL teams (players from colleges outside the AAF footprint being allocated based on their most recent professional team). Only one quarterback could be taken from their region.<ref name=\"espn0\">{{cite news |last1=Rovell |first1=Darren |title=AAF players to get 3-year, $250K contracts |url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/24076702/alliance-american-football-players-get-3-year-250k-contracts |accessdate=September 14, 2018 |work=ESPN.com |date=July 12, 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n** For the inaugural season, a quarterbacks-only \"[[2019 AAF QB Draft|Protect or Pick]]\" draft was conducted in November 2018 in which teams could retain their allocated quarterback or select an unprotected quarterback from another team.<ref>{{cite web|last=Florio|first=Mike|url=https://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2018/10/31/aaf-to-conduct-unusual-draft-process-for-allocating-quarterbacks/|title=AAF to conduct unusual draft process for allocating quarterbacks|publisher=[[Profootballtalk.com]]|date=October 31, 2018|accessdate=November 3, 2018}}</ref>\n* Telecasts featured no [[television timeout]]s and 60 percent fewer \"full-screen commercials,\" with the league aiming for an approximate real-time game length of 150 minutes, down from just over 180 in the NFL.<ref name=\"xfl_competitor\">{{cite news|last1=Gartland|first1=Dan|title=8-team XFL competitor plans to launch in February 2019|url=https://www.si.com/nfl/2018/03/20/alliance-american-football-xfl-competitor-league-launch|accessdate=March 21, 2018|work=SI.com|publisher=Time, Inc.|date=March 20, 2018}}</ref><ref name=wapo_aaf>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/redskins/alliance-of-american-football-to-kick-off-after-super-bowl/2018/03/20/f3ac7db8-2c4f-11e8-8dc9-3b51e028b845_story.html |title=Alliance of American Football to kick off after Super Bowl |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=March 20, 2018 |accessdate=March 20, 2018}}</ref> In turn, the AAF aimed to charge more money for the remaining commercial slots, also alluding to [[product placement]] opportunities that did not interrupt the game telecast.<ref name=ebersolprofile/>\n* There were no [[Conversion (gridiron football)|extra point kicks]]; teams had to attempt [[two-point conversion]]s after a touchdown.\n* Defenses were forbidden from advancing (\"rushing\") more than five players on or across the line of scrimmage, and no defensive player could [[blitz (gridiron football)|cross the line of scrimmage]] from more than two yards outside the [[offensive tackle]]s.<ref name=\"skyjudge\"/> The \"illegal defense\" penalty for violating these rules was a 15-yard penalty.\n* There were no [[Kickoff (gridiron football)|kickoffs]]; possession at the start of each half, and after touchdowns and field goals, began on a team's own 25-yard line, in line with the NFL [[touchback]]s. After a [[safety (gridiron football score)|safety]], the scoring team received possession at their own 35-yard line.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://apnews.com/b298f69df360428091c24079bb814f32 |title=AAF kicks off without kickoffs, but with SkyJudge |agency=[[Associated Press|AP]] |date=February 5, 2019 |accessdate=February 28, 2019}}</ref>\n** In lieu of an [[onside kick]], a team could keep possession of the ball by attempting an \"onside conversion\", a scrimmage play from their own 28-yard line and gaining at least 12 yards (essentially, a fourth-and-12 play).<ref>{{cite web|last=Goldberg|first=Jeff|url=https://aaf.com/safe-to-say-on-side-conversion-play-will-generate-excitement|title=Safe to say, on-side conversion play will generate excitement|work=Alliance of American Football|date=January 28, 2019|accessdate=January 28, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190129064125/https://aaf.com/safe-to-say-on-side-conversion-play-will-generate-excitement|archive-date=January 29, 2019|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> A team was not allowed to attempt such a play after a field goal or touchdown unless it was trailing by 17 or more points, or during the final two minutes of the first half, or during the final five minutes of the second half.<ref>AAF broadcast on CBS Sports Network, 3 March 2019</ref><ref name=\"newrules\">{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/2019/02/06/alliance-american-football-new-league-offers-timely-change-game/2797835002/|title=Alliance of American Football's SkyJudge might have prevented NFC Championship no-call|work=Associated Press|date=February 8, 2019|accessdate=February 8, 2019}}</ref> The onside conversion play was also available after any [[Safety (gridiron football score)|safety]],{{citation needed|date=March 2019}} played from the 18-yard line.<ref name=\"skyjudge\"/>\n* The [[play clock]] ran only 35 seconds, five seconds shorter than in the NFL, but still longer than the CFL's 20 seconds, timed from the spotting of the football. (The league originally proposed a 30-second play clock,<ref name=wapo_aaf/> but Ebersol concluded it would negatively impact the quality of play.)<ref name=ebersolprofile/>\n* Players could not throw the football into the stands or hand it off to a spectator following a touchdown.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=MikePereira |number=1095088703234486272 |title=He will not get a fine and won\u2019t be penalized if he does it again. It is only a foul if a player deliberately throws it and hands it into stands. If a spiked ball bounces into the stands, no foul. It should not have been called. |date=February 11, 2019 |accessdate=March 27, 2019}}</ref> While other leagues (particularly the NCAA) have similar rules in place using rationale based on sportsmanship, the primary motivation for the AAF rule appears to be economic as its footballs (manufactured by [[Wilson Sporting Goods]] and marked with distinctive red, blue, and white stripes) contain expensive tracking technology. The penalty for such behavior was [[unsportsmanlike conduct]], a 15-yard penalty, and if it is determined to be deliberate, a fine can be assessed to the offending player.<ref name=nosouvenirs>{{cite web|url=http://www.footballzebras.com/2019/02/how-the-aafs-strict-no-souvenirs-rule-claimed-its-first-victim/|title=How the AAF\u2019s strict \"no souvenirs\" rule claimed its first victim|work=Football Zebras|date=February 11, 2019|accessdate=February 13, 2019}}</ref> Other [[touchdown celebration]]s are generally tolerated.\n** [[Trent Richardson]] of the [[Birmingham Iron]] was penalized during the first week of AAF play, when a ball he [[Spike (gridiron football)|spike]]d after scoring a touchdown bounced into the stands. AAF officials later determined that Richardson's actions were accidental and did not assess the fine, also apologizing for the penalty.<ref name=nosouvenirs/>\n* There were no automatic [[Replay review in gridiron football|instant replay reviews]] of scoring plays or turnovers as there are in the NFL. Each team was given two coach's challenges, which they could use at any time outside the [[two-minute warning]], and received a third if both challenges were successful. After the two-minute warning in each half and during overtime, the replay booth had sole authority to call for a replay review.<ref name=wapo_aaf/>\n* Outside organizations handled head-safety protocols.<ref name=\"vty\" />\n* In the event of a tie at the end of regulation, a single [[overtime (sports)|overtime]] period would be played, under the [[high school football]] rules of the \"[[Kansas Playoff]].\" Each team would begin on their opponent's 10-yard line and be given one possession (four downs) to score, with no [[field goal]]s allowed. Had a score remained tied after each team was given their possession, the game would end in a tie. Both teams would be given one timeout per overtime possession. The coin toss winner could choose to possess first or defer.<ref name=ebersolprofile/> Had the AAF reached the postseason, accounts differed on what system would be used; early reports had repeated rounds of the Kansas Playoff played until a winner was determined,<ref name=ebersolprofile/> but later reports stated that the AAF would use [[Sudden death (sport)|sudden death]] ([[golden point]]), which had been abolished at all other levels of football by the time of the AAF's debut.<ref name=BRplayoffs>{{cite web |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2823602-how-the-aaf-playoffs-and-schedule-work |title=How the AAF Playoffs and Schedule Work |website=[[Bleacher Report]] |date=March 6, 2019 |accessdate=March 17, 2019}}</ref>\n* Playoffs would have consisted of four teams, the top two teams from each conference.<ref name=azc/>\n* Officiating crews had [[Official (American football)#Eight-official system|eight members on the field]], similar to NCAA Division I football, instead of the [[Official (American football)#Standard seven-official system|standard seven-official system]] used in the NFL and CFL (the eighth officiating member was the center judge). AAF officiating also had a ninth member, called a sky judge, an off-the-field official who reviews every play using technology like a booth review. The sky judge could call or take away [[penalty (gridiron football)|penalties]] missed or made by the field officials.<ref name=\"skyjudge\">{{cite news|last=Munz|first=Jason|url=https://www.commercialappeal.com/story/sports/2019/02/07/aaf-introduce-sky-judge-rule-changes-alliance-football-charlie-ebersol-hines-ward-bill-polian/2783393002/|title=Sky judge and the world of tomorrow: A look at the AAF's notable rule differences|newspaper=[[The Commercial Appeal]]|date=February 7, 2019|accessdate=February 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Business==\nThe Alliance operated as a single entity, with all teams owned and operated by the league, under the name Legendary Field Exhibitions LLC.<ref name=wapo_aaf/> Some of the investors in the AAF included [[Peter Thiel]]'s [[Founders Fund]], [[The Chernin Group]] (which owns [[Barstool Sports]]), [[Jared Allen]], Slow Ventures, [[Adrian Fenty]], Charles King's M Ventures, and [[Keith Rabois]].<ref name=\"vty\"/><ref name=xfl_competitor/> Long-term plans were for the AAF to sell franchises to individual owners.<ref name=leagueonfire/>\n\n[[MGM Resorts International]] made an investment in the AAF tech platform,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Crupi |first1=Anthony |title=The Alliance of American Football bets on success where others have failed |url=https://adage.com/article/media/alliance-american-football-gambles-success/314871/ |accessdate=October 3, 2018 |work=Ad Age |date=September 10, 2018 |language=en|quote=Per terms of the deal, MGM also will invest in the AAF tech platform, ...}}</ref> and entered a three-year sponsorship agreement to become the league's official sports betting sponsor and exclusive gaming partner. The deal marked the first time any sports organization had sold exclusive in-game betting rights to a sportsbook.<ref name=\"USA today\">{{cite web |last1=Gleeson |first1=Scott |title=Alliance of American Football league, spring alternative to NFL, reveals gambling-focused strategy |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/2018/09/11/alliance-american-football-league-reveals-gambling-focused-strategy/1265465002/ |website=USA TODAY |date=September 11, 2018 |accessdate=October 2, 2018 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Rovell |first1=Darren |title=AAF league to have enhanced in-game betting |url=http://www.espn.com/chalk/story/_/id/24632798/alliance-american-football-enhanced-live-game-betting |website=ESPN.com |date=September 10, 2018 |accessdate=October 2, 2018 |language=en }}</ref> [[Scott Butera]], MGM's director of interactive gaming (the division that signed an agreement with the AAF), was formerly the commissioner of the [[Arena Football League]] before his 2018 ouster.<ref name=whyaafinvestor/> Under the terms of the agreement, MGM Resorts International owned all rights to the tech platform in the event the league ceases operations, preventing an investor from buying the league solely for access to the technology.<ref name=dundondoesntown>{{cite web|url=https://www.actionnetwork.com/nfl/aaf-folds-tom-dundon-technology|first=Darren|last=Rovell|title=Sources: Tom Dundon Doesn\u2019t Own AAF\u2019s Gambling-Forward Tech Arm|work=The Action Network|date=April 6, 2019|accessdate=April 7, 2019}}</ref> Gambling functions were never implemented on the league's app,<ref name=dundondoesntown/> and many planned features for the app never materialized due to technical glitches and impracticality.<ref name=leagueonfire/>\n\nThe league also had player bonuses and scholarships, with player bonuses based on performance and fan interaction, players were to earn a year's scholarship in post-secondary education for each season of play.<ref name=\"wapo_aaf\" /> Players got three-year, non-guaranteed contracts worth $250,000 plus health insurance with an escape clause to go to the NFL.<ref name=\"espn0\"/> The three-year contract was believed to be purposely targeting the XFL to prevent second-tier professional players from signing with the XFL if they played in the AAF in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2018/09/01/xfl-sends-up-first-salvo-in-looming-aaf-feud/|title=XFL sends up first salvo in looming AAF feud|first=Mike|last=Florio|work=ProFootballTalk.com|date=September 1, 2018|accessdate=September 18, 2018}}</ref> XFL commissioner [[Oliver Luck]] stated that he did not believe that such a clause would hold up in court after the AAF collapsed, and that the XFL would be willing to sign AAF players.<ref>https://xflnewshub.com/xfl-news/luck-talks-aaf-folding/</ref> The league also has an incentive system that pays members of a team's offensive and defensive units for statistical achievements and also pays players to perform [[community service]]; the exact details of this incentive system were not yet finalized at the start of the 2019 season.<ref name=ebersolprofile/> Players are assigned to each team by way of a centralized process that is largely a [[trade secret]].<ref name=ebersolprofile/> The league showed willingness to offer more money to marquee players; [[Landry Jones]] noted that Ebersol had personally promised a salary of over $1,000,000 to Jones if he played for the San Antonio Commanders; when Jones pressed Ebersol on when he would be paid, Ebersol became evasive, leading Jones to reject the offer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/espn/story/_/id/28640013/landry-jones-face-xfl-does-want-be|title=Landry Jones is the face of the XFL. Does he want to be?|first=Brendan|last=Meyer|work=ESPN.com|date=February 6, 2020|access-date=February 6, 2020}}</ref> [[Matt McGloin]] likewise turned down the AAF, both because of his skepticism over the league and the birth of his child.<ref>{{cite news |author=Kaye, Mike |title=XFL 2020: How ex-Eagles QB Matt McGloin\u2019s son influenced his return to football with New York Guardians |url=https://www.nj.com/eagles/2020/02/xfl-2020-how-ex-eagles-qb-matt-mcgloins-son-influenced-his-return-to-football-with-new-york-guardians-qa-with-penn-state-alum.html |website=NJ.com |date=February 7, 2020 |accessdate=February 16, 2020}}</ref> For the fans, in addition to a [[Fantasy football (American)|fantasy league]] built into mobile broadcasts, there are low ticket prices (each team have a $35/game sideline seat option) and inexpensive food at games.<ref name=\"wapo_aaf\" />  When the league abruptly folded, the league left players to personally pay outstanding bills for their own hotels, as well as their transportation home and even their medical bills from injuries sustained during play.<ref name=\"medical\"/>\n\nThe AAF coaching salaries varied by title, with $500,000 for head coaches, $200\u2013250,000 for coordinators, and $75\u2013150,000 for position coaches. Each AAF team employed between 11 and 13 total coaches, putting the total coaching staff expenditures at around $2 million per staff and $16 million for the entire league.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://footballscoop.com/news/sources-aaf-coaching-salaries-better-might-think/|title=Sources: AAF coaching salaries are better than you might think|first=Zach|last=Barnett|date=February 13, 2019|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Dundon investment===\nOn February 18, 2019, the league announced that [[Tom Dundon]], whose other holdings include the [[Carolina Hurricanes]] of the [[National Hockey League]] (NHL) and [[TopGolf]], agreed to invest $250 million into the league.<ref name=tomdundon>{{cite news|url=http://africa.espn.com/nhl/story/_/id/26030221/hurricanes-owner-tom-dundon-invests-250m-aaf|title=Hurricanes owner Tom Dundon invests $250M in AAF|work=ESPN.com|date=February 19, 2019|accessdate=February 19, 2019}}</ref> He was also named the new chairman of the AAF,<ref name=dundonathletic /> and Dundon reportedly received a majority stake in the league in exchange for his investment.{{cn|date=October 2019}} Dundon's investment was initially reported to be due to the league being in danger of not making payroll.<ref name=dundonathletic>{{cite web|url=https://theathletic.com/825580/2019/02/18/nhl-owner-rescues-fledgling-aaf-with-much-needed-cash-infusion/|title=NHL owner rescues fledgling AAF with much-needed cash infusion|first=David|last=Glenn|work=[[The Athletic]]|url-access=limited|date=February 18, 2019|accessdate=February 19, 2019}}</ref> It was later reported that the payroll issue was due to a glitch in the league's changing of payroll companies, and that Dundon's investment had already been planned.<ref name=CBS19feb19>{{cite news |title=AAF gets $250 million investment from Hurricanes owner Tom Dundon, dismisses report of financial difficulty |url=https://www.cbssports.com/aaf/news/aaf-gets-250-million-investment-from-hurricanes-owner-tom-dundon-dismisses-report-of-financial-difficulty/ |accessdate=19 February 2019 |work=[[CBS Sports]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |date=19 February 2019}}</ref> Dundon later backtracked on his previous claim of a $250 million investment, noting that he had not actually delivered a $250 million [[lump sum]] to the league. Dundon planned on incrementally investing in the league, using $250 million as a theoretical maximum based on if the league were to \"aggressively expand,\" and reserved the right to pull out of the league at any time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/Daily/Morning-Buzz/2019/02/25/Dundon.aspx|title= Tom Dundon Confirms Incremental $250M Investment In AAF|first=Daniel|last=Kaplan|work=Sports Business Journal|date=February 25, 2019|accessdate=February 25, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com:443/en/Daily/Issues/2019/02/22/Leagues%20and%20Governing%20Bodies/AAF.aspx|title=Sources: Dundon Has Committed, Not Yet Invested, Money In AAF|website=www.sportsbusinessdaily.com}}</ref> At the time of the reported April 2 suspension, Dundon had invested an estimated $70 million into the AAF.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.actionnetwork.com/nfl/aaf-suspending-football-operations-darren-rovell|title=Rovell: AAF Suspending Football Operations Immediately|first=Darren|last=Rovell|work=The Action Network|date=April 2, 2019|accessdate=April 2, 2019}}</ref> He had drastically reduced unnecessary expenses and mostly abandoned the technology platform by the end of the league's operations in a desperate attempt to keep the league financially viable.<ref name=leagueonfire/>\n\nEbersol had admitted prior to the start of the season that, on numerous occasions, the AAF had come dangerously close to folding before its first game due to various unstated complications.<ref name=ebersolprofile/> When asked whether some of the AAF's initial investors had dropped out, Ebersol declined to answer.<ref name=whyaafinvestor>{{cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/sports/more-sports/why-aaf-investor-sees-long-lifespan-for-new-football-league/ar-BBTWIKh?li=BBnba9I&srcref=rss|title= Why AAF investor sees long lifespan for new football league |work=USA Today|author=Brent Schrotenboer and Kevin Allen|date=February 22, 2019|accessdate=February 22, 2019}}</ref> After the league suspended operations, it was revealed that one of the league's major investors, former [[Minnesota Vikings]] minority owner [[Reggie Fowler]], had indeed pulled his funding after the inaugural game, necessitating the abrupt sale to Dundon.<ref name=OCRyan/> It came out in late April that Fowler's funds had been frozen by the Department of Justice, after Fowler's indictment on charges of [[money laundering]] for [[cryptocurrency exchanges]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.si.com/nfl/2019/04/30/alliance-american-football-aaf-collapse-charlie-ebersol-tom-dundon|title=The Curious Rise and Spectacular Crash of the Alliance of American Football|work=Sports Illustrated|first=Conor|last=Orr|date=1 May 2019|accessdate=2 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn early March 2019, it was revealed by Bill Polian that the AAF and [[National Football League]] were in informal discussions about a system where players under contract to NFL teams could be loaned to AAF teams. The idea would have been be for NFL teams to assign their third-string quarterback and other players from the bottom half of their roster and practice squads to the AAF to gain more playing time in a similar system to what used to be in place during the existence of [[NFL Europe]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/2019/03/06/aaf-nfl-informal-talks-loaning-younger-players/3085167002/|title=Will NFL teams loan QBs and other players to AAF? Informal talks ongoing|website=USA TODAY|language=en|access-date=2019-03-07}}</ref> This would have in effect made the AAF an official developmental league of the NFL. Dundon sought a change in the NFL's [[collective bargaining agreement]] to protect AAF players who may get injured and miss NFL playing time by ensuring the players still earned a salary from the NFL during their recovery. In late March, Dundon stated that, in reference to the [[National Football League Players Association]] (NFLPA) and its reluctance to cooperate out of concern for injuries, if they are \"not going to give us young players, we can't be a development league\". He added that the AAF was looking at its options, including discontinuing the league if the NFLPA wasn't willing to work with the league.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/2019/03/27/alliance-of-american-football-aaf-tom-dundon-future-nflpa/3287922002/ |title=Majority investor: Alliance of American Football in danger of being discontinued without NFLPA help |first1=Kevin |last1=Allen |first2=Mike |last2=Jones |website=[[USA Today]] |date=March 27, 2019 |accessdate=March 27, 2019}}</ref> [[Profootballtalk.com]] reported shortly thereafter, citing unnamed sources, that if Dundon's demands were not met, he was willing to end his investment before the season ended, possibly as soon as after Week 8, which would cut off the league's cash flow and force it to immediately fold with the playoffs and championship left unplayed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2019/03/27/aaf-may-not-make-it-beyond-this-weekend/|title=AAF may not make it beyond this weekend|first=Mike|last=Florio|work=Profootballtalk.com|date=March 27, 2019|accessdate=March 28, 2019}}</ref> As Week 8 passed, Dundon reiterated his stance on April 1, stating he was still willing to pull his funding before the next week's game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.orlandosentinel.com/sports/open-mike/os-sp-aaf-folding-steve-spurrier-tom-dundon-alliance-of-american-football-20190401-story.html|title=Orlando Apollos coach Steve Spurrier refuses to believe reports AAF could fold this week|first=Mike|last=Bianchi|work=Orlando Sentinel|date=April 1, 2019|accessdate=April 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\nUltimately the AAF lost an estimated $88 million overall, earning only $12 million in revenue against its $100 million expenses.<ref name=\"espnpostmortem\">{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/26957796/inside-short-unhappy-life-alliance-american-football|title=Inside the short, unhappy life of the Alliance of American Football|first=Seth|last=Wickersham|first2=Michael|last2=Rothstein|work=[[ESPN.com]]|date=June 13, 2019|accessdate=June 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Legal matters===\nIn late February 2019, a lawsuit by a venture capitalist in Los Angeles became public, as the AAF issued a statement denying a claim by Robert Vanech that the league was his idea and that he had a handshake agreement with Charlie Ebersol; Vanech is seeking financial damages and 50 percent ownership of the league.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2019/02/25/aaf-disputes-league-was-robert-vanechs-idea/ |title=AAF disputes league was Robert Vanech\u2019s idea |first=Charean |last=Williams |website=[[NBC Sports]] |date=February 25, 2019 |accessdate=February 25, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espn.com/espn/story/_/id/26079108/aaf-being-sued-man-claiming-league-was-idea |title=AAF being sued by man claiming the league was his idea |first=Michael |last=Rothstein |website=[[ESPN]] |date=February 25, 2019 |accessdate=February 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAlso in late February, the league revealed that it had been unable to secure a league-wide [[worker's compensation]] insurance policy prior to the start of the season, forcing the Orlando Apollos to move its practice operations to [[Kingsland, Georgia]], and commute to Orlando for games, as Florida does not consider professional athletes to be eligible for worker's compensation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.orlandosentinel.com/sports/open-mike/os-sp-orlando-apollos-workmans-comp-georgia-practice-20190219-story.html#nt=oft12aH-3gp2|title= Orlando Apollos will start practicing in Georgia because of Florida workers' compensation laws |first=Mike|last=Bianchi|work=Orlando Sentinel|date=February 20, 2019|accessdate=February 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, after the league suspended football operations, two players\u2014punter [[Colton Schmidt]] of the Birmingham Iron and linebacker Reggie Northrup of the Orlando Apollos\u2014filed a [[class action]] lawsuit in California, claiming that they were misled about the financial viability of the league and that the league entered contracts with players in bad faith.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://deadspin.com/lawsuit-claims-the-aaf-intentionally-misled-and-defraud-1833959393 |title=Lawsuit Claims The AAF Intentionally Misled And Defrauded Its Players |first=Gabe |last=Fernandez |website=[[Deadspin]] |date=April 10, 2019 |accessdate=April 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAlso in April, two former front-office league employees filed a class action lawsuit in California, claiming that the league violated the [[Worker Adjustment and Retraining Notification Act of 1988]], which requires large companies to give at least a 60-day advanced notice before large [[layoff]]s.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2019/04/10/former-aaf-employees-allege-defunct-pro-football-league-violated-labor-law/ |title=Former AAF employees allege defunct pro football league violated labor law |first=Nico |last=Savidge |website=[[The Mercury News]] |date=April 10, 2019 |accessdate=April 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\nReggie Fowler was arrested April 30, 2019, on charges related to operating a massive [[cryptocurrency]] scam in 2018, the funds for which were used to fund his AAF investments.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://qz.com/1611214/aaf-football-league-collapse-tied-to-ifinexs-crypto-bank-scandal/|title=How the collapse of a football league is tied to crypto\u2019s biggest banking scandal|first=Matthew|last=DeSilva|date=May 3, 2019|work=Quartz|accessdate=May 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Key people==\n\n\n===Executives===<!-- limit to notable persons, those with their own Wikipedia page -->\n* [[Charlie Ebersol]], co-founder and CEO\n* [[Bill Polian]], co-founder and Head of Football\n* [[John McKay Jr.|J. K. McKay]], Head of Football Operations\n* [[Troy Polamalu]], Head of Player Relations\n* [[Hines Ward]], Head of Football Development\n* [[Tom Veit]], Head of Business Operations\n* [[Mike Pereira]], Officiating Consultant\n* [[Dean Blandino]], Officiating Consultant\n; Player Engagement Board Of Advisors\n* [[Jared Allen]]\n* [[Justin Tuck]]\nSource:<ref>{{cite web |url=https://aaf.com/leadership |title=Leadership |website=aaf.com |accessdate=February 28, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190212011223/https://aaf.com/leadership |archive-date=February 12, 2019 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Board of Directors===\n* [[Thomas Dundon|Tom Dundon]], chairman<ref name=CBS19feb19/>\n* [[Dick Ebersol]]<ref name=\"vty\" /> (ousted midseason)<ref name=leagueonfire/>\n* [[Keith Rabois]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Balakrishnan |first1=Anita |last2=Salinas |first2=Sara |title=Peter Thiel's venture firm is backing a new football league to rival the NFL |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/03/20/peter-thiels-founders-fund-is-backing-alliance-of-american-football.html |website=CNBC |accessdate=September 4, 2018 |date=March 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Media ==\nAs part of its formation, the AAF announced broadcast deals with [[CBS Sports]];<ref name=vty>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2018/digital/news/alliance-american-football-league-cbs-2019-charlie-ebersol-1202731190/|title=New Pro Football League Sets 2019 Debut With CBS Sports Pact|last=Spangler|first=Todd|date=March 20, 2018|work=Variety|access-date=March 21, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> opening day (consisting of two regionally-televised games)<ref name=\"pft\"/> was scheduled for [[CBS]], as well as a playoff semifinal and the championship game.<ref name=vty/><ref>{{cite magazine|last=Feldman|first=Jacob|url=https://www.si.com/tech-media/2019/03/14/cbs-adds-alliance-american-football-games-network-charlie-ebersol-future-league|title=CBS Adds More Alliance of American Football Games to Broadcast Schedule|magazine=[[Sports Illustrated]]|date=March 14, 2019|accessdate=March 14, 2019}}</ref> The telecasts made extensive use of on-field microphones (with head coaches and quarterbacks also miked), and [[Skycam]]s (with two deployed for each game, with one along the sideline, as opposed to having more than one high camera). Half of the games broadcast each week were produced off-site from Sneaky Big Studios in [[Scottsdale, Arizona]]: graphics (which were provided by CBS), Skycam operations, and commentary were performed remotely from the Scottsdale site, as well as studio coverage for all games (via a [[virtual studio]]).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sportsvideo.org/2019/02/08/at-dawn-of-aaf-era-technological-innovation-drives-live-productions/|title=At Dawn of AAF Era, Technological Innovation Drives Live Productions|last=Dachman|first=Jason|website=Sports Video Group|language=en|access-date=2019-02-21}}</ref> Ebersol did not disclose whether or not the league was [[brokered programming|buying the airtime]] or receiving the airtime for free as part of a partnership agreement.<ref name=\"ap20190213\"/> After the season ended, it was confirmed that the AAF had resorted to buying airtime and was unlikely to be able to extract a rights fee from any of its partners for its foreseeable future, a factor in Dundon's decision to withdraw his investment.<ref name=leagueonfire>{{cite web|first=Conor|last=Orr|url=https://www.si.com/nfl/2019/04/30/alliance-american-football-aaf-collapse-charlie-ebersol-tom-dundon|title=League on Fire: The Curious Rise and Spectacular Crash of the Alliance of American Football|work=[[Sports Illustrated]]|date=May 1, 2019|accessdate=May 5, 2019}}</ref> CBS broadcast an ad for the league during its coverage of [[Super Bowl LIII]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.philly.com/sports/nbc-sports-philadelphia-marc-farzetta-amy-fadool-kane-philly-sports-talk-cbs-alliance-american-football-20190123.html|title=NBC Sports Philadelphia\u2019s studio shows will soon look a lot different|last=Tornoe|first=Rob|website=Philly.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-03}}</ref>\n\n[[CBS Sports Network]] aired one game per week, and was scheduled to air one of the playoff games.<ref name=vty/> In addition to local stations,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Steinberg |first1=Leigh |title=AAF: The League That Fills The NFL Offseason Void |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/leighsteinberg/2018/07/26/aaf-the-league-that-fills-the-nfl-offseason-void/ |accessdate=October 24, 2018 |work=Forbes |date=July 26, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> [[TNT (U.S. TV network)|TNT]] was announced as broadcasting two games per season (one regular season and a playoff game which later was expanded to include three regular season games) while [[NFL Network]] aired two weekly games.<ref name=\"Turner, NFL Net\">{{cite web|last=Ourand|first=John|url=https://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/Daily/Morning-Buzz/2019/01/31/AAF.aspx|title=Alliance Of American Football Signs Deals With Turner, NFL Net|publisher=SportsBusiness Daily|date=January 31, 2019|accessdate=January 31, 2019}}</ref> The league's [[mobile app]] offered live streaming of all games except those broadcast on CBS Sports Network, billed as \"AAF Raw\" as most of the AAF live streams contain [[Announcerless game#Legacy|no announcers]] or on-screen graphics, while Turner's [[Bleacher Report|B/R Live]] streamed one game a week.<ref name=\"Turner, NFL Net\" /> Integrated [[Fantasy football (American)|fantasy]] games were available through the AAF site and app as well.<ref name=\"espn\" />\n\nCBSSN's game of the week was called by [[Ben Holden]], [[Adam Archuleta]], and [[John Schriffen]].<ref name=\"pft\">{{cite web|url=https://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2018/12/20/cbs-unveils-aaf-broadcast-teams/|first=Mike|last=Florio|title=CBS unveils AAF broadcast teams|work=Pro Football Talk|date=December 20, 2016|accessdate=December 26, 2018}}</ref> NFL Network's broadcast team for week one consisted of [[Dan Hellie]] on play-by-play and [[Marvin Lewis]] on color commentary.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/NFLMedia/status/1093604994022948864|title=.@nflnetwork's coverage of @TheAAF kicks off Sunday at 8p ET w/ the Salt Lake City Stallions vs. Arizona Hotshots. @DanHellie @MJD & Marvin Lewis are on the call|first=N. F. L.|last=Media|date=February 7, 2019|accessdate=February 12, 2019}}</ref> TNT's broadcast team consisted of [[Brian Anderson (sportscaster)|Brian Anderson]] on play-by-play, Lewis on color commentary, and [[Maurice Jones-Drew]] as sideline reporter. The league did not use set announcer pairings, rotating numerous hosts (several of them from the ''[[NFL on CBS]]'' and the ''[[SEC on CBS]]'') on both play-by-play and color commentary, depending on availability.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://awfulannouncing.com/cbs/marvin-lewis-terrell-davis-and-andrew-siciliano-among-new-names-revealed-for-aaf-broadcasts.html|title=Marvin Lewis, Terrell Davis and Andrew Siciliano among new names revealed for AAF broadcasts|date=2019-02-02|website=Awful Announcing|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-09}}</ref>\n\n[[Sirius XM Radio]], a [[satellite radio]] service, carried a select Game of the Week.<ref name=\"XMRadio\">{{cite web |last1=Alper |first1=Josh |title=SiriusXM will air AAF games |url=https://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2019/02/07/siriusxm-will-air-aaf-games/ |website=NBCsports.com |publisher=NBC Universal |accessdate=6 March 2019}}</ref> Additionally, teams made broadcast deals with local radio affiliates.<ref name=\"SAradio\">{{cite web |title=SAN ANTONIO COMMANDERS ANNOUNCE ESPN SAN ANTONIO 1250 AM/94.5 FM AS OFFICIAL RADIO PARTNER |url=https://www.espnsa.com/san-antonio-commanders-announce-espn-san-antonio-1250-am-94-5-fm-as-official-radio-partner/ |website=ESPN San Antonio |accessdate=6 March 2019 |date=7 January 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"SDradio\">{{cite web |title=XTRA 1360 to be Fleet's flagship station in 2019 |url=https://aaf.com/xtra-1360-to-be-fleets-flagship-station-in-2019 |website=aaf.com |accessdate=6 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190209124238/https://aaf.com/xtra-1360-to-be-fleets-flagship-station-in-2019 |archive-date=February 9, 2019 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"OrlandoRadio\">{{cite web |title=Orlando Apollo's radio deal |url=https://www.bizjournals.com/orlando/news/2018/12/04/orlando-apollos-pro-football-team-snags-radio-deal.html |website=www.bizjournals.com |accessdate=6 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Critics===\nThe AAF received mixed to positive reviews opening night. [[Profootballtalk.com]], in a mostly positive review, praised the league's television product and choice of markets that would embrace the league, singling out the live look-ins at the replay booth during coach's challenges as an innovation that could transfer to the NFL's television broadcasts. The on-field level of play was somewhat less well-received, being compared to [[NFL preseason]] levels, with numerous offensive miscues.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2019/02/10/aaf-off-to-a-solid-start/|first=Michael David|last=Smith|title=AAF off to a solid start|work=Profootballtalk.com|date=February 10, 2019|accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref> [[SB Nation]] had a similar assessment, criticizing the game play as \"much worse than... most of major [[college football]],\" while at the same time noting that the league's innovations were largely successful in making games more interesting.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sbnation.com/2019/2/11/18220196/aaf-rules-games-2019|title=5 things the NFL and college football could learn from the first weekend of the AAF|first=Alex|last=Kirshner|work=SB Nation|date=February 11, 2019|accessdate=February 11, 2019}}</ref> In an admittedly incomplete review, [[Peter King (sportswriter)|Peter King]] stated that although he would not yet draw any \"major conclusions\" about the league, he liked some of the rule changes but feared the overtime process would be a [[gimmick]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2019/02/10/julian-edelman-patriots-mvp-nfl-fmia-peter-king/?cid=pfttease/|title=From his Hollywood Haven, Julian Edelman reflects on LIII MVP, his path and being a perfect Patriot \u00a7 10 Things I Think I Think|work=Football Morning in America|publisher=[[NBC Sports]]|date=February 11, 2019|accessdate=February 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Viewership===\nOvernight [[Nielsen Ratings]] stated that the league-opening regionally televised games on CBS were the highest rated telecast of the night in the [[key demographic]], drawing more viewers than an [[NBA on ABC|NBA game on ABC]] in the same time slot. In overall viewers, both the AAF and NBA lost to a rerun of ''[[America's Got Talent: The Champions]]'' on NBC.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/daily-ratings/tv-ratings-saturday-february-10-2019/|title=TV Ratings Saturday: AAF Football invades the chart, NBA falters|work=TV by the Numbers|date=February 10, 2019|accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref> The NFL Network telecast that week secured 640,000 viewers.<ref name=\"ap20190213\"/> With these comparatively strong initial viewership statistics, the Week 2 ratings were highly anticipated in the interest of developing trended data. In Week 2, the afternoon and evening games on Saturday, February 16, reportedly attracted 1,018,000 and 425,000 viewers, respectively, in addition to the Sunday evening game on February 17 drawing 424,000 viewers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/skedball-weekly-sports-tv-ratings-2-11-2-17-2019.html|title=SKEDBALL: Weekly Sports TV Ratings 2.11-2.17.2019 - Showbuzz Daily|website=www.showbuzzdaily.com}}</ref>  Week 3's NFL Network games drew 491,000 and 515,000 viewers, benefiting in part due to a [[Counterprogramming (television)|counterprogramming]] effort against the [[91st Academy Awards]].<ref>https://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2019/02/27/aaf-ratings-climb-for-week-three-on-nfln/</ref> Week 4's ratings were largely consistent with those of week 2, with the two NFL Network games that week securing ratings of 404,000 and 450,000 viewers, comparable to college basketball and NHL telecasts on the other sports networks.<ref name=awfulannouncing3519/> The disparity between the afternoon and evening games is consistent due to increased competition during primetime hours and the higher market penetration of CBS and TNT compared to NFL Network and CBS Sports Network, the latter of which does not register a rating in the Nielsens.\n\nIn March 2019, building upon these ratings successes, both CBS and TNT added games to their packages; TNT added two additional Saturday afternoon games previously scheduled for B/R Live (which would air special Skycam-only broadcasts of the games as a companion instead), while CBS announced that it would shift two games from CBS Sports Network to broadcast television, including a regular season game on April 6, 2019 (which would have led towards CBS's broadcast of the [[2019 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|2019 NCAA Final Four]]), and one of the conference championship games.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://awfulannouncing.com/cbs/cbs-is-adding-two-more-aaf-games-to-its-broadcast-network-from-cbs-sports-network.html|title=CBS is adding two more AAF games to its broadcast network|date=2019-03-14|website=Awful Announcing|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-14}}</ref><ref name=awfulannouncing3519>{{Cite web|url=https://awfulannouncing.com/turner/tnt-adds-more-aaf-broadcasts-br-live-skycam.html|title=TNT adds March 9 and March 23 AAF games after AAF ratings beat some NHL and MLS broadcasts|date=2019-03-05|website=Awful Announcing|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-06}}</ref> However, due to the suspension of football operations, these games were left unplayed.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite news |url=http://www.sportingnews.com/us/nfl/news/why-is-the-aaf-folding-who-to-blame-alliance-of-american-football/17fmqg4k8rkqp1v6563c4t8kbr |title=Why is the AAF folding? Who to blame for Alliance of American Football's collapse |first=Tadd |last=Haislop |website=[[Sporting News]] |date=April 3, 2019 |accessdate=April 3, 2019}}\n* {{cite news |url=https://www.cbssports.com/aaf/news/aaf-2019-what-went-wrong-and-what-happens-next-following-leagues-sudden-shutdown/ |title=AAF 2019: What went wrong and what happens next following league's sudden shutdown |first=Ben |last=Kercheval |website=[[CBS Sports]] |date=April 3, 2019 |accessdate=April 3, 2019}}\n* {{cite news |url=https://www.si.com/nfl/2019/04/02/alliance-american-football-league-suspension-legal-implications-fallout |title=Chaos and Fallout: The Legal Impact of the AAF's Potential Collapse |first=Michael |last=McCann |website=[[Sports Illustrated]] |date=April 2, 2019 |accessdate=April 4, 2019}}\n* {{cite news |url=https://deadspin.com/the-aafs-sudden-collapse-left-players-high-and-dry-with-1833813021 |title=The AAF's Sudden Collapse Left Players High And Dry With Bills For Housing And Injuries |first=Patrick |last=Redford |website=[[Deadspin]] |date=April 4, 2019 |accessdate=April 4, 2019}}\n* {{cite news |url=https://www.recode.net/2019/4/2/18292598/alliance-for-american-football-silicon-valley-failure |title=It turns out Silicon Valley cannot disrupt the National Football League |first=Theodore |last=Schleifer |website=[[Recode]] |date=April 2, 2019 |accessdate=April 4, 2019}}\n* {{cite news |url=https://www.theringer.com/nfl/2019/4/4/18294528/american-alliance-football-aaf-collapse-suspend-xfl |title=The AAF Failed Because All Minor League Football Does |first=Rodger |last=Sherman |website=[[The Ringer (website)|The Ringer]] |date=April 4, 2019 |accessdate=April 4, 2019}}\n* {{cite news |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/26957796/inside-short-unhappy-life-alliance-american-football |title=Inside the short, unhappy life of the Alliance of American Football |first=Seth Wickersham |last=Michael Rothstein |website=[[ESPN]] |date=June 13, 2019 |accessdate=June 13, 2019}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n\n{{AAF|state=expanded}}\n{{American football in the United States}}\n{{Professional gridiron football leagues in North America}}\n{{CBS Sports}}\n\n[[Category:Alliance of American Football| ]]\n[[Category:2018 establishments in the United States]]\n[[Category:Sports leagues established in 2018]]\n[[Category:American football leagues in the United States]]\n[[Category:Professional sports leagues in the United States]]\n[[Category:Minor and developmental leagues in professional sports]]\n[[Category:Sports leagues disestablished in 2019]]\n[[Category:2019 disestablishments in the United States]]\n[[Category:Companies that have filed for Chapter 7 bankruptcy]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|former professional American football league}}\n{{Use American English|date=March 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox sports league\n| title           = Alliance of American Football\n| current_season  = \n| Formerly        = \n| last_season     = 2019 AAF season\n| logo            = Alliance of American Football logo.png\n| pixels          = 150\n| upcoming_season = \n| sport           = American football\n| founded         = {{start date|2018|3|20}}\n| headquarters    = [[San Francisco]], [[California]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://shop.aaf.com/media/|title=Media|publisher=}}</ref>\n| inaugural       = [[2019 AAF season|2019]]\n| folded          = April 17, 2019 (bankruptcy)<ref name=APchap7>{{cite |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/2019/04/17/aaf-alliance-american-football-files-bankruptcy/3500708002/ |title=AAF files for bankruptcy, officially closes down |agency=[[Associated Press|AP]] |website=[[USA Today]] |date=April 17, 2019 |accessdate=April 17, 2019}}</ref>\n| teams           = 8\n| country         = United States\n| website         = {{url|www.aaf.com}}\n| TV              = {{Plainlist|\n*[[CBS Sports]]\n*[[NFL Network]]\n*[[Turner Sports]]\n}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Alliance of American Football''' ('''AAF''') was a professional [[American football]] league that played a portion of one season in 2019.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Allen |first1=Kevin |title=AAF suspends football operations with two weeks left in regular season |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/2019/04/02/aaf-alliance-american-football-league-suspends-operations/3342451002/ |website=USA TODAY |publisher=Gannett Satellite Information Network, LLC. |accessdate=3 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=APchap7/><ref name=\"espnpostmortem\"/> The AAF consisted of eight centrally owned and operated teams in the southern and western United States, seven of which were located in metropolitan areas with at least one [[Major professional sports leagues in the United States and Canada|major professional sports franchise]].\n\nFounded by [[Charlie Ebersol]] and [[Bill Polian]] in 2018, the AAF began play on February 9, 2019, six days after the [[National Football League]]'s (NFL) [[Super Bowl LIII]] championship game. The league was scheduled to have a 10-week regular season and conclude with a championship game on April 27. After eight weeks of play, however, the league's football operations were suspended by controlling owner [[Thomas Dundon]] on April 2.<ref>{{cite news |author=Kercheval, Ben |title=AAF operations suspended, league's future in doubt after eight games of first season |url=https://www.cbssports.com/aaf/news/aaf-operations-reportedly-suspended-leagues-future-in-doubt-after-eight-games-of-first-season/ |website=cbssports.com |date=April 2, 2019 |accessdate=2019-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|agency=[[ESPN]]|url=http://www.espn.com/espn/story/_/id/26423928/source-aaf-immediately-suspend-operations|title=AAF to immediately suspend operations|publisher=[[ESPN]]|date=April 2, 2019|accessdate=April 2, 2019}}</ref> Two days later, the AAF allowed players to leave their contracts to sign with NFL teams.<ref name=\"Schwartz\">{{Cite web|url=https://ftw.usatoday.com/2019/04/aaf-keith-reaser-kansas-city-chiefs|title=AAF star Keith Reaser becomes first player to sign NFL deal after league shutdown|first=Nick|last=Schwartz|work=USA Today|date=April 4, 2019|accessdate=April 4, 2019}}</ref> The AAF filed for [[Chapter 7, Title 11, United States Code|Chapter 7]] bankruptcy on April 17, 2019, with the league's sole season left incomplete.<ref name=APchap7/><ref name=Chapter7/>\n\n==History==\nCharlie Ebersol, son of former NBC executive and XFL co-founder [[Dick Ebersol]], was inspired to create the AAF in late 2016 after producing the documentary ''This Was the XFL'' for [[ESPN Films]]' ''[[30 for 30]]'' series; upon researching and examining the history of the [[XFL (2001)|XFL]], he came to the conclusion that the concept was viable but that the finished product was both poorly executed and, from an on-field standpoint, bad football. He began developing the AAF in February 2017, about the same time that word had come out about XFL co-founder [[Vince McMahon]] possibly [[XFL (2020)|reviving the old XFL brand]] (which McMahon would indeed do in 2020).<ref name=ebersolprofile>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/aaf-2019-how-the-new-alliance-of-american-football-stands-out-in-an-ever-growing-pro-football-landscape/|title=AAF 2019: How the new Alliance of American Football stands out in a growing pro football landscape|first=Ben|last=Kercheval|work=CBS Sports|date=February 4, 2019|accessdate=February 4, 2019}}</ref> Exhibits in a lawsuit filed by Robert Vanech, who claimed to have co-founded the AAF, state that Ebersol had originally approached McMahon about relaunching the XFL but was unable to come to an agreement, as Ebersol wanted control of the XFL brand and was willing to pay $50 million for the trademark, which McMahon was unwilling to sell.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/sports/football/2019/02/25/aaf-robert-vanech-alliance-american-football-charlie-ebersol-lawsuit/2983124002/?cid=twitter_azcsports|title=More trouble for the AAF? Man reportedly suing league for 50 percent ownership stake|work=AZcentral.com|date=February 25, 2019|accessdate=February 25, 2019}}</ref> In December 2018, [[Charlie Ebersol]] asked Vince McMahon about merging the AAF (which was two months away from starting) with the XFL. McMahon turned him down.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/Journal/Issues/2019/04/08/Leagues-and-Governing-Bodies/AAF.aspx |title=XFL rejected merger with AAF, takes lessons from failed league |last=Kaplan |first=Daniel |date=April 8, 2019 |website=www.sportsbusinessdaily.com |publisher=Sports Business Journal |access-date=February 12, 2020 |quote=In mid-December 2018, Charlie Ebersol and his nascent Alliance of American Football was two months away from the kickoff of its inaugural season \u2014 and it was already running out of money. Ebersol had secured limited funding from venture capital firms when he unveiled the league nine months earlier, but the AAF was on life support. So Ebersol approached WWE chairman and XFL kingpin Vince McMahon about a merger, a key source said. McMahon, who is relaunching the XFL next year, turned him down, the source said. The XFL declined to comment.}}</ref>\n\nThe AAF was announced on March 20, 2018. Ebersol sought to focus on creating a solid football product in the hopes that it would attract fans. He hired a team of experienced football players, coaches and executives to prepare the league for launch.<ref name=ebersolprofile/> The AAF was overseen by former [[National Football League|NFL]] general manager [[Bill Polian]], former [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] safety [[Troy Polamalu]], and executive [[John McKay Jr.|J. K. McKay]]. Advisers also include former Steelers receiver [[Hines Ward]], former [[New York Giants]] and [[Oakland Raiders]] defensive end [[Justin Tuck]], retired referee and current [[Fox NFL]] [[rules analyst]] [[Mike Pereira]], and Ebersol's father, Dick Ebersol.<ref name=\"espn\">{{cite news|last1=Rovell|first1=Darren|title=Former NFLers involved in league to rival XFL|url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/22844453/xfl-documentary-maker-plans-own-football-league|accessdate=March 20, 2018|work=ESPN.com|date=March 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\nEbersol attended the first XFL game in Las Vegas in 2001, and remembered how disappointed his father was by the poor quality of play.<ref name=\"ap20190213\">{{Cite news |url=https://triblive.com/pghtrib/localsports/14610673-94/aafs-officials-pleased-with-opening-weekend-tv-ratings-but-remain-cautious |title=AAF's officials pleased with opening weekend TV ratings but remain cautious |date=2019-02-13 |work=Pittsburgh Tribune-Review |access-date=2019-02-14 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> To ensure professional-level football at launch, the AAF set out to hire coaches with professional football coaching and championship experience.<ref>{{cite web |title=Steve Spurrier to coach Orlando team in new spring league, Alliance of American Football |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/nfl-competitor-alliance-of-american-football-new-football-league-first-team-orlando-steve-spurrier-today/ |website=CBS News |accessdate=October 3, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> On April 7, 2018, the first team, Orlando, was announced with its coach [[Steve Spurrier]].<ref name=cbs>{{cite news|last1=Steimle|first1=Kevin|last2=Breech|first2=John|title=Steve Spurrier announced as first coach and Orlando first host city for Alliance of American Football|url=https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/steve-spurrier-announced-as-first-coach-and-orlando-first-host-city-for-alliance-of-american-football/|accessdate=April 7, 2018|work=CBSSports.com|date=April 7, 2018|language=en}}</ref> By June 2018, the league had announced its eight inaugural teams and their cities.<ref name=\"espn\" />\n\nOn July 30, 2018, the Alliance announced the league had signed 100 players.<ref name=\"mca\">{{cite news |last1=Munz |first1=Jason |title=Alliance of American Football announces Memphis team has signed 28 players |url= https://www.commercialappeal.com/story/sports/2018/08/01/alliance-american-football-memphis-signs-sec-standouts-ut-vols/882425002/ |accessdate=September 14, 2018 |work=The Memphis Commercial Appeal |date=August 1, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> In August 2018, the league held the Alliance Scouting Combine at three locations and four dates: August 4, 2018, in Los Angeles, California; August 18 in Houston, Texas; and August 25\u201326 in Atlanta, Georgia.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ward |first1=Brendan |title=Alliance of American Football hosting scouting combine for players |url=http://www.wmcactionnews5.com/story/38558071/alliance-of-american-football-hosting-scouting-combine-for-players/ |accessdate=September 14, 2018 |work=WMC Action News 5.com |date=July 2, 2018}}</ref> By August 24, 2018, 205 players were signed.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Froyd |first1=Crissy |title=Zach Mettenberger and Antonio Andrews reunite in new pro league |url=https://titanswire.usatoday.com/2018/08/27/zach-mettenberger-antonio-andrews-american-alliance-of-football/ |accessdate=September 14, 2018 |work=Titans Wire |date=August 27, 2018}}</ref> These dates provided an opportunity for players cut at the NFL roster deadline, and each player signed a non-guaranteed three-year contract worth a total of $250,000 ($70,000 in 2019; $80,000 in 2020; $100,000 in 2021),<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espn.com/espn/story/_/id/26423928/source-aaf-immediately-suspend-operations |title=Source: AAF to immediately suspend operations |first=Michael |last=Rothstein |website=[[ESPN]] |date=April 2, 2019 |accessdate=April 2, 2019}}</ref> with performance-based and fan-interaction incentives allowing for players to earn more.<ref name=\"AP news\">{{cite web |last1=Wilner |first1=Barry |title=Alliance signs players cut by NFL teams for spring league |url=https://apnews.com/3accb15c06bd4747acf8d57ffbb5fb42 |website=AP News |accessdate=October 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2018, [[Starter (clothing line)|Starter]], through G-III Sports, which manufactured NFL jerseys and apparel in the 1980s and 1990s, was named the official on-field apparel and game-day uniform supplier for the AAF, marking a return for the brand to professional football after an almost 20 year absence.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Benjamin |first1=Cody |title=Alliance of American Football strikes multi-year uniform, apparel deal with Starter |url=https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/alliance-of-american-football-strikes-multi-year-uniform-apparel-deal-with-starter/ |website=CBSSports.com |date= July 24, 2018  |accessdate=October 2, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> On September 20, the league announced four eastern inaugural franchises' names and logos.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Benjamin |first1=Cody |title=LOOK: Alliance of American Football unveils logos of four pro teams that will debut in 2019 |url=https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/look-alliance-of-american-football-unveils-logos-of-four-pro-teams-that-will-debut-in-2019/ |accessdate=September 21, 2018 |work=CBSSports.com |date=September 20, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> The four western teams' logos and names were revealed five days later.<ref name=\"cbs0\">{{cite news |last1=Benjamin |first1=Cody |title=LOOK: Here's a full list of team names and logos from the Alliance of American Football |url=https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/look-heres-a-full-list-of-team-names-and-logos-from-the-alliance-of-american-football/ |accessdate=October 3, 2018 |work=CBSSports.com |date=September 25, 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Inaugural season===\n{{Main|2019 AAF season}}\nOn October 16, 2018, the Alliance announced its schedule (indicating the day and location, but not the time, of each game) which had two games each on Saturday and on Sunday most weekends.<ref name=azc>{{cite news |title=Alliance of American Football schedule released for Arizona Hotshots, other 7 teams |url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/sports/football/2018/10/16/alliance-american-football-arizona-hotshots-2019-schedule/1658993002/ |accessdate=November 8, 2018 |work=AZ Central |publisher=USA Today |date=October 16, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> Quarterback skills training camps were held at the [[Alamodome]] in [[San Antonio]] on November 12 through 14. On November 27, the league held a four-round [[2019 AAF QB Draft|\"Protect or Pick\" quarterback draft]] in the Esports Arena at [[Luxor Las Vegas]] and broadcast on [[CBS Sports Network]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Scott |first1=Dana |title=Alliance of American Football league to hold 'Protect or Pick' quarterback draft |url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/sports/football/2018/10/31/aaf-hold-new-protect-pick-quarterback-draft/1835643002/ |accessdate=November 5, 2018 |work=AZ Central |publisher=USA Today Network |date=October 31, 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe AAF began [[2019 AAF season|its inaugural, 10-week season]] on February 9, 2019.<ref name=\"espn\" /> The first points in AAF regular season history were scored by kicker [[Younghoe Koo]] of the [[Atlanta Legends]], who made a 38-yard field goal against the [[Orlando Apollos]]. The first touchdown came in the same game with Orlando quarterback [[Garrett Gilbert]] connecting with [[Jalin Marshall]] for a 16-yard score.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbssports.com/aaf/news/aaf-week-1-scores-highlights-spurrier-calls-philly-special-for-td-orlando-and-san-antonio-win-openers/ |title=AAF Week 1 scores, highlights: Spurrier calls 'Philly Special' for TD, Orlando and San Antonio win openers |first=Ben |last=Kercheval |website=[[CBS Sports]] |date=February 9, 2019 |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref> The first shutout was recorded by the [[Birmingham Iron]] when they defeated the [[Memphis Express]], 26\u20130, in Week 1.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbs42.com/news/local/iron-shutout-express-in-aaf-season-opener/1771548771 |title=Iron shutout Express in AAF season opener |first=Simone |last=Eli |website=cbs42.com |date=February 10, 2019 |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref> The first onside conversion (see Rules section, below) was attempted during Week 3, with Atlanta successfully completing a 48-yard pass against Birmingham.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://brobible.com/sports/article/aaf-onside-conversion-rule-fans-love/ |title=The AAF\u2019s Alternative Rule To The Onside Kick Was Used For The First Time Sunday And Fans Are In Love |first=Matt |last=Keohan |website=brobible.com |date=February 25, 2019 |accessdate=February 28, 2019}}</ref> The first [[Safety (gridiron football score)|safety]] was registered by Atlanta against the [[Arizona Hotshots]] in Week 4.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://aaf.com/murray-leads-legends-to-win-over-hotshots |title=Murray leads Legends to win over Hotshots |first=Jaylon |last=Thompson |website=AAF.com |date=March 4, 2019 |accessdate=March 4, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190306043950/https://aaf.com/murray-leads-legends-to-win-over-hotshots |archive-date=March 6, 2019 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The first [[Overtime (sports)|overtime]] game occurred in Week 7, with Memphis defeating Birmingham.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://aaf.com/news/iron-fall-to-express-overtime |title=Iron fall to Express in first overtime game in Alliance history |first=Marq |last=Burnett |website=AAF.com |date=March 25, 2019 |accessdate=March 25, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190325045557/https://aaf.com/news/iron-fall-to-express-overtime |archive-date=March 25, 2019 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nA four-team playoff was to be capped with the league's championship game, initially scheduled to be held at [[Sam Boyd Stadium]] near [[Las Vegas]]. After Dundon took over league operations, he moved the game to the [[Ford Center at the Star]] in [[Frisco, Texas]].<ref>{{cite web|agency=[[Associated Press|AP]]|url=http://www.espn.com/espn/story/_/id/26316149/aaf-shifts-title-game-vegas-frisco-texas|title=AAF shifts title game from Vegas to Frisco, Texas|website=[[ESPN]]|date=March 20, 2019|accessdate=March 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Cessation of operations====\nOn April 2, 2019, the AAF suspended all football operations, on orders from AAF chairman [[Thomas Dundon|Tom Dundon]].<ref name=disappointed/> League co-founder [[Bill Polian]] stated:\n\n{{Quote|I am extremely disappointed to learn Tom Dundon has decided to suspend all football operations of the Alliance of American Football. When Mr. Dundon took over, it was the belief of my co-founder, Charlie Ebersol, and myself that we would finish the season, pay our creditors, and make the necessary adjustments to move forward in a manner that made economic sense for all. The momentum generated by our players, coaches and football staff had us well positioned for future success. Regrettably, we will not have that opportunity.<ref name=disappointed>{{cite news |url=http://www.espn.com/espn/story/_/id/26423928/aaf-suspends-operations-polian-disappointed |title=AAF suspends operations; Polian 'disappointed' |first=Michael |last=Rothstein |website=[[ESPN]] |date=April 3, 2019}}</ref>}}\n\nPlayers found out about the suspension through the Internet before their coaches confirmed the news.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/the-inside-story-of-the-aa-fs-final-day-through-the-eyes-of-its-players-041510929.html|title=The inside story of the AAF's final day, through the eyes of its players|first=Terez|last=Paylor|work=Yahoo! Sports|date=April 3, 2019|accessdate=April 3, 2019}}</ref> Players were evicted from the hotels where their teams were being housed\u2014with some being personally charged for unpaid hotel bills<ref name=OCRyan/>\u2014and required to pay their own way home; they also lost their health insurance and were forced to cover their own medical bills from injuries sustained during play.<ref name=\"medical\">{{cite web|url=https://www.foxbusiness.com/features/aaf-players-booted-from-hotels-left-to-pay-medical-costs-out-of-pocket-report|title=AAF players booted from hotels, left to pay medical costs out of pocket: Report|first=Thomas|last=Barrabi|work=[[Fox Business Network]]|date=April 4, 2019|accessdate=April 4, 2019}}</ref> League employees were notified via an April 2 letter from the AAF board, which did not give a reason for ending the season,<ref name=disappointed/> that their jobs were terminated as of April 3 with no [[Severance package|severance]].<ref name=OCRyan>{{cite news |url=https://www.ocregister.com/2019/04/05/aaf-goes-under-inside-the-sudden-collapse-of-the-alliance-of-american-football/ |title=AAF goes under: Inside the sudden collapse of the Alliance of American Football |first=Ryan |last=Kartje |website=[[Orange County Register]] |date=April 5, 2019 |accessdate=April 5, 2019}}</ref> Ebersol and Dundon refused public comment;<ref name=OCRyan/> Ebersol would eventually speak out on April 17, stating that he had been advised not to speak by his attorneys. He insisted that the money he raised was there and had been vetted up until immediately before the season, claimed that reports of players being saddled with hotel and medical bills were either [[fake news]] or fraudulent charges, and could not ensure that all those owed money would be paid.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/SB-Blogs/Newsletter-Media/2019/04/17.aspx|title=SBJ Media: Charlie Ebersol Speaks|first=John|last=Ourand|work=Sports Business Journal|date=April 17, 2019|accessdate=April 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn April 4, the AAF announced through their official [[Twitter]] account that players were eligible to leave their contracts to sign with NFL teams.<ref name=\"Schwartz\"/> The contracts that players had originally signed included a stipulation that they could leave to sign with NFL teams at the conclusion of an AAF season.<ref>{{cite news |author=Florio, Mike |title=AAF players finally receive authorization to sign with NFL teams |url=https://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2019/04/04/aaf-players-finally-receive-authorization-to-sign-with-nfl-teams/ |website=profootballtalk.com |date=April 4, 2019 |accessdate=2019-04-04}}</ref> The league did not issue any public statement until April 6, when the AAF.com website was updated with a statement, which read in part:\n\n{{Quote|This week, we made the difficult decision to suspend all football operations for the Alliance of American Football. We understand the difficulty that this decision has caused for many people and for that we are very sorry. This is not the way we wanted it to end, but we are also committed to working on solutions for all outstanding issues to the best of our ability. Due to ongoing legal processes, we are unable to comment further or share details about the decision.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://aaf.com |title=Alliance of American Football (homepage) |accessdate=April 6, 2019}}</ref>}}\n\nAt the time its football operations were suspended, the AAF had played eight weeks out of a scheduled ten-week regular season.\n\n====Bankruptcy liquidation====\nOn April 17, the league filed for [[Chapter 7, Title 11, United States Code|Chapter 7]] bankruptcy ([[liquidation]]) in [[United States District Court for the Eastern District of Texas|Texas\u2019 Eastern District]].<ref name=Chapter7>{{Cite web|url=https://deadspin.com/aaf-officially-pulls-the-plug-files-for-bankruptcy-1834121723|title=AAF Officially Pulls The Plug, Files For Bankruptcy|last=Redford|first=Patrick|website=Deadspin|language=en-US|date=2019-04-17|access-date=2019-04-17}}</ref> In the filing, the league claimed assets of $11.3 million, liabilities of $48.3 million, and approximately $536,000 in cash.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=frntofficesport |number=1118584049491152897 |title=BREAKING: @TheAAF has filed for Chapter 7 Bankruptcy. |date=April 17, 2019 |accessdate=April 17, 2019}}</ref> The AAF counted its player contracts among its assets in the bankruptcy filing, blocking players from joining the [[Canadian Football League]].<ref>{{cite news |author=Florio, Mike |title=AAF refuses to release players for possible CFL employment |url=https://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2019/04/12/aaf-refuses-to-release-players-for-possible-cfl-employment/ |website=NBCSports.com |date=April 12, 2019 |accessdate=October 4, 2019}}</ref> This block was lifted a day after the bankruptcy filing.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=BenKercheval |number=1118712875328135168 |date=April 18, 2019 |title=Yes, to correct a previous tweet, I am told by a source that #AAF players can sign with CFL teams. My apologies on not being up to date on that. That\u2019s the updated situation.}}</ref>\n\nThe league's uniforms and equipment were stored in a lot in [[San Antonio, Texas]] and eventually auctioned off in July 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.expressnews.com/business/local/article/XFL-wants-to-score-bankrupt-football-league-s-13884443.php|title=XFL wants to score bankrupt football league\u2019s assets stored in San Antonio warehouse|first=Patrick|last=Danner|work=San Antonio Express-News|date=May 23, 2019|accessdate=May 24, 2019}}</ref> Former [[Arena Football League]] commissioner [[Jerry Kurz]] made the winning bid at $455,000, beating out bids from (among others) the [[XFL (2020)|revived XFL]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2019/07/08/former-arena-league-commissioner-buys-aaf-equipment-at-auction/ |title=Former Arena League commissioner buys AAF equipment at auction |website=[[NBC Sports]] |date=July 8, 2019}}</ref> The perpetually postponed [[Major League Football]] claimed it had agreed to purchase the equipment.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.otcmarkets.com/filing/conv_pdf?id=13557319&guid=mR2IUqr3iO8vn3h |title=MAJOR LEAGUE FOOTBALL INC FORM 10-K: Filed 07/29/19 for the Period Ending 04/30/19 |website=OTCMarkets.com |date=July 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Teams==\n{| class=\"plainrowheaders wikitable\"\n!Team<ref name=\"cbs0\" />\n!City\n!Stadium\n!Capacity\n!Head coach<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wilson |first1=Ryan |title=Alliance of American Football QB Draft: Aaron Murray, Christian Hackenberg highlight QBs taken in AAF event |url=https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/alliance-of-american-football-qb-draft-aaron-murray-christian-hackenberg-highlight-qbs-taken-in-aaf-event/ |accessdate=November 29, 2018 |work=CBSSports.com |date=November 28, 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n|-\n!style=background:#CE1126 colspan=\"7\"| {{color|#FFFFFF|Eastern Conference}}\n|-\n|'''[[Atlanta Legends]]'''\n| [[Atlanta|Atlanta, Georgia]] \n| [[Georgia State Stadium]] \n| align=center|24,333\n| [[Kevin Coyle]]\n|-\n| '''[[Birmingham Iron]]'''\n| [[Birmingham, Alabama]]\n| [[Legion Field]]\n| align=center|71,594\n| [[Tim Lewis]]\n|-\n| '''[[Memphis Express]]'''\n| [[Memphis, Tennessee]]\n| [[Liberty Bowl Memorial Stadium]]\n| align=center|58,325\n| [[Mike Singletary]]\n|-\n| '''[[Orlando Apollos]]'''\n| [[Orlando, Florida]]\n| [[Spectrum Stadium]]\n| align=center|44,206\n| [[Steve Spurrier]]\n|-\n!style=background:#153769 colspan=\"7\"| {{color|#FFFFFF|Western Conference}}\n|-\n| '''[[Arizona Hotshots]]'''\n| [[Tempe, Arizona]]\n| [[Sun Devil Stadium]]\n| align=center|57,078\n| [[Rick Neuheisel]]\n|-\n| '''[[Salt Lake Stallions]]'''\n| [[Salt Lake City|Salt Lake City, Utah]]\n| [[Rice\u2013Eccles Stadium]]\n| align=center|45,807\n| [[Dennis Erickson]]\n|-\n|'''[[San Antonio Commanders]]'''\n| [[San Antonio|San Antonio, Texas]] \n| [[Alamodome]] \n| align=center|64,000\n| [[Mike Riley]]\n|-\n| '''[[San Diego Fleet]]'''\n| [[San Diego|San Diego, California ]]\n| [[SDCCU Stadium]]\n| align=center|70,561\n| [[Mike Martz]]\n|}\n\n{{Location map+ |United States |width=600 |float=center |caption=Locations of teams for the 2019 AAF season.<br />[[File:Red pog.svg|8px]] Eastern Conference [[File:Blue pog.svg|8px]] Western Conference|places=\n         {{Location map~ |United States |lat=33.426389 |long=-111.9325   |label=[[Arizona Hotshots|Hotshots]]           |position=bottom  |mark=blue pog.svg}}\n         {{Location map~ |United States |lat=33.735278 |long=-84.389444  |label=[[Atlanta Legends|Legends]]            |position=top     |mark=red pog.svg}}\n         {{Location map~ |United States |lat=33.511389 |long=-86.842778  |label=[[Birmingham Iron|Iron]]         |position=bottom  |mark=red pog.svg}}\n         {{Location map~ |United States |lat=35.121111 |long=-89.9775    |label=[[Memphis Express|Express]]            |position=top     |mark=Red pog.svg}}\n         {{Location map~ |United States |lat=28.6091   |long=-81.1924    |label=[[Orlando Apollos|Apollos]]            |position=bottom  |mark=Red pog.svg}}\n\t {{Location map~ |United States |lat=40.76     |long=-111.849    |label=[[Salt Lake Stallions|Stallions]] |position=bottom  |mark=blue pog.svg}}\n         {{Location map~ |United States |lat=29.4241   |long=-98.4936    |label=[[San Antonio Commanders|Commanders]] |position=top     |mark=blue pog.svg}}\n         {{Location map~ |United States |lat=32.783056 |long=-117.119444 |label=[[San Diego Fleet|Fleet]]          |position=top     |mark=blue pog.svg}}\n         }}\n\n==Rules==\nEbersol deliberately avoided making radical changes to the rules of the game so as to make it recognizable to the U.S. public. He stated that he used the average length of a feature film, slightly over two hours, as the basis for a typical fan's [[attention span]].<ref name=ebersolprofile/>\n\n* Teams had 52 players on each roster, with some selected by a territorial draft.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://aaf.com/all-eight-alliance-teams-determine-52-player-rosters|title=The Alliance of American Football sets final rosters|work=Alliance of American Football|date=January 29, 2019|accessdate=January 31, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190201013555/https://aaf.com/all-eight-alliance-teams-determine-52-player-rosters|archive-date=February 1, 2019|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The territory assigned to a team consisted of at least five colleges plus designated professional teams, one [[Canadian Football League]], and four NFL teams (players from colleges outside the AAF footprint being allocated based on their most recent professional team). Only one quarterback could be taken from their region.<ref name=\"espn0\">{{cite news |last1=Rovell |first1=Darren |title=AAF players to get 3-year, $250K contracts |url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/24076702/alliance-american-football-players-get-3-year-250k-contracts |accessdate=September 14, 2018 |work=ESPN.com |date=July 12, 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n** For the inaugural season, a quarterbacks-only \"[[2019 AAF QB Draft|Protect or Pick]]\" draft was conducted in November 2018 in which teams could retain their allocated quarterback or select an unprotected quarterback from another team.<ref>{{cite web|last=Florio|first=Mike|url=https://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2018/10/31/aaf-to-conduct-unusual-draft-process-for-allocating-quarterbacks/|title=AAF to conduct unusual draft process for allocating quarterbacks|publisher=[[Profootballtalk.com]]|date=October 31, 2018|accessdate=November 3, 2018}}</ref>\n* Telecasts featured no [[television timeout]]s and 60 percent fewer \"full-screen commercials,\" with the league aiming for an approximate real-time game length of 150 minutes, down from just over 180 in the NFL.<ref name=\"xfl_competitor\">{{cite news|last1=Gartland|first1=Dan|title=8-team XFL competitor plans to launch in February 2019|url=https://www.si.com/nfl/2018/03/20/alliance-american-football-xfl-competitor-league-launch|accessdate=March 21, 2018|work=SI.com|publisher=Time, Inc.|date=March 20, 2018}}</ref><ref name=wapo_aaf>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/redskins/alliance-of-american-football-to-kick-off-after-super-bowl/2018/03/20/f3ac7db8-2c4f-11e8-8dc9-3b51e028b845_story.html |title=Alliance of American Football to kick off after Super Bowl |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=March 20, 2018 |accessdate=March 20, 2018}}</ref> In turn, the AAF aimed to charge more money for the remaining commercial slots, also alluding to [[product placement]] opportunities that did not interrupt the game telecast.<ref name=ebersolprofile/>\n* There were no [[Conversion (gridiron football)|extra point kicks]]; teams had to attempt [[two-point conversion]]s after a touchdown.\n* Defenses were forbidden from advancing (\"rushing\") more than five players on or across the line of scrimmage, and no defensive player could [[blitz (gridiron football)|cross the line of scrimmage]] from more than two yards outside the [[offensive tackle]]s.<ref name=\"skyjudge\"/> The \"illegal defense\" penalty for violating these rules was a 15-yard penalty.\n* There were no [[Kickoff (gridiron football)|kickoffs]]; possession at the start of each half, and after touchdowns and field goals, began on a team's own 25-yard line, in line with the NFL [[touchback]]s. After a [[safety (gridiron football score)|safety]], the scoring team received possession at their own 35-yard line.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://apnews.com/b298f69df360428091c24079bb814f32 |title=AAF kicks off without kickoffs, but with SkyJudge |agency=[[Associated Press|AP]] |date=February 5, 2019 |accessdate=February 28, 2019}}</ref>\n** In lieu of an [[onside kick]], a team could keep possession of the ball by attempting an \"onside conversion\", a scrimmage play from their own 28-yard line and gaining at least 12 yards (essentially, a fourth-and-12 play).<ref>{{cite web|last=Goldberg|first=Jeff|url=https://aaf.com/safe-to-say-on-side-conversion-play-will-generate-excitement|title=Safe to say, on-side conversion play will generate excitement|work=Alliance of American Football|date=January 28, 2019|accessdate=January 28, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190129064125/https://aaf.com/safe-to-say-on-side-conversion-play-will-generate-excitement|archive-date=January 29, 2019|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> A team was not allowed to attempt such a play after a field goal or touchdown unless it was trailing by 17 or more points, or during the final two minutes of the first half, or during the final five minutes of the second half.<ref>AAF broadcast on CBS Sports Network, 3 March 2019</ref><ref name=\"newrules\">{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/2019/02/06/alliance-american-football-new-league-offers-timely-change-game/2797835002/|title=Alliance of American Football's SkyJudge might have prevented NFC Championship no-call|work=Associated Press|date=February 8, 2019|accessdate=February 8, 2019}}</ref> The onside conversion play was also available after any [[Safety (gridiron football score)|safety]],{{citation needed|date=March 2019}} played from the 18-yard line.<ref name=\"skyjudge\"/>\n* The [[play clock]] ran only 35 seconds, five seconds shorter than in the NFL, but still longer than the CFL's 20 seconds, timed from the spotting of the football. (The league originally proposed a 30-second play clock,<ref name=wapo_aaf/> but Ebersol concluded it would negatively impact the quality of play.)<ref name=ebersolprofile/>\n* Players could not throw the football into the stands or hand it off to a spectator following a touchdown.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=MikePereira |number=1095088703234486272 |title=He will not get a fine and won\u2019t be penalized if he does it again. It is only a foul if a player deliberately throws it and hands it into stands. If a spiked ball bounces into the stands, no foul. It should not have been called. |date=February 11, 2019 |accessdate=March 27, 2019}}</ref> While other leagues (particularly the NCAA) have similar rules in place using rationale based on sportsmanship, the primary motivation for the AAF rule appears to be economic as its footballs (manufactured by [[Wilson Sporting Goods]] and marked with distinctive red, blue, and white stripes) contain expensive tracking technology. The penalty for such behavior was [[unsportsmanlike conduct]], a 15-yard penalty, and if it is determined to be deliberate, a fine can be assessed to the offending player.<ref name=nosouvenirs>{{cite web|url=http://www.footballzebras.com/2019/02/how-the-aafs-strict-no-souvenirs-rule-claimed-its-first-victim/|title=How the AAF\u2019s strict \"no souvenirs\" rule claimed its first victim|work=Football Zebras|date=February 11, 2019|accessdate=February 13, 2019}}</ref> Other [[touchdown celebration]]s are generally tolerated.\n** [[Trent Richardson]] of the [[Birmingham Iron]] was penalized during the first week of AAF play, when a ball he [[Spike (gridiron football)|spike]]d after scoring a touchdown bounced into the stands. AAF officials later determined that Richardson's actions were accidental and did not assess the fine, also apologizing for the penalty.<ref name=nosouvenirs/>\n* There were no automatic [[Replay review in gridiron football|instant replay reviews]] of scoring plays or turnovers as there are in the NFL. Each team was given two coach's challenges, which they could use at any time outside the [[two-minute warning]], and received a third if both challenges were successful. After the two-minute warning in each half and during overtime, the replay booth had sole authority to call for a replay review.<ref name=wapo_aaf/>\n* Outside organizations handled head-safety protocols.<ref name=\"vty\" />\n* In the event of a tie at the end of regulation, a single [[overtime (sports)|overtime]] period would be played, under the [[high school football]] rules of the \"[[Kansas Playoff]].\" Each team would begin on their opponent's 10-yard line and be given one possession (four downs) to score, with no [[field goal]]s allowed. Had a score remained tied after each team was given their possession, the game would end in a tie. Both teams would be given one timeout per overtime possession. The coin toss winner could choose to possess first or defer.<ref name=ebersolprofile/> Had the AAF reached the postseason, accounts differed on what system would be used; early reports had repeated rounds of the Kansas Playoff played until a winner was determined,<ref name=ebersolprofile/> but later reports stated that the AAF would use [[Sudden death (sport)|sudden death]] ([[golden point]]), which had been abolished at all other levels of football by the time of the AAF's debut.<ref name=BRplayoffs>{{cite web |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2823602-how-the-aaf-playoffs-and-schedule-work |title=How the AAF Playoffs and Schedule Work |website=[[Bleacher Report]] |date=March 6, 2019 |accessdate=March 17, 2019}}</ref>\n* Playoffs would have consisted of four teams, the top two teams from each conference.<ref name=azc/>\n* Officiating crews had [[Official (American football)#Eight-official system|eight members on the field]], similar to NCAA Division I football, instead of the [[Official (American football)#Standard seven-official system|standard seven-official system]] used in the NFL and CFL (the eighth officiating member was the center judge). AAF officiating also had a ninth member, called a sky judge, an off-the-field official who reviews every play using technology like a booth review. The sky judge could call or take away [[penalty (gridiron football)|penalties]] missed or made by the field officials.<ref name=\"skyjudge\">{{cite news|last=Munz|first=Jason|url=https://www.commercialappeal.com/story/sports/2019/02/07/aaf-introduce-sky-judge-rule-changes-alliance-football-charlie-ebersol-hines-ward-bill-polian/2783393002/|title=Sky judge and the world of tomorrow: A look at the AAF's notable rule differences|newspaper=[[The Commercial Appeal]]|date=February 7, 2019|accessdate=February 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Business==\nThe Alliance operated as a single entity, with all teams owned and operated by the league, under the name Legendary Field Exhibitions LLC.<ref name=wapo_aaf/> Some of the investors in the AAF included [[Peter Thiel]]'s [[Founders Fund]], [[The Chernin Group]] (which owns [[Barstool Sports]]), [[Jared Allen]], Slow Ventures, [[Adrian Fenty]], Charles King's M Ventures, and [[Keith Rabois]].<ref name=\"vty\"/><ref name=xfl_competitor/> Long-term plans were for the AAF to sell franchises to individual owners.<ref name=leagueonfire/>\n\n[[MGM Resorts International]] made an investment in the AAF tech platform,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Crupi |first1=Anthony |title=The Alliance of American Football bets on success where others have failed |url=https://adage.com/article/media/alliance-american-football-gambles-success/314871/ |accessdate=October 3, 2018 |work=Ad Age |date=September 10, 2018 |language=en|quote=Per terms of the deal, MGM also will invest in the AAF tech platform, ...}}</ref> and entered a three-year sponsorship agreement to become the league's official sports betting sponsor and exclusive gaming partner. The deal marked the first time any sports organization had sold exclusive in-game betting rights to a sportsbook.<ref name=\"USA today\">{{cite web |last1=Gleeson |first1=Scott |title=Alliance of American Football league, spring alternative to NFL, reveals gambling-focused strategy |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/2018/09/11/alliance-american-football-league-reveals-gambling-focused-strategy/1265465002/ |website=USA TODAY |date=September 11, 2018 |accessdate=October 2, 2018 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Rovell |first1=Darren |title=AAF league to have enhanced in-game betting |url=http://www.espn.com/chalk/story/_/id/24632798/alliance-american-football-enhanced-live-game-betting |website=ESPN.com |date=September 10, 2018 |accessdate=October 2, 2018 |language=en }}</ref> [[Scott Butera]], MGM's director of interactive gaming (the division that signed an agreement with the AAF), was formerly the commissioner of the [[Arena Football League]] before his 2018 ouster.<ref name=whyaafinvestor/> Under the terms of the agreement, MGM Resorts International owned all rights to the tech platform in the event the league ceases operations, preventing an investor from buying the league solely for access to the technology.<ref name=dundondoesntown>{{cite web|url=https://www.actionnetwork.com/nfl/aaf-folds-tom-dundon-technology|first=Darren|last=Rovell|title=Sources: Tom Dundon Doesn\u2019t Own AAF\u2019s Gambling-Forward Tech Arm|work=The Action Network|date=April 6, 2019|accessdate=April 7, 2019}}</ref> Gambling functions were never implemented on the league's app,<ref name=dundondoesntown/> and many planned features for the app never materialized due to technical glitches and impracticality.<ref name=leagueonfire/>\n\nThe league also had player bonuses and scholarships, with player bonuses based on performance and fan interaction, players were to earn a year's scholarship in post-secondary education for each season of play.<ref name=\"wapo_aaf\" /> Players got three-year, non-guaranteed contracts worth $250,000 plus health insurance with an escape clause to go to the NFL.<ref name=\"espn0\"/> The three-year contract was believed to be purposely targeting the XFL to prevent second-tier professional players from signing with the XFL if they played in the AAF in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2018/09/01/xfl-sends-up-first-salvo-in-looming-aaf-feud/|title=XFL sends up first salvo in looming AAF feud|first=Mike|last=Florio|work=ProFootballTalk.com|date=September 1, 2018|accessdate=September 18, 2018}}</ref> XFL commissioner [[Oliver Luck]] stated that he did not believe that such a clause would hold up in court after the AAF collapsed, and that the XFL would be willing to sign AAF players.<ref>https://xflnewshub.com/xfl-news/luck-talks-aaf-folding/</ref> The league also has an incentive system that pays members of a team's offensive and defensive units for statistical achievements and also pays players to perform [[community service]]; the exact details of this incentive system were not yet finalized at the start of the 2019 season.<ref name=ebersolprofile/> Players are assigned to each team by way of a centralized process that is largely a [[trade secret]].<ref name=ebersolprofile/> The league showed willingness to offer more money to marquee players; [[Landry Jones]] noted that Ebersol had personally promised a salary of over $1,000,000 to Jones if he played for the San Antonio Commanders; when Jones pressed Ebersol on when he would be paid, Ebersol became evasive, leading Jones to reject the offer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/espn/story/_/id/28640013/landry-jones-face-xfl-does-want-be|title=Landry Jones is the face of the XFL. Does he want to be?|first=Brendan|last=Meyer|work=ESPN.com|date=February 6, 2020|access-date=February 6, 2020}}</ref> [[Matt McGloin]] likewise turned down the AAF, both because of his skepticism over the league and the birth of his child.<ref>{{cite news |author=Kaye, Mike |title=XFL 2020: How ex-Eagles QB Matt McGloin\u2019s son influenced his return to football with New York Guardians |url=https://www.nj.com/eagles/2020/02/xfl-2020-how-ex-eagles-qb-matt-mcgloins-son-influenced-his-return-to-football-with-new-york-guardians-qa-with-penn-state-alum.html |website=NJ.com |date=February 7, 2020 |accessdate=February 16, 2020}}</ref>\n For the fans, in addition to a [[Fantasy football (American)|fantasy league]] built into mobile broadcasts, there are low ticket prices (each team have a $35/game sideline seat option) and inexpensive food at games.<ref name=\"wapo_aaf\" />  When the league abruptly folded, the league left players to personally pay outstanding bills for their own hotels, as well as their transportation home and even their medical bills from injuries sustained during play.<ref name=\"medical\"/>\n\nThe AAF coaching salaries varied by title, with $500,000 for head coaches, $200\u2013250,000 for coordinators, and $75\u2013150,000 for position coaches. Each AAF team employed between 11 and 13 total coaches, putting the total coaching staff expenditures at around $2 million per staff and $16 million for the entire league.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://footballscoop.com/news/sources-aaf-coaching-salaries-better-might-think/|title=Sources: AAF coaching salaries are better than you might think|first=Zach|last=Barnett|date=February 13, 2019|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Dundon investment===\nOn February 18, 2019, the league announced that [[Tom Dundon]], whose other holdings include the [[Carolina Hurricanes]] of the [[National Hockey League]] (NHL) and [[TopGolf]], agreed to invest $250 million into the league.<ref name=tomdundon>{{cite news|url=http://africa.espn.com/nhl/story/_/id/26030221/hurricanes-owner-tom-dundon-invests-250m-aaf|title=Hurricanes owner Tom Dundon invests $250M in AAF|work=ESPN.com|date=February 19, 2019|accessdate=February 19, 2019}}</ref> He was also named the new chairman of the AAF,<ref name=dundonathletic /> and Dundon reportedly received a majority stake in the league in exchange for his investment.{{cn|date=October 2019}} Dundon's investment was initially reported to be due to the league being in danger of not making payroll.<ref name=dundonathletic>{{cite web|url=https://theathletic.com/825580/2019/02/18/nhl-owner-rescues-fledgling-aaf-with-much-needed-cash-infusion/|title=NHL owner rescues fledgling AAF with much-needed cash infusion|first=David|last=Glenn|work=[[The Athletic]]|url-access=limited|date=February 18, 2019|accessdate=February 19, 2019}}</ref> It was later reported that the payroll issue was due to a glitch in the league's changing of payroll companies, and that Dundon's investment had already been planned.<ref name=CBS19feb19>{{cite news |title=AAF gets $250 million investment from Hurricanes owner Tom Dundon, dismisses report of financial difficulty |url=https://www.cbssports.com/aaf/news/aaf-gets-250-million-investment-from-hurricanes-owner-tom-dundon-dismisses-report-of-financial-difficulty/ |accessdate=19 February 2019 |work=[[CBS Sports]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |date=19 February 2019}}</ref> Dundon later backtracked on his previous claim of a $250 million investment, noting that he had not actually delivered a $250 million [[lump sum]] to the league. Dundon planned on incrementally investing in the league, using $250 million as a theoretical maximum based on if the league were to \"aggressively expand,\" and reserved the right to pull out of the league at any time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/Daily/Morning-Buzz/2019/02/25/Dundon.aspx|title= Tom Dundon Confirms Incremental $250M Investment In AAF|first=Daniel|last=Kaplan|work=Sports Business Journal|date=February 25, 2019|accessdate=February 25, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com:443/en/Daily/Issues/2019/02/22/Leagues%20and%20Governing%20Bodies/AAF.aspx|title=Sources: Dundon Has Committed, Not Yet Invested, Money In AAF|website=www.sportsbusinessdaily.com}}</ref> At the time of the reported April 2 suspension, Dundon had invested an estimated $70 million into the AAF.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.actionnetwork.com/nfl/aaf-suspending-football-operations-darren-rovell|title=Rovell: AAF Suspending Football Operations Immediately|first=Darren|last=Rovell|work=The Action Network|date=April 2, 2019|accessdate=April 2, 2019}}</ref> He had drastically reduced unnecessary expenses and mostly abandoned the technology platform by the end of the league's operations in a desperate attempt to keep the league financially viable.<ref name=leagueonfire/>\n\nEbersol had admitted prior to the start of the season that, on numerous occasions, the AAF had come dangerously close to folding before its first game due to various unstated complications.<ref name=ebersolprofile/> When asked whether some of the AAF's initial investors had dropped out, Ebersol declined to answer.<ref name=whyaafinvestor>{{cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/sports/more-sports/why-aaf-investor-sees-long-lifespan-for-new-football-league/ar-BBTWIKh?li=BBnba9I&srcref=rss|title= Why AAF investor sees long lifespan for new football league |work=USA Today|author=Brent Schrotenboer and Kevin Allen|date=February 22, 2019|accessdate=February 22, 2019}}</ref> After the league suspended operations, it was revealed that one of the league's major investors, former [[Minnesota Vikings]] minority owner [[Reggie Fowler]], had indeed pulled his funding after the inaugural game, necessitating the abrupt sale to Dundon.<ref name=OCRyan/> It came out in late April that Fowler's funds had been frozen by the Department of Justice, after Fowler's indictment on charges of [[money laundering]] for [[cryptocurrency exchanges]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.si.com/nfl/2019/04/30/alliance-american-football-aaf-collapse-charlie-ebersol-tom-dundon|title=The Curious Rise and Spectacular Crash of the Alliance of American Football|work=Sports Illustrated|first=Conor|last=Orr|date=1 May 2019|accessdate=2 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn early March 2019, it was revealed by Bill Polian that the AAF and [[National Football League]] were in informal discussions about a system where players under contract to NFL teams could be loaned to AAF teams. The idea would have been be for NFL teams to assign their third-string quarterback and other players from the bottom half of their roster and practice squads to the AAF to gain more playing time in a similar system to what used to be in place during the existence of [[NFL Europe]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/2019/03/06/aaf-nfl-informal-talks-loaning-younger-players/3085167002/|title=Will NFL teams loan QBs and other players to AAF? Informal talks ongoing|website=USA TODAY|language=en|access-date=2019-03-07}}</ref> This would have in effect made the AAF an official developmental league of the NFL. Dundon sought a change in the NFL's [[collective bargaining agreement]] to protect AAF players who may get injured and miss NFL playing time by ensuring the players still earned a salary from the NFL during their recovery. In late March, Dundon stated that, in reference to the [[National Football League Players Association]] (NFLPA) and its reluctance to cooperate out of concern for injuries, if they are \"not going to give us young players, we can't be a development league\". He added that the AAF was looking at its options, including discontinuing the league if the NFLPA wasn't willing to work with the league.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/2019/03/27/alliance-of-american-football-aaf-tom-dundon-future-nflpa/3287922002/ |title=Majority investor: Alliance of American Football in danger of being discontinued without NFLPA help |first1=Kevin |last1=Allen |first2=Mike |last2=Jones |website=[[USA Today]] |date=March 27, 2019 |accessdate=March 27, 2019}}</ref> [[Profootballtalk.com]] reported shortly thereafter, citing unnamed sources, that if Dundon's demands were not met, he was willing to end his investment before the season ended, possibly as soon as after Week 8, which would cut off the league's cash flow and force it to immediately fold with the playoffs and championship left unplayed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2019/03/27/aaf-may-not-make-it-beyond-this-weekend/|title=AAF may not make it beyond this weekend|first=Mike|last=Florio|work=Profootballtalk.com|date=March 27, 2019|accessdate=March 28, 2019}}</ref> As Week 8 passed, Dundon reiterated his stance on April 1, stating he was still willing to pull his funding before the next week's game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.orlandosentinel.com/sports/open-mike/os-sp-aaf-folding-steve-spurrier-tom-dundon-alliance-of-american-football-20190401-story.html|title=Orlando Apollos coach Steve Spurrier refuses to believe reports AAF could fold this week|first=Mike|last=Bianchi|work=Orlando Sentinel|date=April 1, 2019|accessdate=April 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\nUltimately the AAF lost an estimated $88 million overall, earning only $12 million in revenue against its $100 million expenses.<ref name=\"espnpostmortem\">{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/26957796/inside-short-unhappy-life-alliance-american-football|title=Inside the short, unhappy life of the Alliance of American Football|first=Seth|last=Wickersham|first2=Michael|last2=Rothstein|work=[[ESPN.com]]|date=June 13, 2019|accessdate=June 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Legal matters===\nIn late February 2019, a lawsuit by a venture capitalist in Los Angeles became public, as the AAF issued a statement denying a claim by Robert Vanech that the league was his idea and that he had a handshake agreement with Charlie Ebersol; Vanech is seeking financial damages and 50 percent ownership of the league.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2019/02/25/aaf-disputes-league-was-robert-vanechs-idea/ |title=AAF disputes league was Robert Vanech\u2019s idea |first=Charean |last=Williams |website=[[NBC Sports]] |date=February 25, 2019 |accessdate=February 25, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espn.com/espn/story/_/id/26079108/aaf-being-sued-man-claiming-league-was-idea |title=AAF being sued by man claiming the league was his idea |first=Michael |last=Rothstein |website=[[ESPN]] |date=February 25, 2019 |accessdate=February 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAlso in late February, the league revealed that it had been unable to secure a league-wide [[worker's compensation]] insurance policy prior to the start of the season, forcing the Orlando Apollos to move its practice operations to [[Kingsland, Georgia]], and commute to Orlando for games, as Florida does not consider professional athletes to be eligible for worker's compensation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.orlandosentinel.com/sports/open-mike/os-sp-orlando-apollos-workmans-comp-georgia-practice-20190219-story.html#nt=oft12aH-3gp2|title= Orlando Apollos will start practicing in Georgia because of Florida workers' compensation laws |first=Mike|last=Bianchi|work=Orlando Sentinel|date=February 20, 2019|accessdate=February 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, after the league suspended football operations, two players\u2014punter [[Colton Schmidt]] of the Birmingham Iron and linebacker Reggie Northrup of the Orlando Apollos\u2014filed a [[class action]] lawsuit in California, claiming that they were misled about the financial viability of the league and that the league entered contracts with players in bad faith.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://deadspin.com/lawsuit-claims-the-aaf-intentionally-misled-and-defraud-1833959393 |title=Lawsuit Claims The AAF Intentionally Misled And Defrauded Its Players |first=Gabe |last=Fernandez |website=[[Deadspin]] |date=April 10, 2019 |accessdate=April 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAlso in April, two former front-office league employees filed a class action lawsuit in California, claiming that the league violated the [[Worker Adjustment and Retraining Notification Act of 1988]], which requires large companies to give at least a 60-day advanced notice before large [[layoff]]s.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2019/04/10/former-aaf-employees-allege-defunct-pro-football-league-violated-labor-law/ |title=Former AAF employees allege defunct pro football league violated labor law |first=Nico |last=Savidge |website=[[The Mercury News]] |date=April 10, 2019 |accessdate=April 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\nReggie Fowler was arrested April 30, 2019, on charges related to operating a massive [[cryptocurrency]] scam in 2018, the funds for which were used to fund his AAF investments.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://qz.com/1611214/aaf-football-league-collapse-tied-to-ifinexs-crypto-bank-scandal/|title=How the collapse of a football league is tied to crypto\u2019s biggest banking scandal|first=Matthew|last=DeSilva|date=May 3, 2019|work=Quartz|accessdate=May 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Key people==\n\n\n===Executives===<!-- limit to notable persons, those with their own Wikipedia page -->\n* [[Charlie Ebersol]], co-founder and CEO\n* [[Bill Polian]], co-founder and Head of Football\n* [[John McKay Jr.|J. K. McKay]], Head of Football Operations\n* [[Troy Polamalu]], Head of Player Relations\n* [[Hines Ward]], Head of Football Development\n* [[Tom Veit]], Head of Business Operations\n* [[Mike Pereira]], Officiating Consultant\n* [[Dean Blandino]], Officiating Consultant\n; Player Engagement Board Of Advisors\n* [[Jared Allen]]\n* [[Justin Tuck]]\nSource:<ref>{{cite web |url=https://aaf.com/leadership |title=Leadership |website=aaf.com |accessdate=February 28, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190212011223/https://aaf.com/leadership |archive-date=February 12, 2019 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Board of Directors===\n* [[Thomas Dundon|Tom Dundon]], chairman<ref name=CBS19feb19/>\n* [[Dick Ebersol]]<ref name=\"vty\" /> (ousted midseason)<ref name=leagueonfire/>\n* [[Keith Rabois]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Balakrishnan |first1=Anita |last2=Salinas |first2=Sara |title=Peter Thiel's venture firm is backing a new football league to rival the NFL |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/03/20/peter-thiels-founders-fund-is-backing-alliance-of-american-football.html |website=CNBC |accessdate=September 4, 2018 |date=March 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Media ==\nAs part of its formation, the AAF announced broadcast deals with [[CBS Sports]];<ref name=vty>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2018/digital/news/alliance-american-football-league-cbs-2019-charlie-ebersol-1202731190/|title=New Pro Football League Sets 2019 Debut With CBS Sports Pact|last=Spangler|first=Todd|date=March 20, 2018|work=Variety|access-date=March 21, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> opening day (consisting of two regionally-televised games)<ref name=\"pft\"/> was scheduled for [[CBS]], as well as a playoff semifinal and the championship game.<ref name=vty/><ref>{{cite magazine|last=Feldman|first=Jacob|url=https://www.si.com/tech-media/2019/03/14/cbs-adds-alliance-american-football-games-network-charlie-ebersol-future-league|title=CBS Adds More Alliance of American Football Games to Broadcast Schedule|magazine=[[Sports Illustrated]]|date=March 14, 2019|accessdate=March 14, 2019}}</ref> The telecasts made extensive use of on-field microphones (with head coaches and quarterbacks also miked), and [[Skycam]]s (with two deployed for each game, with one along the sideline, as opposed to having more than one high camera). Half of the games broadcast each week were produced off-site from Sneaky Big Studios in [[Scottsdale, Arizona]]: graphics (which were provided by CBS), Skycam operations, and commentary were performed remotely from the Scottsdale site, as well as studio coverage for all games (via a [[virtual studio]]).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sportsvideo.org/2019/02/08/at-dawn-of-aaf-era-technological-innovation-drives-live-productions/|title=At Dawn of AAF Era, Technological Innovation Drives Live Productions|last=Dachman|first=Jason|website=Sports Video Group|language=en|access-date=2019-02-21}}</ref> Ebersol did not disclose whether or not the league was [[brokered programming|buying the airtime]] or receiving the airtime for free as part of a partnership agreement.<ref name=\"ap20190213\"/> After the season ended, it was confirmed that the AAF had resorted to buying airtime and was unlikely to be able to extract a rights fee from any of its partners for its foreseeable future, a factor in Dundon's decision to withdraw his investment.<ref name=leagueonfire>{{cite web|first=Conor|last=Orr|url=https://www.si.com/nfl/2019/04/30/alliance-american-football-aaf-collapse-charlie-ebersol-tom-dundon|title=League on Fire: The Curious Rise and Spectacular Crash of the Alliance of American Football|work=[[Sports Illustrated]]|date=May 1, 2019|accessdate=May 5, 2019}}</ref> CBS broadcast an ad for the league during its coverage of [[Super Bowl LIII]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.philly.com/sports/nbc-sports-philadelphia-marc-farzetta-amy-fadool-kane-philly-sports-talk-cbs-alliance-american-football-20190123.html|title=NBC Sports Philadelphia\u2019s studio shows will soon look a lot different|last=Tornoe|first=Rob|website=Philly.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-03}}</ref>\n\n[[CBS Sports Network]] aired one game per week, and was scheduled to air one of the playoff games.<ref name=vty/> In addition to local stations,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Steinberg |first1=Leigh |title=AAF: The League That Fills The NFL Offseason Void |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/leighsteinberg/2018/07/26/aaf-the-league-that-fills-the-nfl-offseason-void/ |accessdate=October 24, 2018 |work=Forbes |date=July 26, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> [[TNT (U.S. TV network)|TNT]] was announced as broadcasting two games per season (one regular season and a playoff game which later was expanded to include three regular season games) while [[NFL Network]] aired two weekly games.<ref name=\"Turner, NFL Net\">{{cite web|last=Ourand|first=John|url=https://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/Daily/Morning-Buzz/2019/01/31/AAF.aspx|title=Alliance Of American Football Signs Deals With Turner, NFL Net|publisher=SportsBusiness Daily|date=January 31, 2019|accessdate=January 31, 2019}}</ref> The league's [[mobile app]] offered live streaming of all games except those broadcast on CBS Sports Network, billed as \"AAF Raw\" as most of the AAF live streams contain [[Announcerless game#Legacy|no announcers]] or on-screen graphics, while Turner's [[Bleacher Report|B/R Live]] streamed one game a week.<ref name=\"Turner, NFL Net\" /> Integrated [[Fantasy football (American)|fantasy]] games were available through the AAF site and app as well.<ref name=\"espn\" />\n\nCBSSN's game of the week was called by [[Ben Holden]], [[Adam Archuleta]], and [[John Schriffen]].<ref name=\"pft\">{{cite web|url=https://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2018/12/20/cbs-unveils-aaf-broadcast-teams/|first=Mike|last=Florio|title=CBS unveils AAF broadcast teams|work=Pro Football Talk|date=December 20, 2016|accessdate=December 26, 2018}}</ref> NFL Network's broadcast team for week one consisted of [[Dan Hellie]] on play-by-play and [[Marvin Lewis]] on color commentary.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/NFLMedia/status/1093604994022948864|title=.@nflnetwork's coverage of @TheAAF kicks off Sunday at 8p ET w/ the Salt Lake City Stallions vs. Arizona Hotshots. @DanHellie @MJD & Marvin Lewis are on the call|first=N. F. L.|last=Media|date=February 7, 2019|accessdate=February 12, 2019}}</ref> TNT's broadcast team consisted of [[Brian Anderson (sportscaster)|Brian Anderson]] on play-by-play, Lewis on color commentary, and [[Maurice Jones-Drew]] as sideline reporter. The league did not use set announcer pairings, rotating numerous hosts (several of them from the ''[[NFL on CBS]]'' and the ''[[SEC on CBS]]'') on both play-by-play and color commentary, depending on availability.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://awfulannouncing.com/cbs/marvin-lewis-terrell-davis-and-andrew-siciliano-among-new-names-revealed-for-aaf-broadcasts.html|title=Marvin Lewis, Terrell Davis and Andrew Siciliano among new names revealed for AAF broadcasts|date=2019-02-02|website=Awful Announcing|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-09}}</ref>\n\n[[Sirius XM Radio]], a [[satellite radio]] service, carried a select Game of the Week.<ref name=\"XMRadio\">{{cite web |last1=Alper |first1=Josh |title=SiriusXM will air AAF games |url=https://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2019/02/07/siriusxm-will-air-aaf-games/ |website=NBCsports.com |publisher=NBC Universal |accessdate=6 March 2019}}</ref> Additionally, teams made broadcast deals with local radio affiliates.<ref name=\"SAradio\">{{cite web |title=SAN ANTONIO COMMANDERS ANNOUNCE ESPN SAN ANTONIO 1250 AM/94.5 FM AS OFFICIAL RADIO PARTNER |url=https://www.espnsa.com/san-antonio-commanders-announce-espn-san-antonio-1250-am-94-5-fm-as-official-radio-partner/ |website=ESPN San Antonio |accessdate=6 March 2019 |date=7 January 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"SDradio\">{{cite web |title=XTRA 1360 to be Fleet's flagship station in 2019 |url=https://aaf.com/xtra-1360-to-be-fleets-flagship-station-in-2019 |website=aaf.com |accessdate=6 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190209124238/https://aaf.com/xtra-1360-to-be-fleets-flagship-station-in-2019 |archive-date=February 9, 2019 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"OrlandoRadio\">{{cite web |title=Orlando Apollo's radio deal |url=https://www.bizjournals.com/orlando/news/2018/12/04/orlando-apollos-pro-football-team-snags-radio-deal.html |website=www.bizjournals.com |accessdate=6 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Critics===\nThe AAF received mixed to positive reviews opening night. [[Profootballtalk.com]], in a mostly positive review, praised the league's television product and choice of markets that would embrace the league, singling out the live look-ins at the replay booth during coach's challenges as an innovation that could transfer to the NFL's television broadcasts. The on-field level of play was somewhat less well-received, being compared to [[NFL preseason]] levels, with numerous offensive miscues.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2019/02/10/aaf-off-to-a-solid-start/|first=Michael David|last=Smith|title=AAF off to a solid start|work=Profootballtalk.com|date=February 10, 2019|accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref> [[SB Nation]] had a similar assessment, criticizing the game play as \"much worse than... most of major [[college football]],\" while at the same time noting that the league's innovations were largely successful in making games more interesting.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sbnation.com/2019/2/11/18220196/aaf-rules-games-2019|title=5 things the NFL and college football could learn from the first weekend of the AAF|first=Alex|last=Kirshner|work=SB Nation|date=February 11, 2019|accessdate=February 11, 2019}}</ref> In an admittedly incomplete review, [[Peter King (sportswriter)|Peter King]] stated that although he would not yet draw any \"major conclusions\" about the league, he liked some of the rule changes but feared the overtime process would be a [[gimmick]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2019/02/10/julian-edelman-patriots-mvp-nfl-fmia-peter-king/?cid=pfttease/|title=From his Hollywood Haven, Julian Edelman reflects on LIII MVP, his path and being a perfect Patriot \u00a7 10 Things I Think I Think|work=Football Morning in America|publisher=[[NBC Sports]]|date=February 11, 2019|accessdate=February 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Viewership===\nOvernight [[Nielsen Ratings]] stated that the league-opening regionally televised games on CBS were the highest rated telecast of the night in the [[key demographic]], drawing more viewers than an [[NBA on ABC|NBA game on ABC]] in the same time slot. In overall viewers, both the AAF and NBA lost to a rerun of ''[[America's Got Talent: The Champions]]'' on NBC.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/daily-ratings/tv-ratings-saturday-february-10-2019/|title=TV Ratings Saturday: AAF Football invades the chart, NBA falters|work=TV by the Numbers|date=February 10, 2019|accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref> The NFL Network telecast that week secured 640,000 viewers.<ref name=\"ap20190213\"/> With these comparatively strong initial viewership statistics, the Week 2 ratings were highly anticipated in the interest of developing trended data. In Week 2, the afternoon and evening games on Saturday, February 16, reportedly attracted 1,018,000 and 425,000 viewers, respectively, in addition to the Sunday evening game on February 17 drawing 424,000 viewers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/skedball-weekly-sports-tv-ratings-2-11-2-17-2019.html|title=SKEDBALL: Weekly Sports TV Ratings 2.11-2.17.2019 - Showbuzz Daily|website=www.showbuzzdaily.com}}</ref>  Week 3's NFL Network games drew 491,000 and 515,000 viewers, benefiting in part due to a [[Counterprogramming (television)|counterprogramming]] effort against the [[91st Academy Awards]].<ref>https://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2019/02/27/aaf-ratings-climb-for-week-three-on-nfln/</ref> Week 4's ratings were largely consistent with those of week 2, with the two NFL Network games that week securing ratings of 404,000 and 450,000 viewers, comparable to college basketball and NHL telecasts on the other sports networks.<ref name=awfulannouncing3519/> The disparity between the afternoon and evening games is consistent due to increased competition during primetime hours and the higher market penetration of CBS and TNT compared to NFL Network and CBS Sports Network, the latter of which does not register a rating in the Nielsens.\n\nIn March 2019, building upon these ratings successes, both CBS and TNT added games to their packages; TNT added two additional Saturday afternoon games previously scheduled for B/R Live (which would air special Skycam-only broadcasts of the games as a companion instead), while CBS announced that it would shift two games from CBS Sports Network to broadcast television, including a regular season game on April 6, 2019 (which would have led towards CBS's broadcast of the [[2019 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|2019 NCAA Final Four]]), and one of the conference championship games.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://awfulannouncing.com/cbs/cbs-is-adding-two-more-aaf-games-to-its-broadcast-network-from-cbs-sports-network.html|title=CBS is adding two more AAF games to its broadcast network|date=2019-03-14|website=Awful Announcing|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-14}}</ref><ref name=awfulannouncing3519>{{Cite web|url=https://awfulannouncing.com/turner/tnt-adds-more-aaf-broadcasts-br-live-skycam.html|title=TNT adds March 9 and March 23 AAF games after AAF ratings beat some NHL and MLS broadcasts|date=2019-03-05|website=Awful Announcing|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-06}}</ref> However, due to the suspension of football operations, these games were left unplayed.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite news |url=http://www.sportingnews.com/us/nfl/news/why-is-the-aaf-folding-who-to-blame-alliance-of-american-football/17fmqg4k8rkqp1v6563c4t8kbr |title=Why is the AAF folding? Who to blame for Alliance of American Football's collapse |first=Tadd |last=Haislop |website=[[Sporting News]] |date=April 3, 2019 |accessdate=April 3, 2019}}\n* {{cite news |url=https://www.cbssports.com/aaf/news/aaf-2019-what-went-wrong-and-what-happens-next-following-leagues-sudden-shutdown/ |title=AAF 2019: What went wrong and what happens next following league's sudden shutdown |first=Ben |last=Kercheval |website=[[CBS Sports]] |date=April 3, 2019 |accessdate=April 3, 2019}}\n* {{cite news |url=https://www.si.com/nfl/2019/04/02/alliance-american-football-league-suspension-legal-implications-fallout |title=Chaos and Fallout: The Legal Impact of the AAF's Potential Collapse |first=Michael |last=McCann |website=[[Sports Illustrated]] |date=April 2, 2019 |accessdate=April 4, 2019}}\n* {{cite news |url=https://deadspin.com/the-aafs-sudden-collapse-left-players-high-and-dry-with-1833813021 |title=The AAF's Sudden Collapse Left Players High And Dry With Bills For Housing And Injuries |first=Patrick |last=Redford |website=[[Deadspin]] |date=April 4, 2019 |accessdate=April 4, 2019}}\n* {{cite news |url=https://www.recode.net/2019/4/2/18292598/alliance-for-american-football-silicon-valley-failure |title=It turns out Silicon Valley cannot disrupt the National Football League |first=Theodore |last=Schleifer |website=[[Recode]] |date=April 2, 2019 |accessdate=April 4, 2019}}\n* {{cite news |url=https://www.theringer.com/nfl/2019/4/4/18294528/american-alliance-football-aaf-collapse-suspend-xfl |title=The AAF Failed Because All Minor League Football Does |first=Rodger |last=Sherman |website=[[The Ringer (website)|The Ringer]] |date=April 4, 2019 |accessdate=April 4, 2019}}\n* {{cite news |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/26957796/inside-short-unhappy-life-alliance-american-football |title=Inside the short, unhappy life of the Alliance of American Football |first=Seth Wickersham |last=Michael Rothstein |website=[[ESPN]] |date=June 13, 2019 |accessdate=June 13, 2019}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n\n{{AAF|state=expanded}}\n{{American football in the United States}}\n{{Professional gridiron football leagues in North America}}\n{{CBS Sports}}\n\n[[Category:Alliance of American Football| ]]\n[[Category:2018 establishments in the United States]]\n[[Category:Sports leagues established in 2018]]\n[[Category:American football leagues in the United States]]\n[[Category:Professional sports leagues in the United States]]\n[[Category:Minor and developmental leagues in professional sports]]\n[[Category:Sports leagues disestablished in 2019]]\n[[Category:2019 disestablishments in the United States]]\n[[Category:Companies that have filed for Chapter 7 bankruptcy]]\n", "name_user": "JMyrleFuller", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBusiness:matt mcgloin also turned them down"