ctors from Seattle]]\n[[Category:Male television writers]]\n[[Category:University of Washington College of Arts and Sciences alumni]]\n[[Category:Washington Huskies football players]]\n[[Category:Writers from Seattle]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:University of Washington School of Drama alumni]]\n[[Category:Mercer Island High School alumni]]\n", "name_user": "142.165.85.237", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eEarly life)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joel_McHale"}
{"title_page": "Languages of Afghanistan", "text_new": "{{Languages of\n|country  = [[Afghanistan]]\n|image    = Afghanistan&#039;s Ethnolinguistic Map.png \n|caption  = [[Ethnolinguistics|Ethnolinguistic]] [[Ethnic groups in Afghanistan|groups of Afghanistan]] in 1997\n|official = [[Dari language|Dari]] and [[Pashto language|Pashto]]<ref name=AO/>\n|regional = [[Dari language|Dari]], [[Pashto language|Pashto]], [[Uzbek language|Uzbek]], [[Turkmen language|Turkmen]], [[Balochi language|Balochi]], [[Pashayi languages|Pashayi]]\n|sign     = [[Afghan Sign Language]]\n}}\n[[File:Map of Languages (in Districts) in Afghanistan.jpg|thumb|251x251px|Most spoken language per district (1985)]]\n[[Afghanistan]] is a multilingual country in which two languages \u2013 [[Dari language|Dari]] and [[Pashto language|Pashto]] \u2013 are both [[official language|official]] and most widely spoken.<ref name=AO/>\n\nDari is the official name of the variety of [[Persian language]] spoken in Afghanistan. It is often referred to as the ''Afghan Persian''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sil.org/iso639-3/documentation.asp?id=prs |title=Documentation for ISO 639 identifier: prs |publisher=Sil.org |date=18 January 2010 |accessdate=December 5, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/fields/2098.html?countryName=Afghanistan&countryCode=af&regionCode=sas&#af |title=The World Factbook: Afghanistan |publisher=Cia.gov |accessdate=December 5, 2014}}</ref> Although still widely known as ''Farsi'' ([[Persian language|Persian]]: \u0641\u0627\u0631\u0633\u06cc; \"Persian\") to its native speakers, the name was officially changed to Dari in 1964 by the Afghan government.<ref name=\"Kaboli\">R. Farhadi and J. R. Perry, [http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/kaboli-colloquial-persian Kaboli], [[Encyclopaedia Iranica]], Online Edition, originally in Vol. XV, Fasc. 3, pp. 276\u2013280, 2009.</ref>\n\nAccording to CIA Official Website in 2017 Afghan Persian or Dari (official) ([[Persian language|Dari]]) 27 million (77%) ({{small|[[First language|L1]] + [[Second language|L2]]}}) (functions as the lingua franca), [[Pashto language|Pashto]] 16.8 million (48%) and  Uzbek 11%, English 6%, Turkmen 3%, Urdu 3%, Pashayi 1%, Nuristani 1%, Arabic 1%, Balochi 1% (2017 est). Data represent most widely spoken languages; shares sum to more than 100% because there is much bilingualism in the country and because respondents were allowed to select more than one language. The Turkic languages Uzbek and Turkmen, as well as Balochi, Pashayi, Nuristani, and Pamiri are the third official languages in areas where the majority speaks them.<ref>https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/resources/the-world-factbook/geos/af.html</ref>\n\nBoth Pashto and Dari (Persian) are [[Indo-European languages]] from the [[Iranian languages]] sub-family. Other regional languages, such as [[Uzbek language|Uzbek]], [[Turkmen language|Turkmen]], [[Balochi language|Balochi]], [[Pashayi language|Pashayi]] and [[Nuristani languages|Nuristani]], are spoken by minority groups across the country.\n\nMinor languages include [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]],<ref name=\"WahabYoungerman2007\">{{cite book|last1=Wahab|first1=Shaista|last2=Youngerman|first2=Barry|title=A Brief History of Afghanistan|year=2007|publisher=Infobase Publishing|language=English|isbn=9781438108193|page=18|quote=Afghan Hindus and Sikhs speak Hindi or Punjabi in addition to Pashto and Dari.}}</ref> [[Askunu language|Ashkunu]], [[Kamkata-viri language|Kamkata-viri]], [[Vasi-vari language|Vasi-vari]], [[Tregami language|Tregami]] and [[Kalasha-ala language|Kalasha-ala]], [[Pamir languages|Pamiri]] ([[Shughni language|Shughni]], [[Munji language|Munji]], [[Ishkashimi language|Ishkashimi]] and [[Wakhi language|Wakhi]]), [[Brahui language|Brahui]], [[Arabic language|Arabic]], Qizilbash, Aimaq, and Pashai and [[Kyrgyz language|Kyrgyz]]. Linguist [[Harald Haarmann]] believes that Afghanistan is home to more than 40 minor languages,<ref>[[Harald Haarmann]]: ''Sprachen-Almanach \u2013 Zahlen und Fakten zu allen Sprachen der Welt.'' Campus-Verl., Frankfurt/Main 2002, {{ISBN|3-593-36572-3}}, S.273\u2013274; Afghanistan</ref> with around 200 different dialects.\n\n== Overview ==\n\nThe [[Persian language|Persian]] or [[Dari language]] functions as the nation's [[lingua franca]] and is the native tongue of various Afghanistan's ethnic groups including the [[Tajiks]], [[Hazaras]] and [[Aimaqs]].<ref name=\"Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica\">{{cite web |url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/7798/Afghanistan/226122/Languages |title=Languages of Afghanistan|publisher=[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]]}}</ref> Pashto is the [[First language|native tongue]] of the [[Pashtun people|Pashtuns]], the dominant ethnic group in Afghanistan.<ref>{{cite web |author=|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/hi/english/static/in_depth/world/2001/war_on_terror/key_maps/ethnic_pashtun.stm|title=Ethnic groups|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=7 June 2013|quote=Pashtun: Estimated to be in excess of 45% of the population, the Pashtuns have been the most dominant ethnic group in Afghanistan.}}</ref> Due to Afghanistan's [[Ethnic groups in Afghanistan|multi-ethnic character]], [[multilingualism]] is a common phenomenon.\n\nThe exact figures about the size and composition of the various ethnolinguistic groups are unavailable since no systematic census has been held in Afghanistan in decades.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/south_asia/3717092.stm|title=Afghan poll's ethnic battleground|first=Pam|last=O'toole|publisher=[[BBC News]]|date=October 6, 2004|accessdate=2010-09-16}}</ref> The table below displays the major languages spoken in Afghanistan per sample statistics:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Spoken Languages in Afghanistan based on samples in <ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"Afghan2006\" /><ref name=\"Afghan2018\" />\n|-\n! Language !! 2006 (as L1)<br>(out of 6,226)<ref name=\"Afghan2006\">The Asia Foundation. [https://asiafoundation.org/resources/pdfs/AGsurvey06.pdf ''Afghanistan in 2006: A Survey of the Afghan People''.]</ref>!! 2006 (as L2)<br>(out of 6,226)<ref name=\"Afghan2006\" /> !! 2013<br>(out of 9,260)<ref name=\":0\">The Asia Foundation. [https://asiafoundation.org/resources/pdfs/2013AfghanSurvey.pdf ''Afghanistan in 2013: A Survey of the Afghan People''.]</ref>!! 2018<br>(out of 13,943)<ref name=\"Afghan2018\">The Asia Foundation. [https://asiafoundation.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/2018_Afghan-Survey_fullReport-12.4.18.pdf ''Afghanistan in 2018: A Survey of the Afghan People''.]</ref>\n\n|-\n| [[Pashto]] || 38% || 6% || 35% || 41%\n|-\n| [[Dari language|Dari]] || 52% || 26% || 48% || 51%\n|-\n| [[Uzbek language|Uzbek]] || 7% || 2% || 9% || 8%\n|-\n| [[Turkmen language|Turkmen]] || 2% || 3% || 3% || 3%\n|-\n| [[Balochi language|Balochi]] || 0% || 0% || 1% || 1%\n|-\n| [[Pashayi languages|Pashayi]] || 0% || 1% || 1% || 1%\n|-\n| [[Nuristani languages|Nuristani]] || N/A || N/A || 1% || 1%\n|-\n| [[Arabic]] || 0% || 2% || 1% || 1%\n|-\n| [[English language|English]] || 0% || 8% || 5% || 6%\n|-\n| [[Urdu]] || 0% || 7% || 2% || 3%\n|}\n\nA sizeable population in Afghanistan, especially in [[Kabul]], can also speak and understand [[Hindustani language|Hindustani]] due to the popularity and influence of [[Bollywood]] films and songs in the region.<ref name=\"Hakala2012\">{{cite web|url=http://media.nationalgeographic.org/assets/file/asia_8.pdf|title=Languages as a Key to Understanding Afghanistan's Cultures|last=Hakala|first=Walter N.|year=2012|publisher=[[National Geographic]]|language=English|accessdate=13 March 2018|quote=In the 1980s and '90s, at least three million Afghans--mostly Pashtun--fled to Pakistan, where a substantial number spent several years being exposed to Hindi- and Urdu-language media, especially Bollywood films and songs, and beng educated in Urdu-language schools, both of which contributed to the decline of Dari, even among urban Pashtuns.}}</ref><ref name=\"Krishnamurthy2013\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gatewayhouse.in/kabul-diary-discovering-the-indian-connection/|title=Kabul Diary: Discovering the Indian connection|last=Krishnamurthy|first=Rajeshwari|date=28 June 2013|publisher=Gateway House: Indian Council on Global Relations|language=English|accessdate=13 March 2018|quote=Most Afghans in Kabul understand and/or speak Hindi, thanks to the popularity of Indian cinema in the country.}}</ref>\n\n== Language policy ==\nThe official languages of the country are Dari and Pashto, as established by the [[1964 Constitution of Afghanistan]]. Dari is the most widely spoken language of Afghanistan's [[official language]]s and acts as a [[lingua franca]] for the country. In 1980, other [[regional language]]s were granted official status in the regions where they are the language of the majority.<ref name=\"Iranica-Afghanistan-lang\">{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/afghanistan-v-languages|title=AFGHANISTAN v. Languages|quote=''A. Official languages. Pa\u1e67t\u014d (1) is the native tongue of 50 to 55 percent of Afghans... Persian (2) is the language most spoken in Afghanistan. The native tongue of twenty five percent of the population, it is split into numerous dialects.''|publisher=Encyclop\u00e6dia Iranica|work=Ch. M. Kieffer|accessdate=2012-04-08}}</ref> This policy was codified in the 2004 [[Constitution of Afghanistan|Afghan Constitution]], which established Uzbek, Turkmen, Balochi, Pashayi, Nuristani and Pamiri as a third official language in areas where they are spoken by a majority of the population.<ref name=\"AO\">{{cite web|title=What Languages are Spoken in Afghanistan?|url=http://alphaomegatranslations.com/2015/09/21/what-languages-are-spoken-in-afghanistan/#preamble |quote=Pashto and Dari are the official languages of the state. are \u2013 in addition to Pashto and Dari \u2013 the third official language in areas where the majority speaks them|year=2004 |accessdate=June 13, 2012}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{portal|Afghanistan}}\n* [[Demographics of Afghanistan]]\n* [[Ethnic groups in Afghanistan]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=tdEyAQAAQBAJ Language Policy and Language Conflict in Afghanistan and Its Neighbors: The Changing Politics of Language Choice]\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100622160229/http://gulf2000.columbia.edu/images/maps/Afghanistan_Languages_lg.jpg Distribution of languages map from Columbia University]\n* [http://www.muturzikin.com/cartesasie/4.htm Linguistic map of Afghanistan]\n\n{{Languages of Afghanistan}}\n{{Asia in topic|Languages of}}\n{{Languages of South Asia}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Languages Of Afghanistan}}\n[[Category:Languages of Afghanistan| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Languages of\n|country  = [[Afghanistan]]\n|image    = Afghanistan&#039;s Ethnolinguistic Map.png \n|caption  = [[Ethnolinguistics|Ethnolinguistic]] [[Ethnic groups in Afghanistan|groups of Afghanistan]] in 1997\n|official = [[Dari language|Dari]] and [[Pashto language|Pashto]]<ref name=AO/>\n|regional = [[Dari language|Dari]], [[Pashto language|Pashto]], [[Uzbek language|Uzbek]], [[Turkmen language|Turkmen]], [[Balochi language|Balochi]], [[Pashayi languages|Pashayi]]\n|sign     = [[Afghan Sign Language]]\n}}\n[[File:Map of Languages (in Districts) in Afghanistan.jpg|thumb|251x251px|Most spoken language per district (1985)]]\n[[Afghanistan]] is a multilingual country in which two languages \u2013 [[Dari language|Dari]] and [[Pashto language|Pashto]] \u2013 are both [[official language|official]] and most widely spoken.<ref name=AO/>\n\nDari is the official name of the variety of [[Persian language]] spoken in Afghanistan. It is often referred to as the ''Afghan Persian''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sil.org/iso639-3/documentation.asp?id=prs |title=Documentation for ISO 639 identifier: prs |publisher=Sil.org |date=18 January 2010 |accessdate=December 5, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/fields/2098.html?countryName=Afghanistan&countryCode=af&regionCode=sas&#af |title=The World Factbook: Afghanistan |publisher=Cia.gov |accessdate=December 5, 2014}}</ref> Although still widely known as ''Farsi'' ([[Persian language|Persian]]: \u0641\u0627\u0631\u0633\u06cc; \"Persian\") to its native speakers, the name was officially changed to Dari in 1964 by the Afghan government.<ref name=\"Kaboli\">R. Farhadi and J. R. Perry, [http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/kaboli-colloquial-persian Kaboli], [[Encyclopaedia Iranica]], Online Edition, originally in Vol. XV, Fasc. 3, pp. 276\u2013280, 2009.</ref>\n\nAccording to CIA Official Website in 2017 Afghan Persian or Dari (official) ([[Persian language|Dari]]) 27 million (77%) ({{small|[[First language|L1]] + [[Second language|L2]]}}) (functions as the lingua franca), [[Pashto language|Pashto]] 16.8 million (48%) and  Uzbek 11%, English 6%, Turkmen 3%, Urdu 3%, Pashayi 1%, Nuristani 1%, Arabic 1%, Balochi 1% (2017 est). Data represent most widely spoken languages; shares sum to more than 100% because there is much bilingualism in the country and because respondents were allowed to select more than one language. The Turkic languages Uzbek and Turkmen, as well as Balochi, Pashayi, Nuristani, and Pamiri are the third official languages in areas where the majority speaks them.<ref>https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/resources/the-world-factbook/geos/af.html</ref>\n\nBoth Pashto and Dari (Persian) are [[Indo-European languages]] from the [[Iranian languages]] sub-family. Other regional languages, such as [[Uzbek language|Uzbek]], [[Turkmen language|Turkmen]], [[Balochi language|Balochi]], [[Pashayi language|Pashayi]] and [[Nuristani languages|Nuristani]], are spoken by minority groups across the country.\n\nMinor languages include [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]],<ref name=\"WahabYoungerman2007\">{{cite book|last1=Wahab|first1=Shaista|last2=Youngerman|first2=Barry|title=A Brief History of Afghanistan|year=2007|publisher=Infobase Publishing|language=English|isbn=9781438108193|page=18|quote=Afghan Hindus and Sikhs speak Hindi or Punjabi in addition to Pashto and Dari.}}</ref> [[Askunu language|Ashkunu]], [[Kamkata-viri language|Kamkata-viri]], [[Vasi-vari language|Vasi-vari]], [[Tregami language|Tregami]] and [[Kalasha-ala language|Kalasha-ala]], [[Pamir languages|Pamiri]] ([[Shughni language|Shughni]], [[Munji language|Munji]], [[Ishkashimi language|Ishkashimi]] and [[Wakhi language|Wakhi]]), [[Brahui language|Brahui]], [[Arabic language|Arabic]], Qizilbash, Aimaq, and Pashai and [[Kyrgyz language|Kyrgyz]]. Linguist [[Harald Haarmann]] believes that Afghanistan is home to more than 40 minor languages,<ref>[[Harald Haarmann]]: ''Sprachen-Almanach \u2013 Zahlen und Fakten zu allen Sprachen der Welt.'' Campus-Verl., Frankfurt/Main 2002, {{ISBN|3-593-36572-3}}, S.273\u2013274; Afghanistan</ref> with around 200 different dialects.\n\n== Overview ==\n\nThe [[Persian language|Persian]] or [[Dari language]] functions as the nation's [[lingua franca]] and is the native tongue of various Afghanistan's ethnic groups including the [[Tajiks]], [[Hazaras]] and [[Aimaqs]].<ref name=\"Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica\">{{cite web |url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/7798/Afghanistan/226122/Languages |title=Languages of Afghanistan|publisher=[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]]}}</ref> Pashto is the [[First language|native tongue]] of the [[Pashtun people|Pashtuns]], the dominant ethnic group in Afghanistan.<ref>{{cite web |author=|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/hi/english/static/in_depth/world/2001/war_on_terror/key_maps/ethnic_pashtun.stm|title=Ethnic groups|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=7 June 2013|quote=Pashtun: Estimated to be in excess of 45% of the population, the Pashtuns have been the most dominant ethnic group in Afghanistan.}}</ref> Due to Afghanistan's [[Ethnic groups in Afghanistan|multi-ethnic character]], [[multilingualism]] is a common phenomenon.\n\nThe exact figures about the size and composition of the various ethnolinguistic groups are unavailable since no systematic census has been held in Afghanistan in decades.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/south_asia/3717092.stm|title=Afghan poll's ethnic battleground|first=Pam|last=O'toole|publisher=[[BBC News]]|date=October 6, 2004|accessdate=2010-09-16}}</ref> The table below displays the major languages spoken in Afghanistan per sample statistics:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Spoken Languages in Afghanistan\n|-\n! Language !! 2006 (as L1)<br>(out of 6,226)<ref name=\"Afghan2006\">The Asia Foundation. [https://asiafoundation.org/resources/pdfs/AGsurvey06.pdf ''Afghanistan in 2006: A Survey of the Afghan People''.]</ref>!! 2006 (as L2)<br>(out of 6,226)<ref name=\"Afghan2006\" /> !! 2013<br>(out of 9,260)<ref>The Asia Foundation. [https://asiafoundation.org/resources/pdfs/2013AfghanSurvey.pdf ''Afghanistan in 2013: A Survey of the Afghan People''.]</ref>!! 2018<br>(out of 13,943)<ref name=\"Afghan2018\">The Asia Foundation. [https://asiafoundation.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/2018_Afghan-Survey_fullReport-12.4.18.pdf ''Afghanistan in 2018: A Survey of the Afghan People''.]</ref>\n\n|-\n| [[Pashto]] || 38% || 6% || 35% || 41%\n|-\n| [[Dari language|Dari]] || 52% || 26% || 48% || 51%\n|-\n| [[Uzbek language|Uzbek]] || 7% || 2% || 9% || 8%\n|-\n| [[Turkmen language|Turkmen]] || 2% || 3% || 3% || 3%\n|-\n| [[Balochi language|Balochi]] || 0% || 0% || 1% || 1%\n|-\n| [[Pashayi languages|Pashayi]] || 0% || 1% || 1% || 1%\n|-\n| [[Nuristani languages|Nuristani]] || N/A || N/A || 1% || 1%\n|-\n| [[Arabic]] || 0% || 2% || 1% || 1%\n|-\n| [[English language|English]] || 0% || 8% || 5% || 6%\n|-\n| [[Urdu]] || 0% || 7% || 2% || 3%\n|}\n\nA sizeable population in Afghanistan, especially in [[Kabul]], can also speak and understand [[Hindustani language|Hindustani]] due to the popularity and influence of [[Bollywood]] films and songs in the region.<ref name=\"Hakala2012\">{{cite web|url=http://media.nationalgeographic.org/assets/file/asia_8.pdf|title=Languages as a Key to Understanding Afghanistan's Cultures|last=Hakala|first=Walter N.|year=2012|publisher=[[National Geographic]]|language=English|accessdate=13 March 2018|quote=In the 1980s and '90s, at least three million Afghans--mostly Pashtun--fled to Pakistan, where a substantial number spent several years being exposed to Hindi- and Urdu-language media, especially Bollywood films and songs, and beng educated in Urdu-language schools, both of which contributed to the decline of Dari, even among urban Pashtuns.}}</ref><ref name=\"Krishnamurthy2013\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gatewayhouse.in/kabul-diary-discovering-the-indian-connection/|title=Kabul Diary: Discovering the Indian connection|last=Krishnamurthy|first=Rajeshwari|date=28 June 2013|publisher=Gateway House: Indian Council on Global Relations|language=English|accessdate=13 March 2018|quote=Most Afghans in Kabul understand and/or speak Hindi, thanks to the popularity of Indian cinema in the country.}}</ref>\n\n== Language policy ==\nThe official languages of the country are Dari and Pashto, as established by the [[1964 Constitution of Afghanistan]]. Dari is the most widely spoken language of Afghanistan's [[official language]]s and acts as a [[lingua franca]] for the country. In 1980, other [[regional language]]s were granted official status in the regions where they are the language of the majority.<ref name=\"Iranica-Afghanistan-lang\">{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/afghanistan-v-languages|title=AFGHANISTAN v. Languages|quote=''A. Official languages. Pa\u1e67t\u014d (1) is the native tongue of 50 to 55 percent of Afghans... Persian (2) is the language most spoken in Afghanistan. The native tongue of twenty five percent of the population, it is split into numerous dialects.''|publisher=Encyclop\u00e6dia Iranica|work=Ch. M. Kieffer|accessdate=2012-04-08}}</ref> This policy was codified in the 2004 [[Constitution of Afghanistan|Afghan Constitution]], which established Uzbek, Turkmen, Balochi, Pashayi, Nuristani and Pamiri as a third official language in areas where they are spoken by a majority of the population.<ref name=\"AO\">{{cite web|title=What Languages are Spoken in Afghanistan?|url=http://alphaomegatranslations.com/2015/09/21/what-languages-are-spoken-in-afghanistan/#preamble |quote=Pashto and Dari are the official languages of the state. are \u2013 in addition to Pashto and Dari \u2013 the third official language in areas where the majority speaks them|year=2004 |accessdate=June 13, 2012}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{portal|Afghanistan}}\n* [[Demographics of Afghanistan]]\n* [[Ethnic groups in Afghanistan]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=tdEyAQAAQBAJ Language Policy and Language Conflict in Afghanistan and Its Neighbors: The Changing Politics of Language Choice]\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100622160229/http://gulf2000.columbia.edu/images/maps/Afghanistan_Languages_lg.jpg Distribution of languages map from Columbia University]\n* [http://www.muturzikin.com/cartesasie/4.htm Linguistic map of Afghanistan]\n\n{{Languages of Afghanistan}}\n{{Asia in topic|Languages of}}\n{{Languages of South Asia}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Languages Of Afghanistan}}\n[[Category:Languages of Afghanistan| ]]\n", "name_user": "Sulaimankhail1", "label": "safe", "comment": "The label was misleading", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Languages_of_Afghanistan"}
